{"title_page": "Bingham McCutchen", "text_new": "{{Infobox law firm\n| name            = Bingham McCutchen LLP\n| logo            = [[File:Bingham logo.png|frameless]]\n| headquarters    = [[One Federal Street]]<br/>[[Boston, Massachusetts]]\n| num_offices     = 14\n| num_attorneys   = approximately 700\n| num_employees   = approximately 1,600\n| practice_areas  = Financial restructuring, securities, litigation, antitrust, private equity, corporate finance, government affairs\n| key_people      = Jay S. Zimmerman (Chairman)<ref name=\"hoovers-overview\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hoovers.com/bingham-mccutchen/--ID__54412--/free-co-factsheet.xhtml |title=Bingham McCutchen - Company Overview - Hoover's |publisher=[[Hoover's|Hoover's, Inc]]}}</ref>\n| revenue         = \n| date_founded    = 1891<ref name=\"hoovers-desc\"/>\n| founder         = \n| company_type    = [[Limited Liability Partnership]]\n| slogan          = Legal insight. Business instinct.\n| homepage        = [http://www.bingham.com Bingham.com]\n| dissolved       = 2014\n}}\n'''Bingham McCutchen LLP''' was a global law firm with approximately 850 [[Lawyer|attorneys]] in nine US offices and five international offices.<ref name=\"offices\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bingham.com/LocationMain.aspx |title=Bingham McCutchen {{!}} Offices |accessdate=2008-01-16 |publisher=Bingham web site |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080113183032/http://www.bingham.com/LocationMain.aspx |archive-date=2008-01-13 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It ceased operations in late 2014, when several hundred of its partners and associate lawyers left the firm to join Philadelphia-based [[Morgan, Lewis & Bockius|Morgan Lewis]].<ref name=MorganLewis>{{cite web|url=http://abovethelaw.com/2014/11/more-fallout-from-the-morgan-lewis-bingham-mccutchen-deal/|title=More Info About The Morgan Lewis / Bingham McCutchen Deal|publisher=abovethelaw.com|accessdate=6 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n'''Bingham, Dana & Gould''' was founded in Boston in 1891.<ref name=\"globe1022\">{{cite news|last1=Fernandes|first1=Deirdre|title=Once-booming Boston law firm struggles to survive|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/business/2014/10/21/future-uncertain-for-one-city-largest-law-firms/OghtwclNVe1PoDnuAuPfEM/story.html|accessdate=9 September 2015|work=The Boston Globe|date=22 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1997, the company experienced sharp growth in the number of attorneys, offices, and revenues by absorbing other law firms.<ref name=\"hoovers-desc\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hoovers.com/bingham-mccutchen/--ID__54412--/free-co-profile.xhtml |title=Bingham McCutchen - Company Description - Hoover's |publisher=[[Hoover's|Hoover's, Inc]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bingham.com/Page.aspx?PageID=4 |title=Charting Our Growth |accessdate=2008-01-16 |publisher=Bingham web site |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080209142711/http://www.bingham.com/Page.aspx?PageID=4 |archive-date=2008-02-09 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 1997, Bingham Dana acquired the 30-lawyer Japanese practice group of Marks & Murase, giving the firm offices in New York and Los Angeles and a strong base of Japanese institutional clients.<ref>{{cite news|title=Leading Japanese Practice Group Joins Bingham, Dana & Gould|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Leading+Japanese+Practice+Group+Joins+Bingham,+Dana+%26+Gould.-a019815612|accessdate=9 September 2015|agency=Business Wire|date=1 October 1997}}</ref> The next outpost was established in [[Hartford, Connecticut|Hartford]] through a merger with 55-lawyer Hebb & Gitlin, a firm that concentrated on international [[bankruptcy]] work. In 2001, Bingham Dana bulked up in New York City through a merger with Richards & O'Neill, a boutique law firm of 55 attorneys known for its [[litigation]] and corporate groups. The next year, in 2002, Bingham Dana merged with [[San Francisco]]-based law firm [[McCutchen, Doyle, Brown & Enersen]] to form 800-lawyer Bingham McCutchen. McCutchen Doyle brought five offices and a litigation and [[intellectual property]] focus. In 2003, the firm expanded in [[Southern California]] by merging with corporate boutique Riordan & McKinzie. 2006 saw a merger between Bingham McCutchen and [[Swidler Berlin Shereff Friedman]], a [[Washington, D.C.]]-based firm which brought greater capabilities in the nation's capital as well as a regulatory group. Bingham also launched in [[Hong Kong]] that same year. In 2007, the firm acquired Los Angeles litigation shop Alschuler Grossman. In July 2009, Bingham McCutchen acquired [[McKee Nelson]], a midsize law firm specializing in [[tax law]] and [[structured finance]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.law.com/jsp/nlj/PubArticleNLJ.jsp?id=1202432014189&Bingham_McCutchen_Acquires_McKee_Nelson&slreturn=1|title=Bingham McCutchen acquires McKee Nelson|last=Beck|first=Susan|date=2009-06-09|work=[[The American Lawyer]]|publisher=[[Incisive Media]]|accessdate=2009-07-07}}</ref>\n\nA team of Bingham attorneys and staff, led by [[Susan Baker Manning]] and [[Sabin Willett]], represented pro bono a dozen [[Uighur people|Uighur]] men held in [[extrajudicial detention]] in the United States [[Guantanamo Bay detention camp]]s, in Cuba.<ref name=NYtimes20070912>\n{{cite news\n| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/09/12/washington/12gitmo.html?ref=todayspaper\n| work=[[The New York Times]]\n| author=[[William Glaberson]]\n| title=Officials Cite Danger in Revealing Detainee Data\n| date= September 12, 2007\n| accessdate=2007-09-12\n| page=A18\n}}</ref><ref name=WashingtonPost20051224>\n{{cite news\n| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/12/23/AR2005122301503.html\n| title=Detainees Face Limited Access to Courts: But Bill Awaiting Bush Signature Would Shield Terror Suspects from U.S. Abuse\n| page=A04\n| work=[[The Washington Post]]\n| author=Josh White\n| date= December 24, 2005\n| accessdate=2008-01-05\n| authorlink= Josh White (journalist)\n}}</ref><ref name=Iht20060927>\n{{cite news\n| url=http://www.iht.com/articles/2006/09/27/opinion/edwillett.php\n| title=The Innocent Man at Guantanamo\n| publisher=[[International Herald Tribune]]\n| author=[[Sabin Willett]]\n| date= September 27, 2006\n| accessdate=2008-01-19\n}}</ref><ref name=Wapo20051114>\n{{cite news\n| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/11/13/AR2005111301061.html\n| title=Detainees Deserve Court Trials\n| pages=A21\n| work=[[The Washington Post]]\n| author=P. Sabin Willett\n| date= November 14, 2005\n| accessdate=2008-01-19\n| authorlink= Sabin Willett\n}}</ref><ref name=BostonGlobe20071203>\n{{cite news\n| url=http://www.boston.com/bostonglobe/editorial_opinion/oped/articles/2007/12/03/i_will_never_leave_guantanamo/\n| title=I will never leave Guantanamo\n| page=\n| pages=\n| publisher=[[Boston Globe]]\n| author=[[Sabin Willett]]\n| date=December 3, 2007\n| accessdate=2008-01-19\n}}</ref>\nBingham litigated a number of habeas corpus cases on behalf of the Uighur clients, as well as cases under the Detainee Treatment Act of 2005 that brought to light evidentiary and procedural flaws in the 2004-05 [[Combatant Status Review Tribunal]]s that were used to justify the Uighurs' ongoing imprisonment. All Bingham clients were subsequently released.\n\nThe Tokyo office of Bingham McCutchen became one of the largest law firms in Japan by its 2007 merger with a domestic law firm headed by Hideyuki Sakai, an insolvency specialist. Unlike most foreign firms in Japan which have minimal domestic practices, Bingham's Tokyo office was predominantly staffed by Japanese attorneys and handled domestic matters such as the restructuring of [[Olympus Corporation]], though it hired a number of foreign attorneys since 2012 in an attempt to strengthen its outbound and cross-border practice and to expand in other legal fields such as intellectual property and investment funds.<ref>{{cite news|last=Brennan|first=Tom|title=Bingham Aims for Top of Tokyo Pack|url=http://www.americanlawyer.com/PubArticleAL.jsp?id=1202618529194&thepage=1|accessdate=10 September 2013|newspaper=The Asian Lawyer|date=9 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nDespite a deep recession which hurt law firms nationwide, the Boston Globe reported that Bingham performed very well financially.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.boston.com/business/articles/2010/02/05/profits_soar_for_boston_law_partners/ | work=The Boston Globe | title=Profits soar for law partners | first=Kit | last=Chellel | date=2010-02-05}}</ref>  In 2009, Bingham's gross revenues increased 12% and profits per partner increased 2%.  Chairman Jay Zimmerman was quoted as saying \"We\u2019ve had our best year ever.\" However, despite an increase in revenues, Bingham froze salaries, and in March 2009 laid off 16 attorneys and 29 support staff.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://abovethelaw.com/2009/03/nationwide_layoff_watch_bingha_1.php |title=Nationwide Layoff Watch: Bingham McCutchen Cuts 39 Overall |author=Elie Mystal |date=5 March 2009 |accessdate=28 October 2010 }}{{dead link|date=July 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n===Collapse===\n\nBingham experienced internal tensions following the 2002 McCutchen merger, and again following the 2009 McKee merger. Both transactions were viewed as \"mergers of equals\" among some insiders, and as unequal acquisitions among others. The McKee transaction involved large compensation guarantees to several key McKee partners which were not immediately disclosed to other Bingham partners. The legacy McKee partners continued to earn relatively high compensation following the acquisition due to the fact that they charged higher hourly rates than the legacy Bingham partners; the legacy Bingham partners nonetheless demanded salary matching, which strained the profits of the firm.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.law360.com/in-depth/articles/820381|title=Why Law Firm Mergers Fail - Law360|website=www.law360.com|access-date=2016-07-26}}</ref>\n\nBingham experienced a massive downsizing from 2012 to 2014, during which time it cut 225 lawyers and saw more than 50 partners leave the firm. Two major cases&mdash;the ''[[Deepwater Horizon]]'' litigation and an IP dispute involving [[Oracle Corporation]]&mdash;ended abruptly, reducing the firm's revenue.<ref name=\"globe1022\" /> Bingham attempted to cut costs by moving back office functions to a new center in Kentucky, but the initial cost of the move ($100,000 per equity partner) hurt the firm's 2014 financial results even further.<ref name=\"bna\">{{cite news|title=In Wake of Bingham, Lawyers Contemplate Services Centers|url=https://bol.bna.com/in-wake-of-bingham-lawyers-contemplate-services-centers/|accessdate=9 September 2015|work=Bloomberg BNA|date=18 June 2015}}</ref> After Bingham's collapse, it was revealed that [[Massachusetts Mutual Life Insurance]] stopped working with Bingham due to the low level of racial diversity among its partners in Boston and Hartford.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ryan|first1=Greg|title=Morgan Lewis inherited diversity problem that cost Bingham a big client|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/boston/news/2015/07/31/morgan-lewis-inherited-diversity-problem-that-cost.html|accessdate=9 September 2015|work=Boston Business Journal|date=31 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2014, 227 of around 300 partners and a similar number of associates joined the Philadelphia-based firm of [[Morgan Lewis & Bockius]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://abovethelaw.com/2014/11/bingham-to-go-bust-in-wake-of-morgan-lewis-raid/ |title=Bingham To Go Bust In Wake Of Morgan Lewis Raid |author=David Lat |date=17 November 2014 |accessdate=17 November 2014}}</ref> Morgan Lewis paid off Bingham's debt as part of the deal,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Passarella|first1=Gina|title=Morgan Lewis finalizes deal with Bingham McCutchen, adds 510 lawyers|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/business/legal/2014/12/02/Morgan-Lewis-finalizes-deal-with-Bingham-McCutchen-adds-510-lawyers/stories/201412020007|accessdate=9 September 2015|work=The Legal Intelligencer|date=2 December 2014}}</ref> and shut down Bingham's Kentucky operations center, relocating some employees to Philadelphia.<ref name=\"bna\" />\n\nBingham's London and Frankfurt offices joined [[Akin Gump Strauss Hauer & Feld]].<ref>{{cite web|title=London and Frankfurt Offices of Bingham McCutchen to Join Akin Gump|url=https://www.akingump.com/en/news-insights/london-and-frankfurt-offices-of-bingham-mccutchen-to-join-akin.html|publisher=Akin Gump|accessdate=9 September 2015}}</ref> 50 of Bingham's 60 lawyers in Tokyo moved to the Japanese law firm of [[Anderson Mori & Tomotsune]], with the remainder joining Morgan Lewis.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Verghese|first1=Kanishk|title=Anderson Mori swoops in for 50 Bingham lawyers in Tokyo|url=http://www.legalbusinessonline.com/appointments/anderson-mori-swoops-50-bingham-lawyers-tokyo/68579|accessdate=9 September 2015|work=Asian Legal Business|date=16 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Offices==\n\nAs of 2014, Bingham McCutchen had offices in [[Beijing]], [[Boston, Massachusetts|Boston]], [[Hartford, Connecticut|Hartford]], [[Hong Kong]], [[Lexington, Kentucky|Lexington]], [[London]], [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]], [[New York City|New York]], [[Orange County, California|Orange County]], [[San Francisco, California|San Francisco]], [[Santa Monica, California]], [[Silicon Valley]], [[Tokyo]], and [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref name=\"offices\"/> It also offered consulting services through subsidiaries Bingham Consulting and Bingham Strategic Advisors.<ref name=\"hoovers-desc\"/>\n\n==Notable people==\n*[[Denise Jefferson Casper]] (judge, [[United States District Court for the District of Massachusetts]])\n*[[Christopher Cox]] (former Chairman, [[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]], and former [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]])\n*[[Barry Goode]] (retired from the firm in 2001 to join state government, and now is a Contra Costa County judge)\n*[[Thurgood Marshall, Jr.]] (former [[Bill Clinton|Clinton]] [[White House]] [[Executive Office of the President|Cabinet Secretary]])\n*[[Steve Merrill]] (former [[Governor of New Hampshire]]) \n*[[Richard Riordan]] (former [[Mayor of Los Angeles, California|Mayor of Los Angeles]])\n*[[Josiah Spaulding]]\n*[[Sabin Willett]]\n*[[Pete Wilson]] (former [[Governor of California]] and former [[United States Senate|U.S. Senator]])\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080129132048/http://www.bingham.com/ Bingham.com Official Website]\n* [http://www.natlawreview.com/organization/bingham-mccutchen-llp Bingham McCutchen National Law Review Profile]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150613140734/http://www.binghammccutchen.biz/bingham-mccutchen/ Bingham McCutchen]\n{{Defunct law firms of the United States}}\n\n[[Category:Law firms established in 1891]]\n[[Category:Defunct law firms of the United States]]\n[[Category:1891 establishments in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Law firms disestablished in 2014]]\n[[Category:2014 disestablishments in Massachusetts]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox law firm\n| name            = Bingham McCutchen LLP\n| logo            = [[File:Bingham logo.png|frameless]]\n| headquarters    = [[One Federal Street]]<br>[[Boston, Massachusetts]]\n| num_offices     = 14\n| num_attorneys   = approximately 700\n| num_employees   = approximately 1,600\n| practice_areas  = Financial restructuring, securities, litigation, antitrust, private equity, corporate finance, government affairs\n| key_people      = Jay S. Zimmerman (Chairman)<ref name=\"hoovers-overview\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hoovers.com/bingham-mccutchen/--ID__54412--/free-co-factsheet.xhtml |title=Bingham McCutchen - Company Overview - Hoover's |publisher=[[Hoover's|Hoover's, Inc]]}}</ref>\n| revenue         = \n| date_founded    = 1891<ref name=\"hoovers-desc\"/>\n| founder         = \n| company_type    = [[Limited Liability Partnership]]\n| slogan          = Legal insight. Business instinct.\n| homepage        = [http://www.bingham.com Bingham.com]\n| dissolved       = 2014\n}}\n'''Bingham McCutchen''' LLP was a global law firm with approximately 850 [[Lawyer|attorneys]] in nine US offices and five international offices.<ref name=\"offices\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bingham.com/LocationMain.aspx |title=Bingham McCutchen {{!}} Offices |accessdate=2008-01-16 |publisher=Bingham web site |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080113183032/http://www.bingham.com/LocationMain.aspx |archive-date=2008-01-13 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It ceased operations in late 2014, when several hundred of its partners and associate lawyers left the firm to join Philadelphia-based [[Morgan, Lewis & Bockius|Morgan Lewis]].<ref name=MorganLewis>{{cite web|url=http://abovethelaw.com/2014/11/more-fallout-from-the-morgan-lewis-bingham-mccutchen-deal/|title=More Info About The Morgan Lewis / Bingham McCutchen Deal|publisher=abovethelaw.com|accessdate=6 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n'''Bingham, Dana & Gould''' was founded in Boston in 1891.<ref name=\"globe1022\">{{cite news|last1=Fernandes|first1=Deirdre|title=Once-booming Boston law firm struggles to survive|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/business/2014/10/21/future-uncertain-for-one-city-largest-law-firms/OghtwclNVe1PoDnuAuPfEM/story.html|accessdate=9 September 2015|work=The Boston Globe|date=22 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1997, the company experienced sharp growth in the number of attorneys, offices, and revenues by absorbing other law firms.<ref name=\"hoovers-desc\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hoovers.com/bingham-mccutchen/--ID__54412--/free-co-profile.xhtml |title=Bingham McCutchen - Company Description - Hoover's |publisher=[[Hoover's|Hoover's, Inc]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bingham.com/Page.aspx?PageID=4 |title=Charting Our Growth |accessdate=2008-01-16 |publisher=Bingham web site |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080209142711/http://www.bingham.com/Page.aspx?PageID=4 |archive-date=2008-02-09 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 1997, Bingham Dana acquired the 30-lawyer Japanese practice group of Marks & Murase, giving the firm offices in New York and Los Angeles and a strong base of Japanese institutional clients.<ref>{{cite news|title=Leading Japanese Practice Group Joins Bingham, Dana & Gould|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Leading+Japanese+Practice+Group+Joins+Bingham,+Dana+%26+Gould.-a019815612|accessdate=9 September 2015|agency=Business Wire|date=1 October 1997}}</ref> The next outpost was established in [[Hartford, Connecticut|Hartford]] through a merger with 55-lawyer Hebb & Gitlin, a firm that concentrated on international [[bankruptcy]] work. In 2001, Bingham Dana bulked up in New York City through a merger with Richards & O'Neill, a boutique law firm of 55 attorneys known for its [[litigation]] and corporate groups. The next year, in 2002, Bingham Dana merged with [[San Francisco]]-based law firm [[McCutchen, Doyle, Brown & Enersen]] to form 800-lawyer Bingham McCutchen. McCutchen Doyle brought five offices and a litigation and [[intellectual property]] focus. In 2003, the firm expanded in [[Southern California]] by merging with corporate boutique Riordan & McKinzie. 2006 saw a merger between Bingham McCutchen and [[Swidler Berlin Shereff Friedman]], a [[Washington, D.C.]]-based firm which brought greater capabilities in the nation's capital as well as a regulatory group. Bingham also launched in [[Hong Kong]] that same year. In 2007, the firm acquired Los Angeles litigation shop Alschuler Grossman. In July 2009, Bingham McCutchen acquired [[McKee Nelson]], a midsize law firm specializing in [[tax law]] and [[structured finance]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.law.com/jsp/nlj/PubArticleNLJ.jsp?id=1202432014189&Bingham_McCutchen_Acquires_McKee_Nelson&slreturn=1|title=Bingham McCutchen acquires McKee Nelson|last=Beck|first=Susan|date=2009-06-09|work=[[The American Lawyer]]|publisher=[[Incisive Media]]|accessdate=2009-07-07}}</ref>\n\nA team of Bingham attorneys and staff, led by [[Susan Baker Manning]] and [[Sabin Willett]], represented pro bono a dozen [[Uighur people|Uighur]] men held in [[extrajudicial detention]] in the United States [[Guantanamo Bay detention camp]]s, in Cuba.<ref name=NYtimes20070912>\n{{cite news\n| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/09/12/washington/12gitmo.html?ref=todayspaper\n| work=[[The New York Times]]\n| author=[[William Glaberson]]\n| title=Officials Cite Danger in Revealing Detainee Data\n| date= September 12, 2007\n| accessdate=2007-09-12\n| page=A18\n}}</ref><ref name=WashingtonPost20051224>\n{{cite news\n| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/12/23/AR2005122301503.html\n| title=Detainees Face Limited Access to Courts: But Bill Awaiting Bush Signature Would Shield Terror Suspects from U.S. Abuse\n| page=A04\n| work=[[The Washington Post]]\n| author=Josh White\n| date= December 24, 2005\n| accessdate=2008-01-05\n| authorlink= Josh White (journalist)\n}}</ref><ref name=Iht20060927>\n{{cite news\n| url=http://www.iht.com/articles/2006/09/27/opinion/edwillett.php\n| title=The Innocent Man at Guantanamo\n| publisher=[[International Herald Tribune]]\n| author=[[Sabin Willett]]\n| date= September 27, 2006\n| accessdate=2008-01-19\n}}</ref><ref name=Wapo20051114>\n{{cite news\n| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/11/13/AR2005111301061.html\n| title=Detainees Deserve Court Trials\n| pages=A21\n| work=[[The Washington Post]]\n| author=P. Sabin Willett\n| date= November 14, 2005\n| accessdate=2008-01-19\n| authorlink= Sabin Willett\n}}</ref><ref name=BostonGlobe20071203>\n{{cite news\n| url=http://www.boston.com/bostonglobe/editorial_opinion/oped/articles/2007/12/03/i_will_never_leave_guantanamo/\n| title=I will never leave Guantanamo\n| page=\n| pages=\n| publisher=[[Boston Globe]]\n| author=[[Sabin Willett]]\n| date=December 3, 2007\n| accessdate=2008-01-19\n}}</ref>\nBingham litigated a number of habeas corpus cases on behalf of the Uighur clients, as well as cases under the Detainee Treatment Act of 2005 that brought to light evidentiary and procedural flaws in the 2004-05 [[Combatant Status Review Tribunal]]s that were used to justify the Uighurs' ongoing imprisonment. All Bingham clients were subsequently released.\n\nThe Tokyo office of Bingham McCutchen became one of the largest law firms in Japan by its 2007 merger with a domestic law firm headed by Hideyuki Sakai, an insolvency specialist. Unlike most foreign firms in Japan which have minimal domestic practices, Bingham's Tokyo office was predominantly staffed by Japanese attorneys and handled domestic matters such as the restructuring of [[Olympus Corporation]], though it hired a number of foreign attorneys since 2012 in an attempt to strengthen its outbound and cross-border practice and to expand in other legal fields such as intellectual property and investment funds.<ref>{{cite news|last=Brennan|first=Tom|title=Bingham Aims for Top of Tokyo Pack|url=http://www.americanlawyer.com/PubArticleAL.jsp?id=1202618529194&thepage=1|accessdate=10 September 2013|newspaper=The Asian Lawyer|date=9 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nDespite a deep recession which hurt law firms nationwide, the Boston Globe reported that Bingham performed very well financially.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.boston.com/business/articles/2010/02/05/profits_soar_for_boston_law_partners/ | work=The Boston Globe | title=Profits soar for law partners | first=Kit | last=Chellel | date=2010-02-05}}</ref>  In 2009, Bingham's gross revenues increased 12% and profits per partner increased 2%.  Chairman Jay Zimmerman was quoted as saying \"We\u2019ve had our best year ever.\" However, despite an increase in revenues, Bingham froze salaries, and in March 2009 laid off 16 attorneys and 29 support staff.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://abovethelaw.com/2009/03/nationwide_layoff_watch_bingha_1.php |title=Nationwide Layoff Watch: Bingham McCutchen Cuts 39 Overall |author=Elie Mystal |date=5 March 2009 |accessdate=28 October 2010 }}{{dead link|date=July 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n===Collapse===\n\nBingham experienced internal tensions following the 2002 McCutchen merger, and again following the 2009 McKee merger. Both transactions were viewed as \"mergers of equals\" among some insiders, and as unequal acquisitions among others. The McKee transaction involved large compensation guarantees to several key McKee partners which were not immediately disclosed to other Bingham partners. The legacy McKee partners continued to earn relatively high compensation following the acquisition due to the fact that they charged higher hourly rates than the legacy Bingham partners; the legacy Bingham partners nonetheless demanded salary matching, which strained the profits of the firm.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.law360.com/in-depth/articles/820381|title=Why Law Firm Mergers Fail - Law360|website=www.law360.com|access-date=2016-07-26}}</ref>\n\nBingham experienced a massive downsizing from 2012 to 2014, during which time it cut 225 lawyers and saw more than 50 partners leave the firm. Two major cases&mdash;the ''[[Deepwater Horizon]]'' litigation and an IP dispute involving [[Oracle Corporation]]&mdash;ended abruptly, reducing the firm's revenue.<ref name=\"globe1022\" /> Bingham attempted to cut costs by moving back office functions to a new center in Kentucky, but the initial cost of the move ($100,000 per equity partner) hurt the firm's 2014 financial results even further.<ref name=\"bna\">{{cite news|title=In Wake of Bingham, Lawyers Contemplate Services Centers|url=https://bol.bna.com/in-wake-of-bingham-lawyers-contemplate-services-centers/|accessdate=9 September 2015|work=Bloomberg BNA|date=18 June 2015}}</ref> After Bingham's collapse, it was revealed that [[Massachusetts Mutual Life Insurance]] stopped working with Bingham due to the low level of racial diversity among its partners in Boston and Hartford.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ryan|first1=Greg|title=Morgan Lewis inherited diversity problem that cost Bingham a big client|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/boston/news/2015/07/31/morgan-lewis-inherited-diversity-problem-that-cost.html|accessdate=9 September 2015|work=Boston Business Journal|date=31 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2014, 227 of around 300 partners and a similar number of associates joined the Philadelphia-based firm of [[Morgan Lewis & Bockius]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://abovethelaw.com/2014/11/bingham-to-go-bust-in-wake-of-morgan-lewis-raid/ |title=Bingham To Go Bust In Wake Of Morgan Lewis Raid |author=David Lat |date=17 November 2014 |accessdate=17 November 2014}}</ref> Morgan Lewis paid off Bingham's debt as part of the deal,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Passarella|first1=Gina|title=Morgan Lewis finalizes deal with Bingham McCutchen, adds 510 lawyers|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/business/legal/2014/12/02/Morgan-Lewis-finalizes-deal-with-Bingham-McCutchen-adds-510-lawyers/stories/201412020007|accessdate=9 September 2015|work=The Legal Intelligencer|date=2 December 2014}}</ref> and shut down Bingham's Kentucky operations center, relocating some employees to Philadelphia.<ref name=\"bna\" />\n\nBingham's London and Frankfurt offices joined [[Akin Gump Strauss Hauer & Feld]].<ref>{{cite web|title=London and Frankfurt Offices of Bingham McCutchen to Join Akin Gump|url=https://www.akingump.com/en/news-insights/london-and-frankfurt-offices-of-bingham-mccutchen-to-join-akin.html|publisher=Akin Gump|accessdate=9 September 2015}}</ref> 50 of Bingham's 60 lawyers in Tokyo moved to the Japanese law firm of [[Anderson Mori & Tomotsune]], with the remainder joining Morgan Lewis.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Verghese|first1=Kanishk|title=Anderson Mori swoops in for 50 Bingham lawyers in Tokyo|url=http://www.legalbusinessonline.com/appointments/anderson-mori-swoops-50-bingham-lawyers-tokyo/68579|accessdate=9 September 2015|work=Asian Legal Business|date=16 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Offices==\n\nAs of 2014, Bingham McCutchen had offices in [[Beijing]], [[Boston, Massachusetts|Boston]], [[Hartford, Connecticut|Hartford]], [[Hong Kong]], [[Lexington, Kentucky|Lexington]], [[London]], [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]], [[New York City|New York]], [[Orange County, California|Orange County]], [[San Francisco, California|San Francisco]], [[Santa Monica, California]], [[Silicon Valley]], [[Tokyo]], and [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref name=\"offices\"/> It also offered consulting services through subsidiaries Bingham Consulting and Bingham Strategic Advisors.<ref name=\"hoovers-desc\"/>\n\n==Notable people==\n*[[Denise Jefferson Casper]] (judge, [[United States District Court for the District of Massachusetts]])\n*[[Christopher Cox]] (former Chairman, [[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]], and former [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]])\n*[[Barry Goode]] (retired from the firm in 2001 to join state government, and now is a Contra Costa County judge)\n*[[Thurgood Marshall, Jr.]] (former [[Bill Clinton|Clinton]] [[White House]] [[Executive Office of the President|Cabinet Secretary]])\n*[[Steve Merrill]] (former [[Governor of New Hampshire]]) \n*[[Richard Riordan]] (former [[Mayor of Los Angeles, California|Mayor of Los Angeles]])\n*[[Josiah Spaulding]]\n*[[Sabin Willett]]\n*[[Pete Wilson]] (former [[Governor of California]] and former [[United States Senate|U.S. Senator]])\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080129132048/http://www.bingham.com/ Bingham.com Official Website]\n* [http://www.natlawreview.com/organization/bingham-mccutchen-llp Bingham McCutchen National Law Review Profile]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150613140734/http://www.binghammccutchen.biz/bingham-mccutchen/ Bingham McCutchen]\n{{Defunct law firms of the United States}}\n\n[[Category:Law firms established in 1891]]\n[[Category:Defunct law firms of the United States]]\n[[Category:1891 establishments in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Law firms disestablished in 2014]]\n[[Category:2014 disestablishments in Massachusetts]]\n", "name_user": "Widefox", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:bold full name per MOS, fix XML", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bingham_McCutchen"}
{"title_page": "Pope\u0219ti, Vrancea", "text_new": "{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = commune\n|county                 = Vrancea\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Vrancea County\n|coordinates            = {{coord|45|35|N|27|06|E|region:RO|display=it}}\n|name=Pope\u0219ti\n|image_map              = Popesti jud Vrancea.png\n}}\n'''Pope\u0219ti''' is a [[Commune in Romania|commune]] located in [[Vrancea County]], [[Romania]]. It is composed of two villages, Pope\u0219ti and Terche\u0219ti. These were part of [[Ureche\u0219ti, Vrancea|Ureche\u0219ti]] Commune until 2003, when they were split off.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Vrancea-geo-stub}}\n{{Vrancea County}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Popesti, Vrancea}}\n[[Category:Communes in Vrancea County]]\n[[Category:Localities in Muntenia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = commune\n|county                 = Vrancea\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Vrancea County\n|coordinates            = {{coord|45|35|N|27|06|E|region:RO|display=it}}\n|name=Pope\u0219ti\n|image_map=\n}}\n'''Pope\u0219ti''' is a [[Commune in Romania|commune]] located in [[Vrancea County]], [[Romania]]. It is composed of two villages, Pope\u0219ti and Terche\u0219ti. These were part of [[Ureche\u0219ti, Vrancea|Ureche\u0219ti]] Commune until 2003, when they were split off.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Vrancea-geo-stub}}\n{{Vrancea County}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Popesti, Vrancea}}\n[[Category:Communes in Vrancea County]]\n[[Category:Localities in Muntenia]]\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pope%C8%99ti,_Vrancea"}
{"title_page": "Aguri (caste)", "text_new": "{{Infobox caste\n| caste_name          = Aguri or Ugra Kshatriya\n| classification      =\n| family_names        =\n| population          = \n| populated_states    = [[West Bengal]]\n| languages           = [[Bengali language|Bengali]]\n| religions           = [[Hinduism]]\n}}\n\n'''Aguri''', also known as '''Ugra Kshatriya''', is a [[caste]] or community of [[Hindu]]s found in the districts of [[Bardhaman district|Bardhaman]], [[Birbhum district|Birbhum]], [[Hooghly district|Hooghly]] and [[Bankura district|Bankura]] in the state of [[West Bengal]] in India.<ref name=\"kundu\">{{cite book |title=\u09ac\u09be\u0999\u09be\u09b2\u09bf \u09b9\u09bf\u09a8\u09cd\u09a6\u09c1 \u099c\u09be\u09a4\u09bf \u09aa\u09b0\u09bf\u099a\u09af\u09bc |trans-title=An Introduction of Bengali Hindu Castes |language=Bengali |last=Kundu |first=Santosh Kumar |year=2008 |publisher=Presidency Library |location=Kolkata |isbn=978-81-89466-13-8 |pages=65\u201367}}</ref> Aguris are considered as a middle-caste group and constitute \"more prosperous owner-peasants\" among the peasant communities of [[Bengal]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Omvedt |first=Gail |authorlink=Gail Omvedt |title=Land, caste, and politics in Indian states |publisher=Authors Guild Publications |year=1982 |lccn=lc82901477 |url=https://books.google.com/books?ei=HCZCVIrhB5SGuATK74IY&id=eW3aAAAAMAAJ&dq=aguri+ugra+kshatriya+caste+bengal&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=aguri |page=92}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Chatterjee|first=Partha |title=The Present History of West Bengal: Essays in Political Criticism |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=1997 |isbn=978-0-19-563945-2|url=https://books.google.com/books?ei=HCZCVIrhB5SGuATK74IY&id=OjhuAAAAMAAJ&dq=aguri+ugra+kshatriya+caste+bengal&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=aguri |page=78}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Singh|first=Kumar Suresh |title=People of India: West Bengal, Volume 43, Part 1 |publisher=Anthropological Survey of India |year=2008 |isbn=978-81-7046-300-9 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IBhWAAAAYAAJ&q=aguri+ugra+kshatriya+caste+bengal&dq=aguri+ugra+kshatriya+caste+bengal&hl=en&sa=X&ei=HCZCVIrhB5SGuATK74IY&ved=0CDIQ6AEwAw |page=xxvii}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nAguris are a cultivating and trading caste. According to Santosh Kumar Kundu, they were brought by the ruler of [[Bardhaman Raj|Burdwan]] from Agra to West Bengal to fight against the British colonists.<ref name=\"kundu\"/> [[William Benjamin Oldham]], a British civil servant and [[ethnography|ethnographer]] who wrote ''Some Historical and Ethnical Aspects of Burdwan District'' (1891), said that they originated from marriage alliances between the  rulers of and the [[Khatri]] rulers of Burdwan. He based this on the Aguri's own account but McLane believes that Oldham was misled by the Aguri. Citing a 1589 work by [[Mukundaram]]. McLane says that the Aguri were present \"almost certainly\" before the arrival of the Khatris in Burdwan.<ref name=\"mclane\">{{cite book |title=Land and Local Kingship in Eighteenth-Century Bengal |last=McLane |first=John R. |date=25 July 2002 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |location= |isbn=978-0-521-52654-8 |page=157 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YH6ijJnUPmcC&pg=PA157}}</ref>\n\n''[[Manusm\u1e5bti|Manu]]'', a Hindu religious text, says Ugra (meaning ''aggressive'') was born to a [[Shudra]] girl by a Kshatriya father. This mixed origin meant that the community was considered to have an ambivalent position in the [[Varna (Hinduism)|Hindu varna system]], although by the 1960s they were [[Sanskritisation|claiming to be pure Kshatriya]].<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=0yqV1Ux0oGIC&pg=PA453 |title=Society In India |first=A. R. |last=Desai |edition=Reprinted |publisher=Popular Prakashan |year=1975 |isbn=978-8-17154-013-6 |page=453}}</ref>\n\n== Culture ==\nAround the beginning of the 20th century, the Aguri were among the agricultural communities that still predominantly adhered to the custom of paying a [[bride price]] at the time of marriage, although some more prosperous members among them were already adopting the increasingly common alternative of paying a [[dowry]]. This minority believed that bride price was deprecated by higher castes.<ref>{{cite book |title=Women and Labour in Late Colonial India: The Bengal Jute Industry |first=Samita |last=Sen |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=1999 |isbn=978-0-521-45363-9 |page=85 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gN1dEJuiZ0cC&pg=PA85}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Bengali Hindu people}}\n\n[[Category:Bengali Hindu castes]]\n[[Category:Social groups of West Bengal]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox caste\n| caste_name          = Aguri or Ugra Kshatriya\n| classification      =\n| family_names        =\n| population          = \n| populated_states    = [[West Bengal]]\n| languages           = [[Bengali language|Bengali]]\n| religions           = [[Hinduism]]\n}}\n\n'''Aguri''', also known as '''Ugra Kshatriya''', is a [[caste]] or community of [[Hindu]]s found in the districts of [[Bardhaman district|Bardhaman]], [[Birbhum district|Birbhum]], [[Hooghly district|Hooghly]] and [[Bankura district|Bankura]] in the state of [[West Bengal]] in India.<ref name=\"kundu\">{{cite book |title=\u09ac\u09be\u0999\u09be\u09b2\u09bf \u09b9\u09bf\u09a8\u09cd\u09a6\u09c1 \u099c\u09be\u09a4\u09bf \u09aa\u09b0\u09bf\u099a\u09af\u09bc |trans-title=An Introduction of Bengali Hindu Castes |language=Bengali |last=Kundu |first=Santosh Kumar |year=2008 |publisher=Presidency Library |location=Kolkata |isbn=978-81-89466-13-8 |pages=65\u201367}}</ref> Aguris are considered as a middle-caste group and constitute \"more prosperous owner-peasants\" among the peasant communities of [[Bengal]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Omvedt |first=Gail |authorlink=Gail Omvedt |title=Land, caste, and politics in Indian states |publisher=Authors Guild Publications |year=1982 |lccn=lc82901477 |url=https://books.google.com/books?ei=HCZCVIrhB5SGuATK74IY&id=eW3aAAAAMAAJ&dq=aguri+ugra+kshatriya+caste+bengal&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=aguri |page=92}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Chatterjee|first=Partha |title=The Present History of West Bengal: Essays in Political Criticism |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=1997 |isbn=978-0-19-563945-2|url=https://books.google.com/books?ei=HCZCVIrhB5SGuATK74IY&id=OjhuAAAAMAAJ&dq=aguri+ugra+kshatriya+caste+bengal&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=aguri |page=78}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Singh|first=Kumar Suresh |title=People of India: West Bengal, Volume 43, Part 1 |publisher=Anthropological Survey of India |year=2008 |isbn=978-81-7046-300-9 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IBhWAAAAYAAJ&q=aguri+ugra+kshatriya+caste+bengal&dq=aguri+ugra+kshatriya+caste+bengal&hl=en&sa=X&ei=HCZCVIrhB5SGuATK74IY&ved=0CDIQ6AEwAw |page=xxvii}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nAguris are a cultivating and trading caste. According to Santosh Kumar Kundu, they were brought by the ruler of [[Bardhaman Raj|Burdwan]] from Agra to West Bengal to fight against the British colonists.<ref name=\"kundu\"/> [[William Benjamin Oldham]], a British civil servant and [[ethnography|ethnographer]] who wrote ''Some Historical and Ethnical Aspects of Burdwan District'' (1891), said that they originated from marriage alliances between the [[Sadgop]] rulers of [[Gopbhum]] and the [[Khatri]] rulers of Burdwan. He based this on the Aguri's own account but McLane believes that Oldham was misled by the Aguri. Citing a 1589 work by [[Mukundaram]]. McLane says that the Aguri were present \"almost certainly\" before the arrival of the Khatris in Burdwan.<ref name=\"mclane\">{{cite book |title=Land and Local Kingship in Eighteenth-Century Bengal |last=McLane |first=John R. |date=25 July 2002 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |location= |isbn=978-0-521-52654-8 |page=157 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YH6ijJnUPmcC&pg=PA157}}</ref>\n\n''[[Manusm\u1e5bti|Manu]]'', a Hindu religious text, says Ugra (meaning ''aggressive'') was born to a [[Shudra]] girl by a Kshatriya father. This mixed origin meant that the community was considered to have an ambivalent position in the [[Varna (Hinduism)|Hindu varna system]], although by the 1960s they were [[Sanskritisation|claiming to be pure Kshatriya]].<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=0yqV1Ux0oGIC&pg=PA453 |title=Society In India |first=A. R. |last=Desai |edition=Reprinted |publisher=Popular Prakashan |year=1975 |isbn=978-8-17154-013-6 |page=453}}</ref>\n\n== Culture ==\nAround the beginning of the 20th century, the Aguri were among the agricultural communities that still predominantly adhered to the custom of paying a [[bride price]] at the time of marriage, although some more prosperous members among them were already adopting the increasingly common alternative of paying a [[dowry]]. This minority believed that bride price was deprecated by higher castes.<ref>{{cite book |title=Women and Labour in Late Colonial India: The Bengal Jute Industry |first=Samita |last=Sen |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=1999 |isbn=978-0-521-45363-9 |page=85 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gN1dEJuiZ0cC&pg=PA85}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Bengali Hindu people}}\n\n[[Category:Bengali Hindu castes]]\n[[Category:Social groups of West Bengal]]\n", "name_user": "Iamdray", "label": "safe", "comment": "i change sodgope caste and gopebhum ruler marriage point because it is disrespectful no caste can create from a marriage allaince.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aguri_(caste)"}
{"title_page": "Hanson Formation", "text_new": "{{Infobox rockunit\n| name           = Hanson Formation \n| image          = View of the Transantarctic Mountains.jpg\n| caption        = The Hanson Formation is located on the Transantarctic Mountains\n| type           = [[Geological formation]]\n| age            = Late [[Sinemurian]]-Lower [[Pliensbachian]]<br />~{{Fossilrange|194|188.5}}\n| period         = Early Jurassic\n| prilithology   = [[Sandstone]], [[tuffite]]\n| otherlithology =\n| namedfor       =\n| namedby        =\n| region         = [[Mount Kirkpatrick]], [[Beardmore Glacier]]\n| country        = {{flag|Antarctica}}\n| coordinates    = {{coord|84.3|S|166.5|E|source:wikidata|display=inline,title}}\n| paleocoordinates = {{coord|57.5|S|35.5|E|display=inline}}\n| unitof         = [[Victoria Group, Antarctica|Victoria Group]]\n| subunits       = Three informal members\n| underlies      = [[Prebble Formation]]\n| overlies       = [[Falla Formation]]\n| thickness      = {{convert|237.5|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n| extent         =\n| area           =\n| map            = {{Location map+ | Antarctica\n| relief = 1\n| width   = 250\n| float   = center\n| places  =\n  {{Location map~ | Antarctica\n  | lat_deg = -84.3\n  | lon_deg = 166.5\n  | mark = Blue pog.svg\n  | marksize = 12\n  }}\n}}\n| map_caption    =\n}}\n\nThe '''Hanson Formation''' is a [[geologic formation]] on [[Mount Kirkpatrick]], [[Antarctica]]. It is one of only two major [[dinosaur]]-bearing rock groups found on the continent of [[Antarctica]] to date; the other is the [[Snow Hill Island Formation]] and related formations from the [[Late Cretaceous]] of the [[Antarctic Peninsula]]. The formation has yielded only a handful of [[Mesozoic]] specimens so far and most of it is as yet unexcavated. Part of the [[Victoria Group, Antarctica|Victoria Group]] of the [[Transantarctic Mountains]], it is below the [[Prebble Formation]] and above the [[Falla Formation]].<ref>Elliot, D.H. (1996). ''The Hanson Formation: a new stratigraphical unit in the Transantarctic Mountains, Antarctica.'' Antarctic Science 8(4):389-394.[http://journals.cambridge.org/action/displayFulltext?type=1&fid=221034&jid=ANS&volumeId=8&issueId=04&aid=221033]</ref> The Formation is related to the Volcanic Activity Linked to the Karoo-Ferar eruptions on the Lower Jurassic.<ref>Ross, P.-S. et White, J.D.L. (2006) Debris jets in continental phreatomagmatic volcanoes: a field study of their subterranean deposits in the Coombs Hills vent complex, Antarctica. Journal of Volcanology and Geothermal Research 149: 62-84</ref><ref>Elliot, D. H., and D. Larsen. 1993. Mesozoic volcanism in the Transantarctic Mountains: depositional environment and tectonic setting; pp. 379\u2013410 in R. H. Findlay, M. R. Banks, J. J. Veevers, and R. Unrug (eds.), Gondwana 8\u2014Assembly, Evolution, and Dispersal. A. A. Balkema, Rotterdam</ref><ref>Heimann, A., T. H. Fleming, D. H. Elliot, and K. A. Foland. 1994.\nA short interval of Jurassic continental flood basalt volcanism in Antarctica as demonstrated by 40Ar/39Ar geochronology. Earth and Planetary Science Letters 121:19\u201341.</ref> The climate of the zone was similar to the modern Southern Chile, Humid, with a temperature interval of 17-18 degrees.<ref>Chandler, M. A., D. Rind, and R. Ruedy. 1992. Pangaean climate during the Early Jurassic: GCM simulations and the sedimentary record of paleoclimate. Geological Society of America Bulletin 104:543\u2013559</ref>\n\n== Paleofauna ==\nThe first dinosaur to be discovered from the Hanson Formation was the predator ''[[Cryolophosaurus]]'' in 1991, which was then formally described in 1994. Alongside these dinosaur remains were fossilized trees, suggesting that plant matter had once grown on Antarctica's surface before it drifted southward. Other finds from the formation include [[tritylodonts]], [[herbivore|herbivorous]] [[mammal|mammal-like]] [[reptile]]s and crow-sized [[pterosaur]]s. Surprisingly were the discovery of [[prosauropod]] remains, which were found commonly on other continents only until the Early Jurassic. However, the bone fragments found at the Hanson Formation were dated until the Middle Jurassic, millions of years later. In 2004, [[paleontologist]]s discovered partial remains of a large [[sauropod]] dinosaur that has not formally been described yet.\n\n__TOC__\n{{clearboth}}\n\n=== Invertebrate paleofauna ===\nThe insects ''[[Ademosynoides]]'' & ''[[Grahamelytron]]'' were claimed to be found on this formation, but they come from the Bajocian of a different formation. [[Beetle|Coleoptera]] and [[Blattoidea]] wings have been found.\n\n=== Bony fish ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align=\"center\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"7\" align=\"center\" | '''[[Bony fish]] of the Hanson Formation'''\n|-\n! Genus !! Species !! Location !! Stratigraphic position !! Material !! width=25% | Notes !! Images\n|-\n|[[Archaeomaenidae]]|| Indeterminate || Mt. Kirkpatrick ||  || Formerly was assigned was assigned to ''[[Oreochima]] ellioti'', that is a slightly younger Archaeomenid fish, and comes from the  [[Carapace Formation]]. Although scales similar of that of this family had been reported, representing at least three different genera.|| An [[archaeomaenidae|archaeomaenid]] [[pachycormiformes|pachycormiform fish]] || \n|-\n|}\n\n=== Synapsids ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align=\"center\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"7\" align=\"center\" | '''[[Synapsid]]s of the Hanson Formation'''\n|-\n! Genus !! Species !! Location !! Stratigraphic position !! Material !! Notes !! Images\n|-\n|[[Tritylodontidae]] <ref>Hammer, W.R. and Smith, N.D. 2008. A tritylodont postcanine from the Hanson Formation of Antarctica. Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology 28:269\u2013273.</ref>|| Indeterminate || Mt. Kirkpatrick || || FMNH PR1824, an isolated upper postcanine tooth. || Is related to the Asian genus ''[[Bienotheroides]]''. Probably the largest member of the family, and among the largest post-triassic Synapsids, with a length over 1.6 m long, was probably robust as a modern [[Wolverine]]. A member of the family of the [[tritylodontidae|tritylodont]]s, one of the most advanced group of [[cynodont]]s. ||[[File:Tritylodon BW.jpg|center|150px]]\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Pterosaurs ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align=\"center\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"7\" align=\"center\" | '''[[Pterosaur]]s of the Hanson Formation'''\n|-\n! Genus !! Species !! Location !! Stratigraphic position !! Material !! Notes !! Images \n|-\n|[[Dimorphodontia]]? <ref name=\"earlyjurassicdistribution\" /><ref name=\"FrozenTime\" /><ref>Hammer, W. R., and W. J. Hickerson. 1996. Implications of an Early Jurassic vertebrate fauna from Antarctica; pp. 215\u2013218 in Michael Morales (ed.), The Continental Jurassic. Museum of Northern Arizona Bulletin 60, Flagstaff</ref>|| Indeterminate ||Mt. Kirkpatrick || || Humerus || Nearly the same size as YPM ''[[Dimorphodon]]''. Its affinities haven't been compared, but its numeral morphotype is common for basal pterosaurs, like in ''[[Preondactylus]]'' or ''[[Arcticodactylus]]'', so can be related to this genera.|| [[File:Dimorphodon2DB.jpg|center|150px]]\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Dinosaurs ===\n{{paleobiota-key-compact}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align=\"center\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"7\" align=\"center\" | '''[[Dinosaur]]s of the Hanson Formation'''<ref name=\"earlyjurassicdistribution\">Weishampel, David B; et al. (2004). \"Dinosaur distribution (Early Jurassic, Asia).\" In: Weishampel, David B.; Dodson, Peter; and Osm\u00f3lska, Halszka (eds.): The Dinosauria, 2nd, Berkeley: University of California Press. p.537. {{ISBN|0-520-24209-2}}.</ref>\n|-\n! Genus !! Species !! Location !! Stratigraphic position !! Material !! Notes !! Images\n|-\n| [[Fabrosauridae]] or ''[[Eocursor]]''-Grade ornithischian<ref>http://www.nbcnews.com/id/41662760/ns/technology_and_science-science/t/primitive-dinosaur-found-antarctic-mountains/#.XePtTuhKjIV</ref><ref>Hammer adds another new dinosaur to his collection: https://augustana.net/x33229.xml</ref><ref>https://vimeo.com/24543922</ref> || Indeterminate|| Mt. Kirkpatrick ||  || (1.2 m) Vertebrae, femur and possible caudal vertebrae || A Chimaera with Anchisaurid material<ref>https://www.britannica.com/topic/Antarctic-Dinosaurs-1812725</ref>  ||\n|-\n| ''[[Glacialisaurus]]''<ref name=SP07/> || ''G. hammeri'' <ref name=\"earlyjurassicdistribution\" /> ||Mt. Kirkpatrick  ||  || A partial right astragalus, medial and lateral distal tarsals, and partial right metatarsus preserved in articulation with each other. || An {{convert|8|m|ft|abbr=on}} long [[Massospondylidae|Massospondyloid]]|| [[File:Glacialisaurus2.jpg|center|250px]]\n|-\n|[[Melanorosauridae]]<ref name=\"SauropodomorphsA\">{{Cite journal|last=Smith|first=Nathan D.|date=2013|title=:New Dinosaurs from the Early Jurassic Hanson Formation of Antarctica, and Patters of Diversity and Biogeography in Early Jurassic Sauropodomorphs.|url=|journal=Geological Society of America Abstracts with Programs|volume=45|issue=7|pages=897|via=}}</ref>|| \"Sauropodomorph A\". New Genus and Species.|| Mt. Kirkpatrick  ||  || Nearly complete juvenile skeleton || Exposed on the Antarctic Dinosaur Exhibit of NHM of Los Angeles, like Sauropodomorph B. Is cited more derived than Sauropodomorph B. near sauropoda, but it is not a Sauropod.<ref name=\"SauropodomorphsB\">https://nhm.org/experience-nhm/exhibitions-natural-history-museum/antarctic-dinosaurs</ref> || \n|-\n|[[Anchisauria]]<ref name=\"SauropodomorphsA\"/>|| \"Sauropodomorph B\". New Genus and Species. || Mt. Kirkpatrick ||  || Several vertebrae and pelvic material || Was exposed on the recently Antarctic Dinosaur Exhibit of NHM of Los Angeles.<ref name=\"SauropodomorphsB\"/> || [[File:Glacialisaurus FMNH.jpg|thumb|left|Restoration of Sauropodomorph B (Small) along with Glacialisaurus]]\n|-\n| [[Sauropoda]]<ref name=SP07/><ref name=pickrell2004/><ref>Joyce, 2004. Digging for dinosaurs in Antarctica: Giant bones suggest icy continent had warmer past. NPR, 1-23-2004.</ref>|| Indeterminate<ref name=\"earlyjurassicdistribution\" /><ref name=pickrell2004/> || Mt. Kirkpatrick ||  ||Three metre-wide pelvis and ilium. Also vertebrae and limb elements.<ref name=\"FrozenTime\">Jeffrey Stilwell, John Long(2011):Frozen in Time: Prehistoric Life in Antarctica.CSIRO Publishing. Pags.100-105 {{ISBN|0643096353}}.</ref> ||A possible ''[[Pulanesaura]]''-grade Sauropod, less derived than ''[[Kotasaurus]]''. The presence of ''Glacialisaurus'' in the Hanson Formation with advanced true sauropods shows that both primitive and advanced members of this lineage existed side by side in the early Jurassic Period.<ref name=SP07/><ref name=DinoAntarctica>{{Cite journal|author=Smith, N.D., Makovicky, P.J., Pol, D., Hammer, W.R., and Currie, P.J. |year=2007 |title=The Dinosaurs of the Early Jurassic Hanson Formation of the Central Transantarctic Mountains: Phylogenetic Review and Synthesis |url=http://pubs.usgs.gov/of/2007/1047/srp/srp003/of2007-1047srp003.pdf |journal=U.S. Geological Survey and the National Academies |pages=5 pp. |doi=10.3133/of2007-1047.srp003|volume=2007|issue=1047srp003}}</ref><ref name=pickrell2004/>|| \n|-\n| [[Coelophysoidea]]?<ref>M. T. Carrano. 2020. Taxonomic opinions on the Dinosauria.</ref> || Indeterminate || Mt. Kirkpatrick ||  || FMNH PR1822, distal left femur || It is on study, pending to 2020. Was considered ''[[Glacialisaurus]]'' remains, although can be a genus similar to ''Coelophysis''. || \n|-\n| [[Coelophysidae]]<ref name=\"TeethTheropod\">http://dml.cmnh.org/1998Aug/msg00810.html</ref> || Indeterminate || Mt. Kirkpatrick ||  || Teeth  || Was described as a Halticosaurid, has been epeculated to be a ''[[Liliensternus]]''-grade Coelophysoid. Estimated length of 5.5 m. || \n|-\n|[[Neotheropoda]]<ref name=\"TeethTheropod\" />|| Indeterminate || Mt. Kirkpatrick ||  || Teeth  || It is probably either a ''[[Tachiraptor]]''-grade averostra, a Coelophysis-like form, or can even be a basal Tetanuran. Small size, estimated around 2.3 m long.|| \n|-\n| ''[[Cryolophosaurus]]''<ref>William R. Hammer, William J. Hickerson(1994):A Crested Theropod Dinosaur from Antarctica.Science  06 May 1994:\nVol. 264, Issue 5160, pp. 828-830 DOI: 10.1126/science.264.5160.828</ref><ref name=\"earlyjurassicdistribution\" /> || ''C. ellioti''<ref name=\"earlyjurassicdistribution\" /> || Mt. Kirkpatrick ||  || Partial skull and partial postcranium.<ref name=\"table-4-1-74\">\"Table 4.1,\" in Weishampel, et al. (2004). Page 74.</ref> Remains of a second specimen were collected in 2010.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=2017|title=New Information on the Theropod Dinosaur Cryolophosaurus Ellioti from the Early Jurassic Hanson Formation Of The Central Transantarctic Mountains|url=http://vertpaleo.org/Annual-Meeting/Annual-Meeting-Home/SVP-2017-program-book-7-20-17a-(1).aspx|journal=SVP Conference Abstracts 2017|volume=|pages=196|via=}}</ref> Juvenile teeth are also known.<ref>Smith, N.D.; Makovicky, P.J.; Hammer, W.R.; Currie, P.J. (2007). \"Osteology of Cryolophosaurus ellioti (Dinosauria: Theropoda) from the Early Jurassic of Antarctica and implications for early theropod evolution\" (PDF). Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society. 151 (2): 377\u2013421. doi:10.1111/j.1096-3642.2007.00325.x.</ref>|| Considered a [[Tetanura]]n theropod, is probably a basal averostra. The specimen is a subadult. || [[File:Cryolophosaurus reconstruction (flipped).jpg|center|250px]]\n|-\n|}\n\n== Flora ==\nFossilized wood is also present in the Hanson Formation, near the stratigraphic level of the tritylodont locality. It has affinities with the [[Araucariaceae]] and similar kinds of [[conifer]]s.<ref>H. S. Gair , G. Norris & John Ricker (1965) Early mesozoic microfloras from Antarctica, New Zealand Journal of Geology and Geophysics, 8:2, 231-235, DOI: 10.1080/00288306.1965.10428109</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Paleontology}}\n* [[List of dinosaur-bearing rock formations]]\n* [[List of fossiliferous stratigraphic units in Antarctica]]\n* [[Mawson Formation]]\n* [[Shafer Peak Formation]]\n\n{{clearboth}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=pickrell2004>{{cite news|last=Pickrell|first=John|title=Two New Dinosaurs Discovered in Antarctica|url=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2004/03/0309_040309_polardinos.html|accessdate=20 December 2013|newspaper=National Geographic|year=2004}}</ref>\n<ref name=SP07>{{cite journal |last=Smith |first=Nathan D. |author2=Pol, Diego |year=2007 |title=Anatomy of a basal sauropodomorph dinosaur from the Early Jurassic Hanson Formation of Antarctica |journal=Acta Palaeontologica Polonica |volume=52 |issue=4 |pages=657\u2013674 |url=https://www.app.pan.pl/archive/published/app52/app52-657.pdf |format=pdf }}</ref>\n}}\n\n[[Category:Geologic formations of Antarctica]]\n[[Category:Jurassic System of Antarctica]]\n[[Category:Hettangian Stage]]\n[[Category:Pliensbachian Stage]]\n[[Category:Sinemurian Stage]]\n[[Category:Sandstone formations]]\n[[Category:Tuff formations]]\n[[Category:Fluvial deposits]]\n[[Category:Paleontology in Antarctica]]\n[[Category:Landforms of the Ross Dependency]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox rockunit\n| name           = Hanson Formation \n| image          =\n| caption        =\n| type           = [[Geological formation]]\n| age            = Late [[Sinemurian]]-Lower [[Pliensbachian]]<br />~{{Fossilrange|194|188.5}}\n| period         = Early Jurassic\n| prilithology   = [[Sandstone]], [[tuffite]]\n| otherlithology =\n| namedfor       =\n| namedby        =\n| region         = [[Mount Kirkpatrick]], [[Beardmore Glacier]]\n| country        = {{flag|Antarctica}}\n| coordinates    = {{coord|84.3|S|166.5|E|source:wikidata|display=inline,title}}\n| paleocoordinates = {{coord|57.5|S|35.5|E|display=inline}}\n| unitof         = [[Victoria Group, Antarctica|Victoria Group]]\n| subunits       = Three informal members\n| underlies      = [[Prebble Formation]]\n| overlies       = [[Falla Formation]]\n| thickness      = {{convert|237.5|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n| extent         =\n| area           =\n| map            = {{Location map+ | Antarctica\n| relief = 1\n| width   = 250\n| float   = center\n| places  =\n  {{Location map~ | Antarctica\n  | lat_deg = -84.3\n  | lon_deg = 166.5\n  | mark = Blue pog.svg\n  | marksize = 12\n  }}\n}}\n| map_caption    =\n}}\n\nThe '''Hanson Formation''' is a [[geologic formation]] on [[Mount Kirkpatrick]], [[Antarctica]]. It is one of only two major [[dinosaur]]-bearing rock groups found on the continent of [[Antarctica]] to date; the other is the [[Snow Hill Island Formation]] and related formations from the [[Late Cretaceous]] of the [[Antarctic Peninsula]]. The formation has yielded only a handful of [[Mesozoic]] specimens so far and most of it is as yet unexcavated. Part of the [[Victoria Group, Antarctica|Victoria Group]] of the [[Transantarctic Mountains]], it is below the [[Prebble Formation]] and above the [[Falla Formation]].<ref>Elliot, D.H. (1996). ''The Hanson Formation: a new stratigraphical unit in the Transantarctic Mountains, Antarctica.'' Antarctic Science 8(4):389-394.[http://journals.cambridge.org/action/displayFulltext?type=1&fid=221034&jid=ANS&volumeId=8&issueId=04&aid=221033]</ref> The Formation is related to the Volcanic Activity Linked to the Karoo-Ferar eruptions on the Lower Jurassic.<ref>Ross, P.-S. et White, J.D.L. (2006) Debris jets in continental phreatomagmatic volcanoes: a field study of their subterranean deposits in the Coombs Hills vent complex, Antarctica. Journal of Volcanology and Geothermal Research 149: 62-84</ref><ref>Elliot, D. H., and D. Larsen. 1993. Mesozoic volcanism in the Transantarctic Mountains: depositional environment and tectonic setting; pp. 379\u2013410 in R. H. Findlay, M. R. Banks, J. J. Veevers, and R. Unrug (eds.), Gondwana 8\u2014Assembly, Evolution, and Dispersal. A. A. Balkema, Rotterdam</ref><ref>Heimann, A., T. H. Fleming, D. H. Elliot, and K. A. Foland. 1994.\nA short interval of Jurassic continental flood basalt volcanism in Antarctica as demonstrated by 40Ar/39Ar geochronology. Earth and Planetary Science Letters 121:19\u201341.</ref> The climate of the zone was similar to the modern Southern Chile, Humid, with a temperature interval of 17-18 degrees.<ref>Chandler, M. A., D. Rind, and R. Ruedy. 1992. Pangaean climate during the Early Jurassic: GCM simulations and the sedimentary record of paleoclimate. Geological Society of America Bulletin 104:543\u2013559</ref>\n\n== Paleofauna ==\nThe first dinosaur to be discovered from the Hanson Formation was the predator ''[[Cryolophosaurus]]'' in 1991, which was then formally described in 1994. Alongside these dinosaur remains were fossilized trees, suggesting that plant matter had once grown on Antarctica's surface before it drifted southward. Other finds from the formation include [[tritylodonts]], [[herbivore|herbivorous]] [[mammal|mammal-like]] [[reptile]]s and crow-sized [[pterosaur]]s. Surprisingly were the discovery of [[prosauropod]] remains, which were found commonly on other continents only until the Early Jurassic. However, the bone fragments found at the Hanson Formation were dated until the Middle Jurassic, millions of years later. In 2004, [[paleontologist]]s discovered partial remains of a large [[sauropod]] dinosaur that has not formally been described yet.\n\n__TOC__\n{{clearboth}}\n\n=== Invertebrate paleofauna ===\nThe insects ''[[Ademosynoides]]'' & ''[[Grahamelytron]]'' were claimed to be found on this formation, but they come from the Bajocian of a different formation. [[Beetle|Coleoptera]] and [[Blattoidea]] wings have been found.\n\n=== Bony fish ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align=\"center\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"7\" align=\"center\" | '''[[Bony fish]] of the Hanson Formation'''\n|-\n! Genus !! Species !! Location !! Stratigraphic position !! Material !! width=25% | Notes !! Images\n|-\n|[[Archaeomaenidae]]|| Indeterminate || Mt. Kirkpatrick ||  || Formerly was assigned was assigned to ''[[Oreochima]] ellioti'', that is a slightly younger Archaeomenid fish, and comes from the  [[Carapace Formation]]. Although scales similar of that of this family had been reported, representing at least three different genera.|| An [[archaeomaenidae|archaeomaenid]] [[pachycormiformes|pachycormiform fish]] || \n|-\n|}\n\n=== Synapsids ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align=\"center\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"7\" align=\"center\" | '''[[Synapsid]]s of the Hanson Formation'''\n|-\n! Genus !! Species !! Location !! Stratigraphic position !! Material !! Notes !! Images\n|-\n|[[Tritylodontidae]] <ref>Hammer, W.R. and Smith, N.D. 2008. A tritylodont postcanine from the Hanson Formation of Antarctica. Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology 28:269\u2013273.</ref>|| Indeterminate || Mt. Kirkpatrick || || FMNH PR1824, an isolated upper postcanine tooth. || Is related to the Asian genus ''[[Bienotheroides]]''. Probably the largest member of the family, and among the largest post-triassic Synapsids, with a length over 1.6 m long, was probably robust as a modern [[Wolverine]]. A member of the family of the [[tritylodontidae|tritylodont]]s, one of the most advanced group of [[cynodont]]s. ||[[File:Tritylodon BW.jpg|center|150px]]\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Pterosaurs ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align=\"center\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"7\" align=\"center\" | '''[[Pterosaur]]s of the Hanson Formation'''\n|-\n! Genus !! Species !! Location !! Stratigraphic position !! Material !! Notes !! Images \n|-\n|[[Dimorphodontia]]? <ref name=\"earlyjurassicdistribution\" /><ref name=\"FrozenTime\" /><ref>Hammer, W. R., and W. J. Hickerson. 1996. Implications of an Early Jurassic vertebrate fauna from Antarctica; pp. 215\u2013218 in Michael Morales (ed.), The Continental Jurassic. Museum of Northern Arizona Bulletin 60, Flagstaff</ref>|| Indeterminate ||Mt. Kirkpatrick || || Humerus || Nearly the same size as YPM ''[[Dimorphodon]]''. Its affinities haven't been compared, but its numeral morphotype is common for basal pterosaurs, like in ''[[Preondactylus]]'' or '