osaurus ellioti (Dinosauria: Theropoda) from the Early Jurassic of Antarctica and implications for early theropod evolution\" (PDF). Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society. 151 (2): 377\u2013421. doi:10.1111/j.1096-3642.2007.00325.x.</ref>|| Considered a [[Tetanura]]n theropod, is probably a basal averostra. The specimen is a subadult. || [[File:Cryolophosaurus reconstruction (flipped).jpg|center|250px]]\n|-\n|}\n\n== Flora ==\nFossilized wood is also present in the Hanson Formation, near the stratigraphic level of the tritylodont locality. It has affinities with the [[Araucariaceae]] and similar kinds of [[conifer]]s.<ref>H. S. Gair , G. Norris & John Ricker (1965) Early mesozoic microfloras from Antarctica, New Zealand Journal of Geology and Geophysics, 8:2, 231-235, DOI: 10.1080/00288306.1965.10428109</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Paleontology}}\n* [[List of dinosaur-bearing rock formations]]\n* [[List of fossiliferous stratigraphic units in Antarctica]]\n* [[Mawson Formation]]\n* [[Shafer Peak Formation]]\n\n{{clearboth}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=pickrell2004>{{cite news|last=Pickrell|first=John|title=Two New Dinosaurs Discovered in Antarctica|url=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2004/03/0309_040309_polardinos.html|accessdate=20 December 2013|newspaper=National Geographic|year=2004}}</ref>\n<ref name=SP07>{{cite journal |last=Smith |first=Nathan D. |author2=Pol, Diego |year=2007 |title=Anatomy of a basal sauropodomorph dinosaur from the Early Jurassic Hanson Formation of Antarctica |journal=Acta Palaeontologica Polonica |volume=52 |issue=4 |pages=657\u2013674 |url=https://www.app.pan.pl/archive/published/app52/app52-657.pdf |format=pdf }}</ref>\n}}\n\n[[Category:Geologic formations of Antarctica]]\n[[Category:Jurassic System of Antarctica]]\n[[Category:Hettangian Stage]]\n[[Category:Pliensbachian Stage]]\n[[Category:Sinemurian Stage]]\n[[Category:Sandstone formations]]\n[[Category:Tuff formations]]\n[[Category:Fluvial deposits]]\n[[Category:Paleontology in Antarctica]]\n[[Category:Landforms of the Ross Dependency]]\n", "name_user": "Yewtharaptor", "label": "safe", "comment": "Image", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hanson_Formation"}
{"title_page": "Credit theory of money", "text_new": "{{short description|Economic theory concerning the relationship between credit and money.}}\n[[File:SAM PC 1 - Tally sticks 1 - Overview.jpg|thumb|Single and split tally sticks in the [[Swiss Alpine Museum]] \u2013 similar items may have been used in debt based economic systems thought to pre-date the use of coinage.]]\n'''Credit theories of money''', also called '''debt theories of money''',  are [[monetary economics|monetary economic]] theories concerning the relationship between [[Credit (finance)|credit]] and [[money]]. Proponents of these theories, such as [[Alfred Mitchell-Innes]], sometimes emphasize that money and credit/[[debt]] are the same thing, seen from different points of view.<ref>As [[Alfred Mitchell-Innes|Innes]] mentions in ''What is money?'' (1913), whenever he uses the word ''credit'' or ''debt'', \"the thing spoken of is precisely the same in both cases, the one or the other word being used according as the situation is being looked at from the point of view of the creditor or of the debtor.\"</ref> Proponents assert that the essential nature of money is credit (debt), at least in eras where money is not backed by a commodity such as gold.  Two common strands of thought within these theories are the idea that money originated as a unit of account for debt, and the position that [[money creation]] involves the simultaneous creation of debt. Some proponents of credit theories of money argue that money is best understood as debt even in systems often understood as using [[commodity money]]. Others hold that money equates to credit only in a system based on [[fiat money]], where they argue that all forms of money including cash can be considered as forms of credit money.\n\nThe first formal credit theory of money arose in the 19th century. Anthropologist [[David Graeber]] has argued that for most of human history, money has been widely understood to represent debt, though he concedes that even prior to the [[Modern history|modern era]], there have been several periods where rival theories like [[metallism]] have held sway.\n\n==Scholarship==\nAccording to [[Joseph Schumpeter]], the first known advocate of a credit theory of money was [[Plato]].  Schumpeter describes [[metallism]]  as the other of \"two fundamental theories of money\", saying the first known advocate of metallism was [[Aristotle]].<ref>Chpt 1 Graeco-Roman Economics , 'History of Economic Analysis'',  [[Joseph Schumpeter]] , (1954)</ref><ref>{{Cite web\n|url= https://www.mtholyoke.edu/courses/fmoseley/conference/nelson1.pdf\n|title= Marx's objections to credit theories of money (extract from Nelson's 1999 book: ''Marx's concept of Money'' )\n|publisher= [[Mount Holyoke College]]\n|author= Anitra Nelson\n|accessdate=2013-07-08}}\n</ref> The earliest modern thinker to formulate a credit theory of money was [[Henry Dunning Macleod]] (1821-1902), with his work in the 19th century, most especially with his ''The Theory of Credit'' (1889). \nMacleod's work was expanded on by [[Alfred Mitchell-Innes]] in his papers ''What is Money?'' (1913) and ''The Credit Theory of Money'' (1914),<ref>Originally published in ''The Banking Law Journal'', since reprinted in books such as Wray (2004) and made available online by the [[Community Exchange System|CES]]</ref> where he argued against the then conventional view of money arising as a means to improve the practice of barter.  In this alternative view, [[commerce]] and [[taxation]] created obligations between parties which were forms of [[credit (finance)|credit]] and debt. Devices such as [[tally stick]]s were used to record these obligations and these then became [[negotiable instrument]]s which could function as money.  As Innes puts it in his 1914 article:\n\n{{quote|The Credit Theory is this: that a sale and purchase is the exchange of a commodity for credit. From this main theory springs the sub-theory that the value of credit or money does not depend on the value of any metal or metals, but on the right which the creditor acquires to \"payment,\" that is to say, to satisfaction for the credit, and on the obligation of the debtor to \"pay\" his debt and conversely on the right of the debtor to release himself from his debt by the tender of an equivalent debt owed by the creditor, and the obligation of the creditor to accept this tender in satisfaction of his credit. }}\n\nInnes goes on to note that a major problem in getting the public to understand the extent to which monetary systems are debt based is the challenge in persuading them that  \"things are not the way they seem\".<ref name = \"Wray\">\n{{cite book \n|editor = Randy Wray \n|title=Credit & State Theories of Money \n|chapter= See esp Chpt 1 7 \n|year=2004\n|isbn=1843765136 \n|publisher= Edward Elgar \n}}</ref>\n\nA Quantity Theory of Credit was proposed in 1992 by [[Richard Werner]], whereby credit creation is disaggregated into credit for GDP and non-GDP (financial circulation). The approach is tested empirically in a general-to-specific econometric time series model and found to be superior to alternative and traditional theories. According to Werner bank credit creation for GDP transactions [[Granger causality|Granger-causes]] nominal GDP growth, while credit creation for financial transactions explains asset prices and banking crises.<ref name = \"Werner\">Richard A. Werner, 1993, Towards a Quantity Theorem of Disaggregated Credit and International Capital Flows, with Evidence from Japan, paper presented at the Royal Economic Society Annual Conference in York in April 1993, and the 5th Annual PACAP Conference on Pacific-Asian Capital Markets in Kuala Lumpur, June 1993 and published later as Richard A. Werner, 1997, Towards a New Monetary Paradigm: A Quantity Theorem of Disaggregated Credit, with Evidence from Japan, Kredit und Kapital, 30, 2, pp. 276-309. Available at http://eprints.soton.ac.uk/36569/. See also http://www.kredit-und-kapital.de/archiv/1997-2.html#r1 and Werner, Richard A. (2012). Towards a New Research Programme on \u2018Banking and the Economy\u2019 \u2013 Implications of the Quantity Theory of Credit for the Prevention and Resolution of Banking and Debt Crises, International Review of Financial Analysis, 25, 94-105, [http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1057521912000555] </ref> Based on this, Werner (2005) developed a new approach to macroeconomics, which integrates the nature of banks as money creators in macroeconomics - usually ignored in conventional macroeconomics.<ref>Richard A. Werner, 2005, New Paradigm in Macroeconomics, Palgrave Macmillan.</ref> Werner's approach is based on the scientific research methodology (the inductive method), not the axiomatic-hypothetical deductive approach commonly used in macroeconomics, which assumes away the existence of banks or market rationing. Hence in his approach markets are not expected to be in equilibrium, but the short side principle applies, which emphasises the power of banks in making decisions about the amount and allocation of credit created and distributed in the economy. Werner used the Quantity Theory of Credit (also known as the Quantity Theory of Disaggregated Credit) to develop a new monetary policy for post-crisis banking systems, which he called 'Quantitative Easing' (Werner, 1995, published in the Japanese financial newspaper, the Nikkei), a name later adopted by the Bank of Japan and Bank of England for related policies <ref> Richard A. Werner (1995), Keiki kaifuku, ry\u014dteki kiny\u016b kanwa kara, (How to Create a Recovery through \u2018Quantitative Monetary Easing\u2019), The Nihon Keizai Shinbun (Nikkei), \u2018Keizai Ky\u014dshitsu\u2019 (\u2018Economics Classroom\u2019), 2 September 1995 (morning edition), p. 26; English translation by T. John Cooke (November 2011)[http://eprints.soton.ac.uk/340476/]</ref>. The role of banks as creators of both the credit and the money supply has since been empirically demonstrated by Werner in widely-noted finance journal publications.<ref> Werner, Richard A. (2016), A lost century in Economics: Three theories of banking and the conclusive evidence, International Review of Financial Analysis, 46, July, 361\u2013379, online: [http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1057521915001477]  and Werner, Richard A.  (2014). Can Banks Individually Create Money Out of Nothing? \u2013 The Theories and the Empirical Evidence, International Review of Financial Analysis, 36, 1-19, [http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1057521914001070] </ref>\n\nSince the late 20th century, Innes' credit theory of money has been integrated into [[Modern Monetary Theory]]. The theory also combines elements of [[chartalism]], noting that [[high powered money]] is functionally an [[IOU]] from the state,<ref name=\"mmt\">{{citation|first1=Scott |last1= Fullwiler| first2=Stephanie |last2= Kelton | first3=L. Randall | last3= Wray |contribution = Modern Money Theory : A Response to Critics|title= Working Paper Series: Modern Monetary Theory - A Debate| pages=17\u201326|publisher = [[Political Economy Research Institute]] |location=Amherst, MA |number = 279 | date = January 2012 | accessdate= May 26, 2019| url= http://www.peri.umass.edu/fileadmin/pdf/working_papers/working_papers_251-300/WP279.pdf }}</ref> and therefore, \"all 'state money' is also 'credit money'\". The state ensures there is demand for its IOUs by accepting them as payment for taxes, fees, fines, tithes, and tribute.<ref name=\"MMTreply\">\u00c9ric Tymoigne and L. Randall Wray, [http://www.levyinstitute.org/pubs/wp_778.pdf \"Modern Money Theory 101: A Reply to Critics,\"] Levy Economics Institute of Bard College, Working Paper No. 778 (November 2013).</ref>\n\nIn his 2011 book ''[[Debt: The First 5000 Years]]'', the anthropologist [[David Graeber]] asserted that the best available evidence suggests the original monetary systems were debt based, and that most subsequent systems have been too. Exceptions where the relationship between money and debt was less clear occurred during periods where money has been backed by [[bullion]], as happens with a [[gold standard]]. Graeber echoes earlier theorists such as Innes by saying that during these eras population perception was that money derived its value from the precious metals of which the coins were made,<ref>This is the classic [[Metallism|Metallist]] view.</ref> but that even in these periods money is more accurately understood as debt. Graeber states that the three main functions of money are to act as: a  [[medium of exchange]]; a [[unit of account]]; and a [[store of value]]. Graeber writes that since [[Adam Smith]]'s time, economists have tended to emphasise money as a ''medium of exchange''.<ref>Polanyi goes as far as to say [[David Ricardo|Ricardo]] \"indoctrinated\" economists into viewing money just as a  ''medium of exchange'' - see chapter 16 of [[The Great Transformation (book)|The Great Transformation]].</ref> For Graeber, when money first appeared its primary purpose was to act as a ''unit of account'', to denominate debt. He writes that coins were originally created as [[token coin|tokens]] which represented a unit of account rather than being an amount of [[precious metal]] which could be bartered.<ref name = \"Graeber\">{{citation|title=Debt: The First 5000 Years |chapter= ''passim'', see especially chapter 2: The Myth of Barter |author=David Graeber |year=2011 |isbn=978-1-61219-181-2|title-link= Debt: The First 5000 Years }}</ref>\n\nEconomics commentator Philip Coggan holds that the world's current monetary system became debt-based after the [[Nixon Shock]], in which President Nixon suspended the link between money and [[gold]] in 1971. He writes that \"Modern money is debt and debt is money\".  Since the 1971 Nixon Shock, debt creation  and [[money creation|the creation of money]] increasingly took place at once. This simultaneous creation of money and debt occurs as a feature of [[fractional reserve banking]]. After a commercial bank approves a loan, it is able to create the corresponding amount of money, which is then acquired by the borrower along with a similar amount of debt.<ref>The new debt will generally soon exceed the newly created money due to added interest.</ref> \nCoggan goes on to say that debtors often prefer debt-based monetary systems such as [[fiat money]] over commodity-based systems like the gold standard, because the former tend to allow much higher volumes of money to circulate in the economy, and tend to be more expansive. This makes their debts easier to repay. Coggan refers to [[William Jennings Bryan]]'s 19th century [[Cross of Gold speech]] as one of the first great attempts to weaken the link between gold and money; he says the former US presidential candidate was trying to expand the [[monetary base]] in the interests of indebted farmers, who at the time were often being forced into bankruptcy.  However Coggan also says that the excessive debt which can be built up under a debt-based monetary system can end up hurting all sections of society, including debtors.<ref name = \"Promises\">\n{{cite book |author             = Philip Coggan\n |title              = Paper Promises: Money, Debt and the New World Order\n |chapter            = ''passim'', see esp Introduction\n |year               = 2011\n |isbn               = 978-1846145100\n |publisher          = Allen Lane\n |chapter-url-access = registration\n |chapter-url        = https://archive.org/details/paperpromisesmon0000cogg_z0h5\n |url-access         = registration\n |url                = https://archive.org/details/paperpromisesmon0000cogg_z0h5\n}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2012 paper, economic theorist [[Perry Mehrling]] notes that what is commonly regarded as money can often be viewed as debt.  He posits a hierarchy of assets with gold<ref>In the Financial sector, gold is often said to be the only financial asset that does not represent someone else's liability to pay.</ref> at the top, then [[currency]], then [[deposits]] and then [[securities]]. The lower down the hierarchy, the easier it is to view the asset as reflecting someone else's debt.<ref>{{cite web\n|url= http://www.ieor.columbia.edu/pdf-files/Mehrling_P_FESeminar_Sp12-02.pdf\n|archive-url= https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20121221064955/http://www.ieor.columbia.edu/pdf-files/Mehrling_P_FESeminar_Sp12-02.pdf\n|url-status= dead\n|archive-date= 2012-12-21\n|title= The Inherent Hierarchy of Money\n|work= [[Columbia University]]\n|author= Perry Mehrling\n|date= 2012-01-25\n|accessdate= 2012-07-10\n|author-link= Perry Mehrling\n}}</ref>\nA later 2012 paper from Claudio Borio of the [[Bank for International Settlements|BIS]] made the contrary case that it is loans that give rise to deposits, rather than the other way round.<ref>\"[http://www.bis.org/publ/work395.pdf The financial cycle and macroeconomics: What have we learnt?]\", by Claudio Borio, [[Bank for International Settlements]]  December 2012</ref>\n\nIn a book published in June 2013, the writer Felix Martin, influenced by Werner (2003, 2005), argued that credit based theories of money are correct, citing many of Werner's sources, such as Macleod:  \"currency ... represents transferable debt, and nothing else\". Martin writes that it is difficult for people to grasp the nature of money, because money is such a central part of society, and alludes to the Chinese proverb that \"If you want to know what water is like, don't ask the fish.\"<ref>Richard A. Werner (2003), Princes of the Yen, 2nd edition by Quantum Publishers [www.quantumpublishers.com]</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=Felix Martin|title=Money: The Unauthorized Biography|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1Su0AAAAQBAJ|date=4 March 2014|publisher=Knopf Doubleday Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-307-96244-7}} Chapter 1</ref><ref> \n{{Cite web\n|url= https://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/jun/09/money-biography-felix-martin-review\n|title= Money: The Unauthorised Biography by Felix Martin \u2013 review\n|publisher= [[The Guardian]]\n|author= Ian Birrell\n|date = 2013-06-09\n|accessdate=2013-07-08}}\n</ref>\n\n==Advocacy==\nThe conception that money is essentially equivalent to credit or debt has long been used by those advocating particular reforms of the monetary system, and by commentators calling for various [[monetary policy]] responses to events such as the [[financial crisis of 2007\u20132008]].  A view held in common by most recent advocates, from all shades of political opinion, is that money can be equated with debt in the context of the contemporary monetary system.  The view that money is equivalent to debt even in systems based on [[commodity money]] tends to be held only by those to the left of the political spectrum. Regardless of any commonality in their understanding of credit theories of money, the actual reforms proposed by advocates of different political orientations are sometimes diametrically opposed.<ref name = \"Promises\"/>\n\n===Advocacy for a return to a gold standard or similar commodity based system.===\n[[File:Ronpaul1.jpg|thumb|250px|Former US presidential candidate [[Ron Paul]] has spoken out against ''fiat money'', partly on the grounds that it encourages the buildup of debt.<ref>{{Cite web\n|url=http://archive.lewrockwell.com/paul/paul125.html\n|title= Fiat Paper Money\n|publisher=LewRockwell.com\n|author=  Ron Paul\n|date = 12 Sep 2003\n|accessdate= 16 July 2012|author-link= Ron Paul\n}}\n</ref>\n]]\n\nAdvocates from an [[Austrian School]], [[right-libertarianism|right-libertarian]] perspective often hold that money is equivalent to debt in our current  monetary system, but that it need not be in one where money has inherent value, such as a [[gold standard]]. They have frequently used this view point to support arguments that it would be best to return to a gold standard, to other forms of commodity money, or at least to a monetary system where money has positive value. Similar views are also occasionally expressed by [[conservatives]]. As an example of the latter, former British minister of state  [[Malcolm Sinclair, 20th Earl of Caithness|The Earl of Caithness]] made a 1997 speech in [[The House of Lords]] where he stated that since the 1971 Nixon Shock, the British [[money supply]] had grown by  2145% and personal debt had risen by almost 3000%. He argued that Britain ought to move from its current \"debt-based monetary system\" to one based on equity:<ref>{{cite web\n|url= http://prosperityuk.com/2001/06/our-debt-based-money-system-will-break-us/\n|title=Our Debt-Based Money System Will Break Us\n|work= Prosperity UK\n|author= Malcolm Sinclair, 20th Earl of Caithness\n|date = 1997-03-05\n|accessdate=2012-07-12|author-link=Malcolm Sinclair, 20th Earl of Caithness\n}}\n</ref>\n\n{{quote|It is also a good time to stand back, to reassess whether our economy is soundly based. I would contest that it is not ... as it is debt-based ... a system which by its very actions causes the value of money to decrease is dishonest and has within it its own seeds of destruction. We did not vote for it. It grew upon us gradually but markedly since 1971 when the commodity-based system was abandoned...We all want our businesses to succeed, but under the existing system the irony is that the better our banks, building societies and lending institutions do, the more debt is created ... There is a different way: it is an equity-based system and one in which those businesses can play a responsible role. The next government must grasp the nettle, accept their responsibility for controlling the money supply and change from our debt-based monetary system. My Lords, will they? If they do not, our monetary system will break us and the sorry legacy we are already leaving our children will be a disaster.}}\n\nIn the early to mid-1970s, a return to a gold-anchored system was advocated by gold-rich creditor countries including France and Germany.<ref name = \"Eric\">{{cite book \n|last=Helleiner \n|first=Eric\n|title=States and the Reemergence of Global Finance: From Bretton Woods to the 1990s\n|year=1995\n|isbn=0-8014-8333-6  \n|publisher= [[Cornell University Press]]\n}}</ref>\nA return has repeatedly been advocated by libertarians, as they tend to see commodity money as far preferable to [[fiat money]]. Since the 2008 crisis and the rapid rise in the price of gold that soon followed it, a return to a gold standard has frequently been advocated by [[gold|goldbugs]].<ref name = \"Promises\"/><ref name = \"Izabella\">{{Cite web\n|url= http://ftalphaville.ft.com/blog/2012/05/31/1023571/debunking-goldbugs/\n|title= Debunking goldbugs\n|publisher= [[The Financial Times]]\n|author=  Izabella Kaminska\n|date = 31 May 2012\n|accessdate= 16 July 2012}}\n</ref>\n\n===Advocacy against the gold standard===\nFrom centrist<ref>During the two centuries leading up to WWII, it was mostly only those who leaned towards the left who opposed the Gold Standard, but this has since became a centrist position.</ref> and left-wing perspectives, credit theories of money have been used to oppose the gold standard while it was still in effect, and to reject arguments for its reinstatement. Innes's 1914 paper is an early example of this.<ref name = \"Wray\"/><ref name = \"Promises\"/><ref name = \"Izabella\"/>\n\n===Advocacy for expansionary monetary policy===\nFrom a moderate mainstream perspective,  [[Martin Wolf]] has argued that since most money in our contemporary system is already being dual-created with debt by private banks, there is no reason to oppose monetary creation by [[central bank]]s in order to support monetary policy such as [[quantitative easing]]. In Wolf's view, the argument against Q.E. on the grounds that it creates debt is offset by potential benefits to economic growth and employment, and because the increase in debt would be temporary and easy to reverse.<ref>{{Cite web\n|url= http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/93c4e11e-ec39-11df-9e11-00144feab49a.html\n|title= The Fed is right to turn on the tap\n|publisher= [[The Financial Times]]\n|author=  Martin Wolf\n|date = 9 Nov 2010\n|accessdate= 16 July 2012|author-link= Martin Wolf\n}}\n</ref>\n\n===Advocacy for debt cancellation===\nArguments for [[debt forgiveness]]  have long been made from people of all political orientations; as an example, in 2010 hedge fund manager [[Hugh Hendry]], a strong believer in [[free market]]s, argued for a partial cancellation of Greece's debt as part of the solution to the [[Euro crisis]].<ref>{{Cite web\n|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/watch-hedge-funder-hugh-hendry-say-he-wants-the-euro-and-greece-to-tumble-fight-with-joe-stiglitz-2010-2\n|title=  Watch Hedge Funder Hugh Hendry Fight WIth Joe Stiglitz\n|publisher= [[Business Insider]]\n|author = Courtney Comstock\n|date=2010-02-10\n|accessdate=2012-07-18\n}}\n</ref> But generally advocates of debt forgiveness simply point out that debts are too high in relation to the debtors\u2019 ability to repay; they don't make reference to a debt-based theory of money. Exceptions include [[David Graeber]], who from a radical perspective, has used credit theories of money to argue against recent trends to strengthen the enforcement of debt collection, such as greater use of custodial sentences against debtors in the US. He also argued against the over-zealous application of the view that paying one\u2019s debts is central to morality, and has proposed the enactment of a biblical style [[Jubilee (biblical)|Jubilee]] where debts will be cancelled for all.<ref name = \"Graeber\"/>\n\n=== Advocacy for full-reserve banking ===\n{{main|Monetary reform}}\nThe 2008 financial crisis has led to renewed interest in full reserve banking and [[sovereign money]] issued by a [[central bank]]. Monetary reformers point out that [[fractional reserve banking]] and debt-based money lead to unpayable debt, growing [[economic inequality|inequality]], inevitable [[bankruptcy|bankruptcies]], and an imperative for perpetual and [[Sustainability|unsustainable]] [[economic growth]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Jackson |first1=Andrew |last2=Dyson |first2=Ben |title=Modernizing Money. Why our Monetary System is Broken and how it can be Fixed |date=2012 |publisher=Positive Money |isbn=978-0-9574448-0-5}}</ref>\n\n=== Advocacy for the ongoing establishment of new community banks ===\n[[Richard Werner|Werner]] argues that the knowledge and understanding of banks as creators and allocators of the money supply should be harnessed to benefit humanity in general and ordinary people in particular - instead of abolishing this power, as the 'monetary reform' movement demands. According to Werner this can be done by establishing hundreds of not-for-profit community banks, modelled on Germany's local co-operative banks, Raiffeisenbanks and Sparkasse savings banks. These banks have been one of the drivers of the striking success for [[Mittelstand|German small firms]] over the past two centuries in delivering job creation, strong exports and constantly upgraded technology. Werner says that instead of further centralising the power of money creation in the hands of ever fewer people, as monetary reformers and central planners demand, this public privilege should be returned \"to the people to whom it belongs\", and this can only be done in a meaningful way with sufficient accountability by copying the traditional German community banks. <ref>Richard A. Werner (2018), Shifting from central planning to a decentralised economy, www.professorwerner.org [https://professorwerner.org/shifting-from-central-planning-to-a-decentralised-economy/] see also Local First Community Interest Company and their movement to establish community banks [https://www.local-first.org.uk] </ref>\n\n==Relationship with other theories of money==\nDebt theories of money fall into a broader category of work which postulates that [[Endogenous money|monetary creation is endogenous]].<ref name = \"Wray\"/><ref>Simply put, this contrasts with exogenous creation where money is created by events such as new finds of gold occurring outside of a narrowly conceived economy.</ref>\n\nHistorically,  debt theories of money have overlapped with [[chartalism]] and were opposed to [[metallism]].<ref>In the 19th century, and to an extent the early 20th century, metallism enjoyed an almost \"unchallenged\" position as the dominant theory of money \u2013 see for example Chapter 1 of Schumpeter's ''History of Economic Analysis''</ref>  This largely remains the case today, especially in the forms commonly held by those to the left of the [[left-right politics|political spectrum]].<ref>Chartalists will sometimes say money derives it value by virtue of being the legal way to pay ones debt to the State as taxes. Debt theories can be broader in scope \u2013 Graeber, Innes and others have argued that organic debt based monetary systems that did not involve the state continued to operate well into the 19th century.</ref>  Conversely, in the forms held by late 20th-century and 21st-century advocates with a [[right-libertarianism|conservative libertarian]] perspective, debt theories of money are often compatible with the [[quantity theory of money]] and with metallism, at least when the latter is broadly understood.<ref name = \"Wray\"/><ref name = \"Graeber\"/><ref name = \"Promises\"/><ref name = \"CvM\">\n{{cite book \n|editor = Stephanie A. Bell and Edward J. Nell\n|title=The State, the Market, and the Euro: Chartalism Versus Metallism in the theory of money\n|chapter=  ''Passim''\n|year=2003\n|isbn=1843761564\n|publisher= Edward Elgar \n}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Cols}}\n* [[Demand Note]]\n* [[Jubilee Debt Coalition]]\n* [[Trillion-dollar coin]]\n{{Colend}}\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book | title=Where Does Money Come From?: A Guide to the UK Monetary & Banking System| last1=Ryan-Collins | first1= Josh |  last2= Werner| first2= Richard | last3=Jackson | first3= Andrew |year=2014 |publisher =New Economics Foundation |  isbn =978-1908506542 | pages = }}\n\n[[Category:Credit]]\n[[Category:Monetary economics]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Economic theory concerning the relationship between credit and money.}}\n[[File:SAM PC 1 - Tally sticks 1 - Overview.jpg|thumb|Single and split tally sticks in the [[Swiss Alpine Museum]] \u2013 similar items may have been used in debt based economic systems thought to pre-date the use of coinage.]]\n'''Credit theories of money''', also called '''debt theories of money''',  are [[monetary economics|monetary economic]] theories concerning the relationship between [[Credit (finance)|credit]] and [[money]]. Proponents of these theories, such as [[Alfred Mitchell-Innes]], sometimes emphasize that money and credit/[[debt]] are the same thing, seen from different points of view.<ref>As [[Alfred Mitchell-Innes|Innes]] mentions in ''What is money?'' (1913), whenever he uses the word ''credit'' or ''debt'', \"the thing spoken of is precisely the same in both cases, the one or the other word being used according as the situation is being looked at from the point of view of the creditor or of the debtor.\"</ref> Proponents assert that the essential nature of money is credit (debt), at least in eras where money is not backed by a commodity such as gold.  Two common strands of thought within these theories are the idea that money originated as a unit of account for debt, and the position that [[money creation]] involves the simultaneous creation of debt. Some proponents of credit theories of money argue that money is best understood as debt even in systems often understood as using [[commodity money]]. Others hold that money equates to credit only in a system based on [[fiat money]], where they argue that all forms of money including cash can be considered as forms of credit money.\n\nThe first formal credit theory of money arose in the 19th century. Anthropologist [[David Graeber]] has argued that for most of human history, money has been widely understood to represent debt, though he concedes that even prior to the [[Modern history|modern era]], there have been several periods where rival theories like [[metallism]] have held sway.\n\n==Scholarship==\nAccording to [[Joseph Schumpeter]], the first known advocate of a credit theory of money was [[Plato]].  Schumpeter describes [[metallism]]  as the other of \"two fundamental theories of money\", saying the first known advocate of metallism was [[Aristotle]].<ref>Chpt 1 Graeco-Roman Economics , 'History of Economic Analysis'',  [[Joseph Schumpeter]] , (1954)</ref><ref>{{Cite web\n|url= https://www.mtholyoke.edu/courses/fmoseley/conference/nelson1.pdf\n|title= Marx's objections to credit theories of money (extract from Nelson's 1999 book: ''Marx's concept of Money'' )\n|publisher= [[Mount Holyoke College]]\n|author= Anitra Nelson\n|accessdate=2013-07-08}}\n</ref> The earliest modern thinker to formulate a credit theory of money was [[Henry Dunning Macleod]] (1821-1902), with his work in the 19th century, most especially with his ''The Theory of Credit'' (1889). \nMacleod's work was expanded on by [[Alfred Mitchell-Innes]] in his papers ''What is Money?'' (1913) and ''The Credit Theory of Money'' (1914),<ref>Originally published in ''The Banking Law Journal'', since reprinted in books such as Wray (2004) and made available online by the [[Community Exchange System|CES]]</ref> where he argued against the then conventional view of money arising as a means to improve the practice of barter.  In this alternative view, [[commerce]] and [[taxation]] created obligations between parties which were forms of [[credit (finance)|credit]] and debt. Devices such as [[tally stick]]s were used to record these obligations and these then became [[negotiable instrument]]s which could function as money.  As Innes puts it in his 1914 article:\n\n{{quote|The Credit Theory is this: that a sale and purchase is the exchange of a commodity for credit. From this main theory springs the sub-theory that the value of credit or money does not depend on the value of any metal or metals, but on the right which the creditor acquires to \"payment,\" that is to say, to satisfaction for the credit, and on the obligation of the debtor to \"pay\" his debt and conversely on the right of the debtor to release himself from his debt by the tender of an equivalent debt owed by the creditor, and the obligation of the creditor to accept this tender in satisfaction of his credit. }}\n\nInnes goes on to note that a major problem in getting the public to understand the extent to which monetary systems are debt based is the challenge in persuading them that  \"things are not the way they seem\".<ref name = \"Wray\">\n{{cite book \n|editor = Randy Wray \n|title=Credit & State Theories of Money \n|chapter= See esp Chpt 1 7 \n|year=2004\n|isbn=1843765136 \n|publisher= Edward Elgar \n}}</ref>\n\nA Quantity Theory of Credit was proposed in 1992 by [[Richard Werner]], whereby credit creation is disaggregated into credit for GDP and non-GDP (financial circulation). The approach is tested empirically in a general-to-specific econometric time series model and found to be superior to alternative and traditional theories. According to Werner bank credit creation for GDP transactions [[Granger causality|Granger-causes]] nominal GDP growth, while credit creation for financial transactions explains asset prices and banking crises.<ref name = \"Werner\">Richard A. Werner, 1993, Towards a Quantity Theorem of Disaggregated Credit and International Capital Flows, with Evidence from Japan, paper presented at the Royal Economic Society Annual Conference in York in April 1993, and the 5th Annual PACAP Conference on Pacific-Asian Capital Markets in Kuala Lumpur, June 1993 and published later as Richard A. Werner, 1997, Towards a New Monetary Paradigm: A Quantity Theorem of Disaggregated Credit, with Evidence from Japan, Kredit und Kapital, 30, 2, pp. 276-309. Available at http://eprints.soton.ac.uk/36569/. See also http://www.kredit-und-kapital.de/archiv/1997-2.html#r1 and Werner, Richard A. (2012). Towards a New Research Programme on \u2018Banking and the Economy\u2019 \u2013 Implications of the Quantity Theory of Credit for the Prevention and Resolution of Banking and Debt Crises, International Review of Financial Analysis, 25, 94-105, [http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1057521912000555] </ref> Based on this, Werner (2005) developed a new approach to macroeconomics, which integrates the nature of banks as money creators in macroeconomics - usually ignored in conventional macroeconomics.<ref>Richard A. Werner, 2005, New Paradigm in Macroeconomics, Palgrave Macmillan.</ref> Werner's approach is based on the scientific research methodology (the inductive method), not the axiomatic-hypothetical deductive approach commonly used in macroeconomics, which assumes away the existence of banks or market rationing. Hence in his approach markets are not expected to be in equilibrium, but the short side principle applies, which emphasises the power of banks in making decisions about the amount and allocation of credit created and distributed in the economy. Werner used the Quantity Theory of Credit (also known as the Quantity Theory of Disaggregated Credit) to develop a new monetary policy for post-crisis banking systems, which he called 'Quantitative Easing' (Werner, 1995, published in the Japanese financial newspaper, the Nikkei), a name later adopted by the Bank of Japan and Bank of England for related policies <ref> Richard A. Werner (1995), Keiki kaifuku, ry\u014dteki kiny\u016b kanwa kara, (How to Create a Recovery through \u2018Quantitative Monetary Easing\u2019), The Nihon Keizai Shinbun (Nikkei), \u2018Keizai Ky\u014dshitsu\u2019 (\u2018Economics Classroom\u2019), 2 September 1995 (morning edition), p. 26; English translation by T. John Cooke (November 2011)[http://eprints.soton.ac.uk/340476/]</ref>. The role of banks as creators of both the credit and the money supply has since been empirically demonstrated by Werner in widely-noted finance journal publications.<ref> Werner, Richard A. (2016), A lost century in Economics: Three theories of banking and the conclusive evidence, International Review of Financial Analysis, 46, July, 361\u2013379, online: [http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1057521915001477]  and Werner, Richard A.  (2014). Can Banks Individually Create Money Out of Nothing? \u2013 The Theories and the Empirical Evidence, International Review of Financial Analysis, 36, 1-19, [http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1057521914001070] </ref>\n\nSince the late 20th century, Innes' credit theory of money has been integrated into [[Modern Monetary Theory]]. The theory also combines elements of [[chartalism]], noting that [[high powered money]] is functionally an [[IOU]] from the state,<ref name=\"mmt\">{{citation|first1=Scott |last1= Fullwiler| first2=Stephanie |last2= Kelton | first3=L. Randall | last3= Wray |contribution = Modern Money Theory : A Response to Critics|title= Working Paper Series: Modern Monetary Theory - A Debate| pages=17\u201326|publisher = [[Political Economy Research Institute]] |location=Amherst, MA |number = 279 | date = January 2012 | accessdate= May 26, 2019| url= http://www.peri.umass.edu/fileadmin/pdf/working_papers/working_papers_251-300/WP279.pdf }}</ref> and therefore, \"all 'state money' is also 'credit money'\". The state ensures there is demand for its IOUs by accepting them as payment for taxes, fees, fines, tithes, and tribute.<ref name=\"MMTreply\">\u00c9ric Tymoigne and L. Randall Wray, [http://www.levyinstitute.org/pubs/wp_778.pdf \"Modern Money Theory 101: A Reply to Critics,\"] Levy Economics Institute of Bard College, Working Paper No. 778 (November 2013).</ref>\n\nIn his 2011 book ''[[Debt: The First 5000 Years]]'', the anthropologist [[David Graeber]] asserted that the best available evidence suggests the original monetary systems were debt based, and that most subsequent systems have been too. Exceptions where the relationship between money and debt was less clear occurred during periods where money has been backed by [[bullion]], as happens with a [[gold standard]]. Graeber echoes earlier theorists such as Innes by saying that during these eras population perception was that money derived its value from the precious metals of which the coins were made,<ref>This is the classic [[Metallism|Metallist]] view.</ref> but that even in these periods money is more accurately understood as debt. Graeber states that the three main functions of money are to act as: a  [[medium of exchange]]; a [[unit of account]]; and a [[store of value]]. Graeber writes that since [[Adam Smith]]'s time, economists have tended to emphasise money as a ''medium of exchange''.<ref>Polanyi goes as far as to say [[David Ricardo|Ricardo]] \"indoctrinated\" economists into viewing money just as a  ''medium of exchange'' - see chapter 16 of [[The Great Transformation (book)|The Great Transformation]].</ref> For Graeber, when money first appeared its primary purpose was to act as a ''unit of account'', to denominate debt. He writes that coins were originally created as [[token coin|tokens]] which represented a unit of account rather than being an amount of [[precious metal]] which could be bartered.<ref name = \"Graeber\">{{citation|title=Debt: The First 5000 Years |chapter= ''passim'', see especially chapter 2: The Myth of Barter |author=David Graeber |year=2011 |isbn=978-1-61219-181-2|title-link= Debt: The First 5000 Years }}</ref>\n\nEconomics commentator Philip Coggan holds that the world's current monetary system became debt-based after the [[Nixon Shock]], in which President Nixon suspended the link between money and [[gold]] in 1971. He writes that \"Modern money is debt and debt is money\".  Since the 1971 Nixon Shock, debt creation  and [[money creation|the creation of money]] increasingly took place at once. This simultaneous creation of money and debt occurs as a feature of [[fractional reserve banking]]. After a commercial bank approves a loan, it is able to create the corresponding amount of money, which is then acquired by the borrower along with a similar amount of debt.<ref>The new debt will generally soon exceed the newly created money due to added interest.</ref> \nCoggan goes on to say that debtors often prefer debt-based monetary systems such as [[fiat money]] over commodity-based systems like the gold standard, because the former tend to allow much higher volumes of money to circulate in the economy, and tend to be more expansive. This makes their debts easier to repay. Coggan refers to [[William Jennings Bryan]]'s 19th century [[Cross of Gold speech]] as one of the first great attempts to weaken the link between gold and money; he says the former US presidential candidate was trying to expand the [[monetary base]] in the interests of indebted farmers, who at the time were often being forced into bankruptcy.  However Coggan also says that the excessive debt which can be built up under a debt-based monetary system can end up hurting all sections of society, including debtors.<ref name = \"Promises\">\n{{cite book |author             = Philip Coggan\n |title              = Paper Promises: Money, Debt and the New World Order\n |chapter            = ''passim'', see esp Introduction\n |year               = 2011\n |isbn               = 978-1846145100\n |publisher          = Allen Lane\n |chapter-url-access = registration\n |chapter-url        = https://archive.org/details/paperpromisesmon0000cogg_z0h5\n |url-access         = registration\n |url                = https://archive.org/details/paperpromisesmon0000cogg_z0h5\n}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2012 paper, economic theorist [[Perry Mehrling]] notes that what is commonly regarded as money can often be viewed as debt.  He posits a hierarchy of assets with gold<ref>In the Financial sector, gold is often said to be the only financial asset that does not represent someone else's liability to pay.</ref> at the top, then [[currency]], then [[deposits]] and then [[securities]]. The lower down the hierarchy, the easier it is to view the asset as reflecting someone else's debt.<ref>{{cite web\n|url= http://www.ieor.columbia.edu/pdf-files/Mehrling_P_FESeminar_Sp12-02.pdf\n|archive-url= https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20121221064955/http://www.ieor.columbia.edu/pdf-files/Mehrling_P_FESeminar_Sp12-02.pdf\n|url-status= dead\n|archive-date= 2012-12-21\n|title= The Inherent Hierarchy of Money\n|work= [[Columbia University]]\n|author= Perry Mehrling\n|date= 2012-01-25\n|accessdate= 2012-07-10\n|author-link= Perry Mehrling\n}}</ref>\nA later 2012 paper from Claudio Borio of the [[Bank for International Settlements|BIS]] made the contrary case that it is loans that give rise to deposits, rather than the other way round.<ref>\"[http://www.bis.org/publ/work395.pdf The financial cycle and macroeconomics: What have we learnt?]\", by Claudio Borio, [[Bank for International Settlements]]  December 2012</ref>\n\nIn a book published in June 2013, the writer Felix Martin, influenced by Werner (2003, 2005), argued that credit based theories of money are correct, citing many of Werner's sources, such as Macleod:  \"currency ... represents transferable debt, and nothing else\". Martin writes that it is difficult for people to grasp the nature of money, because money is such a central part of society, and alludes to the Chinese proverb that \"If you want to know what water is like, don't ask the fish.\"<ref>Richard A. Werner (2003), Princes of the Yen, 2nd edition by Quantum Publishers [www.quantumpublishers.com]</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=Felix Martin|title=Money: The Unauthorized Biography|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1Su0AAAAQBAJ|date=4 March 2014|publisher=Knopf Doubleday Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-307-96244-7}} Chapter 1</ref><ref> \n{{Cite web\n|url= https://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/jun/09/money-biography-felix-martin-review\n|title= Money: The Unauthorised Biography by Felix Martin \u2013 review\n|publisher= [[The Guardian]]\n|author= Ian Birrell\n|date = 2013-06-09\n|accessdate=2013-07-08}}\n</ref>\n\n==Advocacy==\nThe conception that money is essentially equivalent to credit or debt has long been used by those advocating particular reforms of the monetary system, and by commentators calling for various [[monetary policy]] responses to events such as the [[financial crisis of 2007\u20132008]].  A view held in common by most recent advocates, from all shades of political opinion, is that money can be equated with debt in the context of the contemporary monetary system.  The view that money is equivalent to debt even in systems based on [[commodity money]] tends to be held only by those to the left of the political spectrum. Regardless of any commonality in their understanding of credit theories of money, the actual reforms proposed by advocates of different political orientations are sometimes diametrically opposed.<ref name = \"Promises\"/>\n\n===Advocacy for a return to a gold standard or similar commodity based system.===\n[[File:Ronpaul1.jpg|thumb|250px|Former US presidential candidate [[Ron Paul]] has spoken out against ''fiat money'', partly on the grounds that it encourages the buildup of debt.<ref>{{Cite web\n|url=http://archive.lewrockwell.com/paul/paul125.html\n|title= Fiat Paper Money\n|publisher=LewRockwell.com\n|author=  Ron Paul\n|date = 12 Sep 2003\n|accessdate= 16 July 2012|author-link= Ron Paul\n}}\n</ref>\n]]\n\nAdvocates from an [[Austrian School]], [[right-libertarianism|right-libertarian]] perspective often hold that money is equivalent to debt in our current  monetary system, but that it need not be in one where money has inherent value, such as a [[gold standard]]. They have frequently used this view point to support arguments that it would be best to return to a gold standard, to other forms of commodity money, or at least to a monetary system where money has positive value. Similar views are also occasionally expressed by [[conservatives]]. As an example of the latter, former British minister of state  [[Malcolm Sinclair, 20th Earl of Caithness|The Earl of Caithness]] made a 1997 speech in [[The House of Lords]] where he stated that since the 1971 Nixon Shock, the British [[money supply]] had grown by  2145% and personal debt had risen by almost 3000%. He argued that Britain ought to move from its current \"debt-based monetary system\" to one based on equity:<ref>{{cite web\n|url= http://prosperityuk.com/2001/06/our-debt-based-money-system-will-break-us/\n|title=Our Debt-Based Money System Will Break Us\n|work= Prosperity UK\n|author= Malcolm Sinclair, 20th Earl of Caithness\n|date = 1997-03-05\n|accessdate=2012-07-12|author-link=Malcolm Sinclair, 20th Earl of Caithness\n}}\n</ref>\n\n{{quote|It is also a good time to stand back, to reassess whether our economy is soundly based. I would contest that it is not ... as it is debt-based ... a system which by its very actions causes the value of money to decrease is dishonest and has within it its own seeds of destruction. We did not vote for it. It grew upon us gradually but markedly since 1971 when the commodity-based system was abandoned...We all want our businesses to succeed, but under the existing system the irony is that the better our banks, building societies and lending institutions do, the more debt is created ... There is a different way: it is an equity-based system and one in which those businesses can play a responsible role. The next government must grasp the nettle, accept their responsibility for controlling the money supply and change from our debt-based monetary system. My Lords, will they? If they do not, our monetary system will break us and the sorry legacy we are already leaving our children will be a disaster.}}\n\nIn the early to mid-1970s, a return to a gold-anchored system was advocated by gold-rich creditor countries including France and Germany.<ref name = \"Eric\">{{cite book \n|last=Helleiner \n|first=Eric\n|title=States and the Reemergence of Global Finance: From Bretton Woods to the 1990s\n|year=1995\n|isbn=0-8014-8333-6  \n|publisher= [[Cornell University Press]]\n}}</ref>\nA return has repeatedly been advocated by libertarians, as they tend to see commodity money as far preferable to [[fiat money]]. Since the 2008 crisis and the rapid rise in the price of gold that soon followed it, a return to a gold standard has frequently been advocated by [[gold|goldbugs]].<ref name = \"Promises\"/><ref name = \"Izabella\">{{Cite web\n|url= http://ftalphaville.ft.com/blog/2012/05/31/1023571/debunking-goldbugs/\n|title= Debunking goldbugs\n|publisher= [[The Financial Times]]\n|author=  Izabella Kaminska\n|date = 31 May 2012\n|accessdate= 16 July 2012}}\n</ref>\n\n===Advocacy against the gold standard===\nFrom centrist<ref>During the two centuries leading up to WWII, it was mostly only those who leaned towards the left who opposed the Gold Standard, but this has since became a centrist position.</ref> and left-wing perspectives, credit theories of money have been used to oppose the gold standard while it was still in effect, and to reject arguments for its reinstatement. Innes's 1914 paper is an early example of this.<ref name = \"Wray\"/><ref name = \"Promises\"/><ref name = \"Izabella\"/>\n\n===Advocacy for expansionary monetary policy===\nFrom a moderate mainstream perspective,  [[Martin Wolf]] has argued that since most money in our contemporary system is already being dual-created with debt by private banks, there is no reason to oppose monetary creation by [[central bank]]s in order to support monetary policy such as [[quantitative easing]]. In Wolf's view, the argument against Q.E. on the grounds that it creates debt is offset by potential benefits to economic growth and employment, and because the increase in debt would be temporary and easy to reverse.<ref>{{Cite web\n|url= http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/93c4e11e-ec39-11df-9e11-00144feab49a.html\n|title= The Fed is right to turn on the tap\n|publisher= [[The Financial Times]]\n|author=  Martin Wolf\n|date = 9 Nov 2010\n|accessdate= 16 July 2012|author-link= Martin Wolf\n}}\n</ref>\n\n===Advocacy for debt cancellation===\nArguments for [[debt forgiveness]]  have long been made from people of all political orientations; as an example, in 2010 hedge fund manager [[Hugh Hendry]], a strong believer in [[free market]]s, argued for a partial cancellation of Greece's debt as part of the solution to the [[Euro crisis]].<ref>{{Cite web\n|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/watch-hedge-funder-hugh-hendry-say-he-wants-the-euro-and-greece-to-tumble-fight-with-joe-stiglitz-2010-2\n|title=  Watch Hedge Funder Hugh Hendry Fight WIth Joe Stiglitz\n|publisher= [[Business Insider]]\n|author = Courtney Comstock\n|date=2010-02-10\n|accessdate=2012-07-18\n}}\n</ref> But generally advocates of debt forgiveness simply point out that debts are too high in relation to the debtors\u2019 ability to repay; they don't make reference to a debt-based theory of money. Exceptions include David Graeber, who from a radical perspective, has used credit theories of money to argue against recent trends to strengthen the enforcement of debt collection, such as greater use of custodial sentences against debtors in the US. He also argued against the over-zealous application of the view that paying one\u2019s debts is central to morality, and has proposed the enactment of a biblical style [[Jubilee (biblical)|Jubilee]] where debts will be cancelled for all.<ref name = \"Graeber\"/>\n\n=== Advocacy for full-reserve banking ===\n{{main|Monetary reform}}\nThe 2008 financial crisis has led to renewed interest in full reserve banking and [[sovereign money]] issued by a [[central bank]]. Monetary reformers point out that [[fractional reserve banking]] and debt-based money lead to unpayable debt, growing [[economic inequality|inequality]], inevitable [[bankruptcy|bankruptcies]], and an imperative for perpetual and [[Sustainability|unsustainable]] [[economic growth]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Jackson |first1=Andrew |last2=Dyson |first2=Ben |title=Modernizing Money. Why our Monetary System is Broken and how it can be Fixed |date=2012 |publisher=Positive Money |isbn=978-0-9574448-0-5}}</ref>\n\n=== Advocacy for the ongoing establishment of new community banks ===\n[[Richard Werner|Werner]] argues that the knowledge and understanding of banks as creators and allocators of the money supply should be harnessed to benefit humanity in general and ordinary people in particular - instead of abolishing this power, as the 'monetary reform' movement demands. According to Werner this can be done by establishing hundreds of not-for-profit community banks, modelled on Germany's local co-operative banks, Raiffeisenbanks and Sparkasse savings banks. These banks have been one of the drivers of the striking success for [[Mittelstand|German small firms]] over the past two centuries in delivering job creation, strong exports and constantly upgraded technology. Werner says that instead of further centralising the power of money creation in the hands of ever fewer people, as monetary reformers and central planners demand, this public privilege should be returned \"to the people to whom it belongs\", and this can only be done in a meaningful way with sufficient accountability by copying the traditional German community banks. <ref>Richard A. Werner (2018), Shifting from central planning to a decentralised economy, www.professorwerner.org [https://professorwerner.org/shifting-from-central-planning-to-a-decentralised-economy/] see also Local First Community Interest Company and their movement to establish community banks [https://www.local-first.org.uk] </ref>\n\n==Relationship with other theories of money==\nDebt theories of money fall into a broader category of work which postulates that [[Endogenous money|monetary creation is endogenous]].<ref name = \"Wray\"/><ref>Simply put, this contrasts with exogenous creation where money is created by events such as new finds of gold occurring outside of a narrowly conceived economy.</ref>\n\nHistorically,  debt theories of money have overlapped with [[chartalism]] and were opposed to [[metallism]].<ref>In the 19th century, and to an extent the early 20th century, metallism enjoyed an almost \"unchallenged\" position as the dominant theory of money \u2013 see for example Chapter 1 of Schumpeter's ''History of Economic Analysis''</ref>  This largely remains the case today, especially in the forms commonly held by those to the left of the [[left-right politics|political spectrum]].<ref>Chartalists will sometimes say money derives it value by virtue of being the legal way to pay ones debt to the State as taxes. Debt theories can be broader in scope \u2013 Graeber, Innes and others have argued that organic debt based monetary systems that did not involve the state continued to operate well into the 19th century.</ref>  Conversely, in the forms held by late 20th-century and 21st-century advocates with a [[right-libertarianism|conservative libertarian]] perspective, debt theories of money are often compatible with the [[quantity theory of money]] and with metallism, at least when the latter is broadly understood.<ref name = \"Wray\"/><ref name = \"Graeber\"/><ref name = \"Promises\"/><ref name = \"CvM\">\n{{cite book \n|editor = Stephanie A. Bell and Edward J. Nell\n|title=The State, the Market, and the Euro: Chartalism Versus Metallism in the theory of money\n|chapter=  ''Passim''\n|year=2003\n|isbn=1843761564\n|publisher= Edward Elgar \n}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Cols}}\n* [[Demand Note]]\n* [[Jubilee Debt Coalition]]\n* [[Trillion-dollar coin]]\n{{Colend}}\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book | title=Where Does Money Come From?: A Guide to the UK Monetary & Banking System| last1=Ryan-Collins | first1= Josh |  last2= Werner| first2= Richard | last3=Jackson | first3= Andrew |year=2014 |publisher =New Economics Foundation |  isbn =978-1908506542 | pages = }}\n\n[[Category:Credit]]\n[[Category:Monetary economics]]\n", "name_user": "Chowasekai", "label": "safe", "comment": "Linked author to his comment", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Credit_theory_of_money"}
{"title_page": "Stephen Dorrell", "text_new": "{{short description|British Liberal Democrat politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name             = Stephen Dorrell\n|image            = Stephen dorrell mp -nhs confederation annual conferencepercent2c manchester-11july2011 - crop.jpg\n|office1          = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Education|Shadow Secretary of State for Education and Employment]]\n|leader1          = [[William Hague]]\n|term_start1      = 11 June 1997\n|term_end1        = 2 June 1998\n|predecessor1     = [[Gillian Shephard]]\n|successor1       = [[David Willetts]]\n|office2          = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Health]]\n|leader2          = [[John Major]]\n|term_start2      = 2 May 1997\n|term_end2        = 11 June 1997\n|predecessor2     = [[Chris Smith, Baron Smith of Finsbury|Chris Smith]]\n|successor2       = [[John Maples]]\n|office3          = [[Secretary of State for Health]]\n|primeminister3   = [[John Major]]\n|term_start3      = 5 July 1995\n|term_end3        = 2 May 1997\n|predecessor3     = [[Virginia Bottomley]]\n|successor3       = [[Frank Dobson]]\n|office4          = [[Secretary of State for National Heritage]]\n|primeminister4   = [[John Major]]\n|term_start4      = 20 July 1994\n|term_end4        = 5 July 1995\n|predecessor4     = [[Peter Brooke]]\n|successor4       = [[Virginia Bottomley]]\n|office5          = [[Financial Secretary to the Treasury]]\n|primeminister5   = [[John Major]]\n|term_start5      = 11 April 1992\n|term_end5        = 11 July 1994\n|predecessor5     = [[Francis Maude]]\n|successor5       = [[George Young, Baron Young of Cookham|George Young]]\n|office6 = [[Lord Commissioner of the Treasury]]\n|primeminister6 = [[Margaret Thatcher]]\n|predecessor6 = [[Tony Durant]]\n|successor6 = [[Michael Fallon]]\n|term_start6 = 20 December 1988\n|term_end6 = 3 May 1990\n|office7          = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br/>for [[Charnwood (UK Parliament constituency)|Charnwood]]\n|term_start7      = 1 May 1997\n|term_end7        = 30 March 2015\n|predecessor7     = Constituency established\n|successor7       = [[Edward Argar]]\n|office8          = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br/>for [[Loughborough (UK Parliament constituency)|Loughborough]]\n|term_start8      = 3 May 1979\n|term_end8        = 8 April 1997\n|predecessor8     = [[John Desmond Cronin|John Cronin]]\n|successor8       = [[Andy Reed (politician)|Andy Reed]]\n|birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1952|3|25|df=y}}\n|birth_place      = [[Worcester]], [[England]]\n|death_date       = \n|death_place      = \n|party            = [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] (2019\u2013present)\n|otherparty       = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] (before 2019)<br>\n[[Change UK]] (2019)\n|spouse           = Penelope Taylor\n|alma_mater       = [[Brasenose College, Oxford]]\n|website          = [http://www.stephendorrell.org.uk Official website]\n}}\n\n'''Stephen James Dorrell''' (born 25 March 1952) is a British [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] politician. <ref name=persweb>{{cite web|url=http://www.stephendorrell.org.uk/person/rt-hon-stephen-dorrell-mp|title=Stephen Dorrell MP -official constituency website|accessdate=2 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021011753/http://www.stephendorrell.org.uk/person/rt-hon-stephen-dorrell-mp|archive-date=21 October 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> He served as the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Loughborough (UK Parliament constituency)|Loughborough]] between 1979 and 1997 and then for [[Charnwood (UK Parliament constituency)|Charnwood]] from 1997 to 2015.\n\nDorrell most recently served for four years as Chairman of the [[House of Commons (UK)|House of Commons]] [[Health Select Committee]] from 2010 to 2014. In the 1990s he was a full member of [[John Major]]'s [[Cabinet of the United Kingdom|Cabinet]] for almost three years, whilst serving as both [[Secretary of State for National Heritage]] and then [[Secretary of State for Health]] until the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]]. He was also a Patron of the [[Tory Reform Group]].\n\nSince 2014 he has been a consultant with the health and public service practice of [[KPMG]].\n\nIn the spring of 2019 he left the Conservative Party to join [[Change UK]] and was the lead candidate on the party's list in the [[West Midlands (European Parliament constituency)|West Midlands]] region at the [[2019 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|2019 European Parliament election]]. After failing to be elected, he defected to the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] and was the unsuccessful Liberal Democrat candidate for [[Buckingham (UK Parliament constituency)|Buckingham]] in the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]].\n\n==Early life and  education==\nDorrell was born in [[Worcester]] and educated at [[Uppingham School]], [[Rutland]] and [[Brasenose College, Oxford]], where he was awarded a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree. He was a member of the [[Royal Air Force Volunteer Reserve]] for two years from 1971.\n\n==Political career==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=October 2015}}\nDuring the [[February 1974 United Kingdom general election|February 1974 general election]], Dorrell acted as a personal assistant to Conservative minister [[Peter Walker, Baron Walker of Worcester|Peter Walker]]. Aged only 22, he contested the safe [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] seat of [[Kingston upon Hull East (UK Parliament constituency)|Kingston upon Hull East]] at the October 1974 general election, but was heavily defeated by the sitting MP (and later [[Deputy Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Deputy Prime Minister]]), [[John Prescott]], who was returned with a majority of 25,793 votes.\n\nAt the [[1979 United Kingdom general election|1979 general election]], the Conservatives were returned to office under the leadership of [[Margaret Thatcher]]. Dorrell, then 27, was elected to the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] for the marginal seat of [[Loughborough (UK Parliament constituency)|Loughborough]], ousting the veteran Labour MP [[John Desmond Cronin|John Cronin]] by 5,199 votes. He remained an MP until standing down from Parliament at the 2015 General Election.\n\nOn his election he was the ''[[Baby of the House of Commons]]'', an informal title for the youngest member.  He was succeeded as the ''Baby of the House'' on 9 April 1981 when [[Bobby Sands]] was elected at the [[April 1981 Fermanagh and South Tyrone by-election]]; however, Sands died on 5 May 1981 whilst on [[1981 Irish hunger strike|hunger strike]] in [[Maze (HM Prison)|Long Kesh Prison]]. Dorrell again became the ''Baby of the House'' until 20 August 1981, when Sands' successor [[Owen Carron]] was elected at the [[August 1981 Fermanagh and South Tyrone by-election]]. He nonetheless remained the youngest MP to take his seat in the House of Commons ([[Sinn Fein]] members do not take their seats) until the 1983 election, when [[Charles Kennedy]] succeeded him.\n\nFollowing his election to [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|parliament]] in 1979 he was a member of the [[Department for Transport|Transport]] [[Select committee (United Kingdom)|Select committee]]. After the [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983 general election]] he was appointed as the [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] to his old boss Peter Walker, who had now become the [[Secretary of State for Energy]].\n\n===In government===\nDorrell was promoted to government after the [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987 General Election]] by the [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] [[Margaret Thatcher]] as an [[Whip (politics)|Assistant Government Whip]], and in 1988 became a Lord Commissioner to the Treasury 'full whip'. He was appointed as the [[Parliamentary Under Secretary of State]] at the [[Department of Health (United Kingdom)|Department of Health]] in 1990 under the premiership of [[John Major]]. After the [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992 General Election]] he became the [[Secretary to the Treasury#Financial Secretaries of the Treasury, 1852-present|Financial Secretary to the Treasury]].\n\nDorrell was promoted to the Major [[Cabinet of the United Kingdom|Cabinet]] as the [[Secretary of State for National Heritage]] in 1994, and on appointment became a Member of the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Council]]. He  headhunted [[Jennifer Page (Millennium Dome)|Jennie Page]] for the job of [[Millennium Dome]] Chief Executive according to ''[[The Observer]]''.<ref name = \"domedreamsdashed\" >{{cite news|title=How Dome dreams were dashed|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2000/feb/06/millennium.uk|accessdate=31 July 2008|work=[[The Observer]]|first=Vanessa|last=Thorpe|date=5 February 2000|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130824035334/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2000/feb/06/millennium.uk|archive-date=24 August 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> He was transferred to become the [[Secretary of State for Health]] in 1995, and remained in position until the end of the Conservative administration at the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]].\n\nDorrell was often deployed in the media as a spokesman for the Major government, as it was felt he conveyed an air of approachability and popular appeal. During one party conference season in the late 1990s he was followed by a camera crew from the BBC's Breakfast show, capturing the behind-the-scenes build-up to his conference speech. The actual speech was also shown, including his joke (at the height of tensions in the Conservative party over Europe) that he considered himself a 'bureausceptic'. Unfortunately the joke, a reference to trying to reduce the level of [[red tape]] in the Health Service, fell on deaf ears.{{citation needed|date=October 2015}}\n\n===After government===\nWhen constituency boundaries were revised for the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 election]], he moved with his key rural voters into the new [[Charnwood (UK Parliament constituency)|Charnwood]] constituency. He won the seat comfortably with a majority of 5,900, although Loughborough was lost to [[Andy Reed (politician)|Andy Reed]] of Labour.{{citation needed|date=October 2015}}\n\nHe launched a bid for the leadership of the Conservative Party in 1997, but withdrew before the first ballot when it became clear his support amongst Conservative MPs was negligible. Instead he threw his support behind [[Kenneth Clarke]]'s bid. Under [[William Hague]] he became [[Shadow Cabinet|shadow]] [[Secretary of State for Education and Employment]], but left the shadow cabinet in 1998, and was a [[backbencher]] for the remainder of his parliamentary career.\n\n====Chairman of Health Select Committee and views on NHS reforms====\nIn June 2010, Dorrell was elected Chairman of the [[Health Select Committee]]. In June 2011, following concerns over the unpopularity of [[Andrew Lansley]]'s [[Health and Social Care Act 2012|NHS reforms]], Dorrell was tipped as a possible successor but stated that he wanted to continue as the committee chairman for the full parliament.<ref name=beebJH1>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-13712255|title=Stephen Dorrell rules out return as Health Secretary|author=John Hess|date=9 June 2011|work=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=1 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320044801/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-13712255|archive-date=20 March 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> An alternate view was that David Cameron would not want any more \"Tory retreads\" from previous governments.<ref name=beebJH1/> Dorrell acknowledged that resources would become tighter but changes driven by new medicines and new expectations were inevitable and integration of health care and social care would be both better and more efficient.<ref name=beebJH1/>\n\nInterviewed in 2012, Dorrell stated that the 4% per year for four years efficiency targets, agreed before the 2010 election and described as \"a huge challenge\", were taking too long to achieve.<ref name=beebNHS>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-16696197|title=Stephen Dorrell: NHS faces huge challenge|work=[[BBC News]]|date=24 January 2012|accessdate=1 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120409202249/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-16696197|archive-date=9 April 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> Whilst the bill had good points, e.g. involving clinicians and local authorities, more independence for public health etc. savings required a change in the way care is delivered not just changes in management structure.<ref name=beebNHS/> The reforms were acting as a \"disruption and distraction\".<ref name=beebNHS/>  They were a secondary issue compared with the need to make efficiency savings of \u00a320bn, he added.<ref name=gard>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/healthcare-network/2012/mar/02/nhs-reform-reality-stephen-dorrell|title=NHS reform debate has lost touch with reality, says Stephen Dorrell|author=Clare Horton|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=2 March 2012|accessdate=2 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160308223105/http://www.theguardian.com/healthcare-network/2012/mar/02/nhs-reform-reality-stephen-dorrell|archive-date=8 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDorrell resigned in June 2014 and was succeeded by [[Sarah Wollaston]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Dr Sarah Wollaston elected as health committee chairwoman|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-27911517|accessdate=14 July 2014|work=[[BBC News]]|date=18 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140701160020/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-27911517|archive-date=1 July 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Expenses investigation over \"secret flat rent deal\" with care home owners====\nIn November 2012 Dorrell was reported to the [[Independent Parliamentary Standards Authority]] (IPSA) after arranging to sell his London flat to \u201cfriends\u201d who owned a chain of nursing homes, subsequently renting it back at \u00a31,400 a month, funded by the taxpayer. His impartiality as chairman was questioned as the Health Select Committee was investigating social care, and some of the chain's nursing homes had been criticised by the [[Care Quality Commission]].  Committee members were not aware of the financial connection. [[David Cameron]] refused to get involved, saying it was a matter for IPSA. IPSA said that the rules banned MPs from renting from family members, not from friends.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/9694228/MPs-expenses-Stephen-Dorrell-MP-reported-to-sleaze-watchdog-over-secret-flat-rent-deal.html|title=MPs' expenses: Stephen Dorrell MP reported to sleaze watchdog over secret flat rent deal|author=Christopher Hope|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=21 November 2012|accessdate=24 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141025173926/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/9694228/MPs-expenses-Stephen-Dorrell-MP-reported-to-sleaze-watchdog-over-secret-flat-rent-deal.html|archive-date=25 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Standing down from Parliament===\nIn November 2014, he surprised local party members and staff by announcing his future retirement from the House to take a job with consultancy [[KPMG]] in \"a senior role supporting their health and public service practice...\". The role, he said, was \"incompatible with seeking re-election to the House of Commons\". Fellow Leicestershire Conservative MP [[Andrew Bridgen]] also expressed surprise, but said that the prestige of Parliament had fallen since the [[United Kingdom parliamentary expenses scandal|expenses scandal]], and a number of experienced MPs were leaving. Neighbouring Loughborough MP [[Nicky Morgan]] described him as \"a really important political figure in Leicestershire since 1979. He has been a great support to me\". She denied claims she would stand in Dorrell's Charnwood seat (rather than Loughborough) at the 2015 general election, saying that these were \"rumour-mongering\" by members of the Labour Party. (In May 2015 she held the Loughborough seat with an increased majority.)\n\nThe Labour candidate for Charnwood, Sean Kelly Walsh, paid tribute to Dorrell's long service and constituency work, as well as his roles as Secretary of State for Health and chairman of the Health Affairs Select Committee.<ref name=dan>{{cite news|url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Conservative-Charnwood-MP-Stephen-Dorrell/story-24673441-detail/story.html|title=Conservative Charnwood MP Stephen Dorrell quitting Parliament to join KPMG|work=Leicester Mercury|author=danjmartin|date=25 November 2014|access-date=26 November 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150219133226/http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Conservative-Charnwood-MP-Stephen-Dorrell/story-24673441-detail/story.html|archive-date=19 February 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Resignation call over conflict of interest===\nIn December 2014, Dorrell was criticised for alleged conflict of interest when it became clear that he would be working both as an MP and KPMG consultant for six months until the election, and that KPMG were considering bidding for a \u00a31 billion NHS contract. Pointing out that Dorrell had previously admitted the two roles were incompatible, Dr Clive Peedell, co-leader of the [[National Health Action Party]], called for him to resign from one of the posts. Dorrell responded saying no issues were raised as he was not seeking re-election.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/conservative/11264425/Stephen-Dorrell-MP-faces-calls-to-resign-over-conflict-of-interest.html|title=Stephen Dorrell MP faces calls to resign over conflict of interest|work=Daily Telegraph|date=1 December 2014|accessdate=4 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141203220517/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/conservative/11264425/Stephen-Dorrell-MP-faces-calls-to-resign-over-conflict-of-interest.html|archive-date=3 December 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2015, a group of six pensioners, who called at Dorrell's offices in [[Thurmaston]] to hand in a 2,286 signature petition calling on him to resign, were told they were trespassing and the police would be called. Hanif Asmal, Chairman of Charnwood Conservative Association claimed police were called as the group didn\u2019t have an appointment.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Police-called-deal-petitioning-pensioners-MP/story-25838352-detail/story.html|title=Police called to MP Stephen Dorrell's office to deal with petitioning pensioners|author=PA_Warzynski|work=Leicester Mercury|date=11 January 2015|access-date=17 January 2015|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150115064212/http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Police-called-deal-petitioning-pensioners-MP/story-25838352-detail/story.html|archive-date=15 January 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', Dorrell's extra-parliamentary work took up 1,736 hours, or 33.4 hours per week, in 2014.<ref name=lyn>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/investigations/11428075/The-MPs-who-topped-up-their-salaries-with-1600-an-hour-second-jobs.html|title=The MPs who topped up their salaries with \u00a31,600-an-hour second jobs|author=Lyndsey Telford and Luke Heighton|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=22 February 2015|accessdate=23 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150223213505/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/investigations/11428075/The-MPs-who-topped-up-their-salaries-with-1600-an-hour-second-jobs.html|archive-date=23 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> ''The Telegraph'' also stated he voted in 63% of opportunities in Parliament, ranking him 517 out of 650 MPs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/general-election-2015/11522642/Election-2015-How-active-was-my-MP.html|title=Election 2015: How active was my MP?|author=Michael Wilkinson|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=28 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150425133839/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/general-election-2015/11522642/Election-2015-How-active-was-my-MP.html|archive-date=25 April 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Criticisms of business practice==\nDorrell has been criticised for his actions when, in 2009, his family-owned firm went into a [[prepack administration]], a \"controversial\" but legal procedure which the Government's [[Insolvency Service]] said was \"mocking rules\".<ref name= backlash>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/retailandconsumer/5880627/MP-Stephen-Dorrell-faces-backlash-over-Wensum-pre-pack.html|title=MP Stephen Dorrell faces backlash over Wensum 'pre-pack'|author=Graham Ruddick|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=21 July 2009|accessdate=1 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110828153033/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/retailandconsumer/5880627/MP-Stephen-Dorrell-faces-backlash-over-Wensum-pre-pack.html|archive-date=28 August 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>  \nDavid Blake, Director of the [[Cass Business School]] in London, believes the method is used to dump pension fund liabilities.<ref name=Fran>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/8555694.stm|title=How firms 'avoid' pension costs|author=Fran Abrams|work=[[BBC News]]|date=9 March 2010|accessdate=1 May 2012}}</ref> The controversy may have deterred David Cameron from inviting Dorrell to join the Front Bench.<ref name= backlash/> His stake was in clothing company, Faithful, a family business established in the 19th century which made [[blue collar]] [[workwear]] in [[Worcester]].<ref name=fo4>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/console/b00r66v2|title=Pensions crisis|publisher=BBC File on 4|author=Fran Abrams|date=14 March 2010|accessdate=1 May 2012}}</ref> Finance Director Steve Hall reported the company had been quite profitable until 2004 when it was split between Dorrell and his brother.<ref name=fo4/>  \n\nBy 2005, after loss-making acquisitions, the [[defined benefit|company pensions]] [[Minimum funding requirement|deficit]] was almost \u00a33 million. The pension scheme was changed to [[money purchase]], and the factory site was [[Pledge (law)|pledged]] to support it.<ref name=fo4/> However, when the site was sold, some of the money was used to buy another business, and the firm was bought by stock market-listed Wensum.<ref name=fo4/> None of the money was paid into the pension scheme.<ref name=fo4/> Per Dorrell, the scheme then required 10% of annual turnover, making (debt or equity) restructuring (by financiers) impossible.<ref name=fo4/> An independent trustee was appointed, the pension fund received nothing and Wensum continued as a company.<ref name=fo4/> In May 2009, Wensum was put into a prepack administration which allowed a new company, GG125, to acquire Wensum's assets for \u00a37.9 million, whilst leaving its debts unpaid.<ref name=imm>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/retailandconsumer/6209674/Stephen-Dorrell-criticised-over-immoral-deal.html|title=Stephen Dorrell criticised over 'immoral' deal|author=Graham Ruddick|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=19 September 2009|accessdate=1 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120421054205/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/retailandconsumer/6209674/Stephen-Dorrell-criticised-over-immoral-deal.html|archive-date=21 April 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><br />\n \nGG125 was then renamed Wensum Group Limited.<ref name= imm/> The deal was completed in a day, Dorrell receiving a director salary (increased to \u00a3200,000 in September 2009) plus 15% share ownership in the new company.<ref name=fo4/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/6237266/MP-gets-pay-rise-as-creditors-struggle-with-4m-debt.html|title=MP gets pay rise as creditors struggle with \u00a34m debt|author=Graham Ruddick|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=27 September 2009|accessdate=1 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121112154447/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/6237266/MP-gets-pay-rise-as-creditors-struggle-with-4m-debt.html|archive-date=12 November 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> As company contributions had ceased, the workers were put into the [[Pension Protection Fund]] (PPF), which caps (often reducing) personal payouts and tends to erode with inflation.<ref name=fo4/> Hall expected 30\u201340% pension loss to him as such.<ref name=Fran/> Dorrell and his wife had already withdrawn their pensions.<ref name=fo4/> Dorrell claimed he had lost \u00a3550,000 because of the failure and that the alternative to the prepack would have offered less.<ref name= backlash/>\n\nThe prepack was criticised as \"completely immoral\", and inappropriate for listed companies, by a South African creditor, LA group. It had sold a clothing manufacturer to Wensum in May 2009 for Wensum shares which became worthless and ceased after the prepack.<ref name= imm/> Another Wensum shareholder compared the deal to a \"spider eviscerating a fly it has caught, taking all the good bits, then dropping the useless carcass, which is the creditors, the shareholders and of course the taxpayer\".<ref name= backlash/>\n\n==After Parliament==\nHe was reckoned by the [[Health Service Journal]] to be the 24th most influential person  in the English NHS in 2015 after he became Chair of the [[NHS Confederation]].<ref>{{cite news|title=HSJ100 2015|url=http://www.hsj.co.uk/7000366.article|accessdate=23 December 2015|publisher=Health Service Journal|date=23 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151224052509/http://www.hsj.co.uk/7000366.article|archive-date=24 December 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016 he became Chair of the [[European Movement UK]], succeeding [[Richard Corbett]], in order to lead its campaign to stop [[Brexit]].\n\nIn 2018, Dorrell became a committee member of the Tories Against Brexit campaign, which is run  by Citizens4Britain.org. He also became the chair of healthcare consultancy [[LaingBuisson]].<ref>{{cite web|title=LaingBuisson names chairman and CEO|url=http://www.pmlive.com/pharma_appointments/laingbuisson_names_chairman_and_ceo_1052738|website=PMLive|accessdate=6 May 2017|language=en|date=4 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160707055525/http://www.pmlive.com/pharma_appointments/laingbuisson_names_chairman_and_ceo_1052738|archive-date=7 July 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHe became a supporter of [[Change UK]] in 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dorrell |first1=Stephen |title=As nationalists grip the Tories, I now support Change UK |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2019/apr/14/nationalists-grip-tories-i-now-support-change-uk-brexit-european-elections |accessdate=14 April 2019 |work=[[The Observer]] |date=14 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190414090703/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2019/apr/14/nationalists-grip-tories-i-now-support-change-uk-brexit-european-elections |archive-date=14 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> He stood for the party in the [[2019 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|2019 European Parliament elections]] in the constituency of the [[West Midlands (European Parliament constituency)|West Midlands]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/former-tory-cabinet-minister-stephen-16168202|title=Ex-Tory minister Stephen Dorrell stands for anti-Brexit party|last=Walker|first=Jonathan|date=2019-04-23|website=birminghammail|access-date=2019-04-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423220949/https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/former-tory-cabinet-minister-stephen-16168202|archive-date=23 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDorrell stood unsuccessfully in the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]] as the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] candidate for [[Buckingham (UK Parliament constituency)|Buckingham]] to succeed former [[Speaker of the British House of Commons|Speaker of the House of Commons]] [[John Bercow]], having joined the Lib Dems in August from [[Change UK]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/buckslibdems/status/1190558455955939329?s=21|title=Stephen Dorrell to contest Buckingham for @LibDems! He held a number of senior posts incl Secretary of State for Health. He left the Conservatives earlier this year & has since joined @LibDems. We're campaigning to WIN Buckingham. Meet Stephen today! http://bit.ly/BCLDSuperSaturday\u00a0\u2026pic.twitter.com/EhKrDmivVi|first=Bucks Lib|last=Dems \u00a0\ud83d\udd36|date=2 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000608 |title=BBC election result |access-date=13 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190413154208/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000608 |archive-date=13 April 2019 |url-status=live |work=BBC News }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life ==\nDorrell is married to Penelope Taylor<ref name=WPR>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliamentaryrecord.com/content/profiles/mp/Stephen-Dorrell/Charnwood/116|title=Stephen Dorrell MP|publisher=Westminster Parliamentary Record|access-date=2 May 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120527133143/http://www.parliamentaryrecord.com/content/profiles/mp/Stephen-Dorrell/Charnwood/116|archive-date=27 May 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and has three sons and a daughter.\n\nHe is a Trustee of [[Uppingham School]] and a Governor of [[Loughborough Endowed Schools]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/regmem/?p=10175|title=Changes to the Register of Members' Interests Stephen Dorrell|publisher=TheyWorkForYou|accessdate=2 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111230195956/http://www.theyworkforyou.com/regmem/?p=10175|archive-date=30 December 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n<!--Conservative Party profile-->\n*{{UK MP links | parliament = stephen-dorrell/336 | hansard = mr-stephen-dorrell | hansardcurr = 3007 | guardian = 1442/stephen-dorrell | publicwhip = Stephen_Dorrell | theywork = stephen_dorrell | record = Stephen-Dorrell/Charnwood/116 | bbc = 25769.stm | journalisted = stephen-dorrell }}\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/2061932.stm Profile: Stephen Dorrell MP], ''[[BBC News]]'', 18 October 2002\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Cronin (British politician)|John Cronin]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Loughborough (UK Parliament constituency)|Loughborough]]|years=[[1979 United Kingdom general election|1979]]\u2013[[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Andy Reed (politician)|Andy Reed]]}}\n|-\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Charnwood (UK Parliament constituency)|Charnwood]]|years=[[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]\u2013[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Edward Argar]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[David Alton, Baron Alton of Liverpool|David Alton]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Baby of the House]]|years=1979\u20131981}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Bobby Sands]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Bobby Sands]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Baby of the House]]|years=1981}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Owen Carron]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Francis Maude]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Financial Secretary to the Treasury]]|years=1992\u20131994}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[George Young, Baron Young of Cookham|George Young]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Peter Brooke, Baron Brooke of Sutton Mandeville|Peter Brooke]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary of State for National Heritage]]|years=1994\u20131995}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Virginia Bottomley]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Virginia Bottomley]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary of State for Health]]|years=1995\u20131997}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Frank Dobson]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Harriet Harman]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow Secretary of State for Health]]|years=1997}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[John Maples]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Gillian Shephard]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow Secretary of State for Education|Shadow Secretary of State for Education and Employment]]|years=1997\u20131998}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[David Willetts]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Babies of the House}}\n{{Secretary of State for Health}}\n{{Secretary of State for Culture}}\n{{Major Ministry}}\n{{1997 Conservative Party leadership election}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dorrell, Stephen}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Brasenose College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:British people of English descent]]\n[[Category:British Secretaries of State]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Dorrell family]]\n[[Category:The Independent Group politicians]]\n[[Category:KPMG people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Loughborough]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Financial Secretary to the Treasury]]\n[[Category:People educated at Uppingham School]]\n[[Category:People from Worcester]]\n[[Category:Secretaries of State for Health (UK)]]\n[[Category:Secretaries of State for National Heritage]]\n[[Category:Shadow Secretaries of State for Health]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1979\u20131983]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1983\u20131987]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1987\u20131992]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1992\u20131997]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British Liberal Democrat politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name             = Stephen Dorrell\n|image            = Stephen dorrell mp -nhs confederation annual conferencepercent2c manchester-11july2011 - crop.jpg\n|office1          = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Education|Shadow Secretary of State for Education and Employment]]\n|leader1          = [[William Hague]]\n|term_start1      = 11 June 1997\n|term_end1        = 2 June 1998\n|predecessor1     = [[Gillian Shephard]]\n|successor1       = [[David Willetts]]\n|office2          = [[Shadow Secretary of State for Health]]\n|leader2          = [[John Major]]\n|term_start2      = 2 May 1997\n|term_end2        = 11 June 1997\n|predecessor2     = [[Chris Smith, Baron Smith of Finsbury|Chris Smith]]\n|successor2       = [[John Maples]]\n|office3          = [[Secretary of State for Health]]\n|primeminister3   = [[John Major]]\n|term_start3      = 5 July 1995\n|term_end3        = 2 May 1997\n|predecessor3     = [[Virginia Bottomley]]\n|successor3       = [[Frank Dobson]]\n|office4          = [[Secretary of State for National Heritage]]\n|primeminister4   = [[John Major]]\n|term_start4      = 20 July 1994\n|term_end4        = 5 July 1995\n|predecessor4     = [[Peter Brooke]]\n|successor4       = [[Virginia Bottomley]]\n|office5          = [[Financial Secretary to the Treasury]]\n|primeminister5   = [[John Major]]\n|term_start5      = 11 April 1992\n|term_end5        = 11 July 1994\n|predecessor5     = [[Francis Maude]]\n|successor5       = [[George Young, Baron Young of Cookham|George Young]]\n|office6 = [[Lord Commissioner of the Treasury]]\n|primeminister6 = [[Margaret Thatcher]]\n|predecessor6 = [[Tony Durant]]\n|successor6 = [[Michael Fallon]]\n|term_start6 = 20 December 1988\n|term_end6 = 3 May 1990\n|office7          = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br/>for [[Charnwood (UK Parliament constituency)|Charnwood]]\n|term_start7      = 1 May 1997\n|term_end7        = 30 March 2015\n|predecessor7     = Constituency established\n|successor7       = [[Edward Argar]]\n|office8          = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br/>for [[Loughborough (UK Parliament constituency)|Loughborough]]\n|term_start8      = 3 May 1979\n|term_end8        = 8 April 1997\n|predecessor8     = [[John Desmond Cronin|John Cronin]]\n|successor8       = [[Andy Reed (politician)|Andy Reed]]\n|birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1952|3|25|df=y}}\n|birth_place      = [[Worcester]], [[England]]\n|death_date       = \n|death_place      = \n|party            = [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] (2019\u2013present)\n|otherparty       = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] (before 2019)<br>\n[[Change UK]] (2019)\n|spouse           = Penelope Taylor\n|alma_mater       = [[Brasenose College, Oxford]]\n|website          = [http://www.stephendorrell.org.uk Official website]\n}}\n\n'''Stephen James Dorrell''' (born 25 March 1952) is a British [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] politician. <ref name=persweb>{{cite web|url=http://www.stephendorrell.org.uk/person/rt-hon-stephen-dorrell-mp|title=Stephen Dorrell MP -official constituency website|accessdate=2 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021011753/http://www.stephendorrell.org.uk/person/rt-hon-stephen-dorrell-mp|archive-date=21 October 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> He served as the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Loughborough (UK Parliament constituency)|Loughborough]] between 1979 and 1997 and then for [[Charnwood (UK Parliament constituency)|Charnwood]] from 1997 to 2015.\n\nDorrell most recently served for four years as Chairman of the [[House of Commons (UK)|House of Commons]] [[Health Select Committee]] from 2010 to 2014. In the 1990s he was a full member of [[John Major]]'s [[Cabinet of the United Kingdom|Cabinet]] for almost three years, whilst serving as both [[Secretary of State for National Heritage]] and then [[Secretary of State for Health]] until the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]]. He was also a Patron of the [[Tory Reform Group]].\n\nSince 2014 he has been a consultant with the health and public service practice of [[KPMG]].\n\nIn the spring of 2019 he left the Conservative Party to join [[Change UK]] and was the lead candidate on the party's list in the [[West Midlands (European Parliament constituency)|West Midlands]] region at the [[2019 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|2019 European Parliament election]]. After failing to be elected, he defected to the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] and was the unsuccessful Liberal Democrat candidate for [[Buckingham (UK Parliament constituency)|Buckingham]] in the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]].\n\n==Early life and  education==\nDorrell was born in [[Worcester]] and educated at [[Uppingham School]], [[Rutland]] and [[Brasenose College, Oxford]], where he was awarded a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree. He was a member of the [[Royal Air Force Volunteer Reserve]] for two years from 1971.\n\n==Political career==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=October 2015}}\nDuring the [[February 1974 United Kingdom general election|February 1974 general election]], Dorrell acted as a personal assistant to Conservative minister [[Peter Walker, Baron Walker of Worcester|Peter Walker]]. Aged only 22, he contested the safe [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] seat of [[Kingston upon Hull East (UK Parliament constituency)|Kingston upon Hull East]] at the October 1974 general election, but was heavily defeated by the sitting MP (and later [[Deputy Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Deputy Prime Minister]]), [[John Prescott]], who was returned with a majority of 25,793 votes.\n\nAt the [[1979 United Kingdom general election|1979 general election]], the Conservatives were returned to office under the leadership of [[Margaret Thatcher]]. Dorrell, then 27, was elected to the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] for the marginal seat of [[Loughborough (UK Parliament constituency)|Loughborough]], ousting the veteran Labour MP [[John Desmond Cronin|John Cronin]] by 5,199 votes. He remained an MP until standing down from Parliament at the 2015 General Election.\n\nOn his election he was the ''[[Baby of the House of Commons]]'', an informal title for the youngest member.  He was succeeded as the ''Baby of the House'' on 9 April 1981 when [[Bobby Sands]] was elected at the [[April 1981 Fermanagh and South Tyrone by-election]]; however, Sands died on 5 May 1981 whilst on [[1981 Irish hunger strike|hunger strike]] in [[Maze (HM Prison)|Long Kesh Prison]]. Dorrell again became the ''Baby of the House'' until 20 August 1981, when Sands' successor [[Owen Carron]] was elected at the [[August 1981 Fermanagh and South Tyrone by-election]]. He nonetheless remained the youngest MP to take his seat in the House of Commons ([[Sinn Fein]] members do not take their seats) until the 1983 election, when [[Charles Kennedy]] succeeded him.\n\nFollowing his election to [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|parliament]] in 1979 he was a member of the [[Department for Transport|Transport]] [[Select committee (United Kingdom)|Select committee]]. After the [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983 general election]] he was appointed as the [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] to his old boss Peter Walker, who had now become the [[Secretary of State for Energy]].\n\n===In government===\nDorrell was promoted to government after the [[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987 General Election]] by the [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] [[Margaret Thatcher]] as an [[Whip (politics)|Assistant Government Whip]], and in 1988 became a Lord Commissioner to the Treasury 'full whip'. He was appointed as the [[Parliamentary Under Secretary of State]] at the [[Department of Health (United Kingdom)|Department of Health]] in 1990 under the premiership of [[John Major]]. After the [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992 General Election]] he became the [[Secretary to the Treasury#Financial Secretaries of the Treasury, 1852-present|Financial Secretary to the Treasury]].\n\nDorrell was promoted to the Major [[Cabinet of the United Kingdom|Cabinet]] as the [[Secretary of State for National Heritage]] in 1994, and on appointment became a Member of the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Council]]. He  headhunted [[Jennifer Page (Millennium Dome)|Jennie Page]] for the job of [[Millennium Dome]] Chief Executive according to ''[[The Observer]]''.<ref name = \"domedreamsdashed\" >{{cite news|title=How Dome dreams were dashed|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2000/feb/06/millennium.uk|accessdate=31 July 2008|work=[[The Observer]]|first=Vanessa|last=Thorpe|date=5 February 2000|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130824035334/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2000/feb/06/millennium.uk|archive-date=24 August 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> He was transferred to become the [[Secretary of State for Health]] in 1995, and remained in position until the end of the Conservative administration at the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]].\n\nDorrell was often deployed in the media as a spokesman for the Major government, as it was felt he conveyed an air of approachability and popular appeal. During one party conference season in the late 1990s he was followed by a camera crew from the BBC's Breakfast show, capturing the behind-the-scenes build-up to his conference speech. The actual speech was also shown, including his joke (at the height of tensions in the Conservative party over Europe) that he considered himself a 'bureausceptic'. Unfortunately the joke, a reference to trying to reduce the level of [[red tape]] in the Health Service, fell on deaf ears.{{citation needed|date=October 2015}}\n\n===After government===\nWhen constituency boundaries were revised for the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 election]], he moved with his key rural voters into the new [[Charnwood (UK Parliament constituency)|Charnwood]] constituency. He won the seat comfortably with a majority of 5,900, although Loughborough was lost to [[Andy Reed (politician)|Andy Reed]] of Labour.{{citation needed|date=October 2015}}\n\nHe launched a bid for the leadership of the Conservative Party in 1997, but withdrew before the first ballot when it became clear his support amongst Conservative MPs was negligible. Instead he threw his support behind [[Kenneth Clarke]]'s bid. Under [[William Hague]] he became [[Shadow Cabinet|shadow]] [[Secretary of State for Education and Employment]], but left the shadow cabinet in 1998, and was a [[backbencher]] for the remainder of his parliamentary career.\n\n====Chairman of Health Select Committee and views on NHS reforms====\nIn June 2010, Dorrell was elected Chairman of the [[Health Select Committee]]. In June 2011, following concerns over the unpopularity of [[Andrew Lansley]]'s [[Health and Social Care Act 2012|NHS reforms]], Dorrell was tipped as a possible successor but stated that he wanted to continue as the committee chairman for the full parliament.<ref name=beebJH1>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-13712255|title=Stephen Dorrell rules out return as Health Secretary|author=John Hess|date=9 June 2011|work=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=1 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320044801/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-13712255|archive-date=20 March 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> An alternate view was that David Cameron would not want any more \"Tory retreads\" from previous governments.<ref name=beebJH1/> Dorrell acknowledged that resources would become tighter but changes driven by new medicines and new expectations were inevitable and integration of health care and social care would be both better and more efficient.<ref name=beebJH1/>\n\nInterviewed in 2012, Dorrell stated that the 4% per year for four years efficiency targets, agreed before the 2010 election and described as \"a huge challenge\", were taking too long to achieve.<ref name=beebNHS>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-16696197|title=Stephen Dorrell: NHS faces huge challenge|work=[[BBC News]]|date=24 January 2012|accessdate=1 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120409202249/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-16696197|archive-date=9 April 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> Whilst the bill had good points, e.g. involving clinicians and local authorities, more independence for public health etc. savings required a change in the way care is delivered not just changes in management structure.<ref name=beebNHS/> The reforms were acting as a \"disruption and distraction\".<ref name=beebNHS/>  They were a secondary issue compared with the need to make efficiency savings of \u00a320bn, he added.<ref name=gard>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/healthcare-network/2012/mar/02/nhs-reform-reality-stephen-dorrell|title=NHS reform debate has lost touch with reality, says Stephen Dorrell|author=Clare Horton|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=2 March 2012|accessdate=2 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160308223105/http://www.theguardian.com/healthcare-network/2012/mar/02/nhs-reform-reality-stephen-dorrell|archive-date=8 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDorrell resigned in June 2014 and was succeeded by [[Sarah Wollaston]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Dr Sarah Wollaston elected as health committee chairwoman|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-27911517|accessdate=14 July 2014|work=[[BBC News]]|date=18 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140701160020/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-27911517|archive-date=1 July 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Expenses investigation over \"secret flat rent deal\" with care home owners====\nIn November 2012 Dorrell was reported to the [[Independent Parliamentary Standards Authority]] (IPSA) after arranging to sell his London flat to \u201cfriends\u201d who owned a chain of nursing homes, subsequently renting it back at \u00a31,400 a month, funded by the taxpayer. His impartiality as chairman was questioned as the Health Select Committee was investigating social care, and some of the chain's nursing homes had been criticised by the [[Care Quality Commission]].  Committee members were not aware of the financial connection. [[David Cameron]] refused to get involved, saying it was a matter for IPSA. IPSA said that the rules banned MPs from renting from family members, not from friends.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/9694228/MPs-expenses-Stephen-Dorrell-MP-reported-to-sleaze-watchdog-over-secret-flat-rent-deal.html|title=MPs' expenses: Stephen Dorrell MP reported to sleaze watchdog over secret flat rent deal|author=Christopher Hope|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=21 November 2012|accessdate=24 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141025173926/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/9694228/MPs-expenses-Stephen-Dorrell-MP-reported-to-sleaze-watchdog-over-secret-flat-rent-deal.html|archive-date=25 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Standing down from Parliament===\nIn November 2014, he surprised local party members and staff by announcing his future retirement from the House to take a job with consultancy [[KPMG]] in \"a senior role supporting their health and public service practice...\". The role, he said, was \"incompatible with seeking re-election to the House of Commons\". Fellow Leicestershire Conservative MP [[Andrew Bridgen]] also expressed surprise, but said that the prestige of Parliament had fallen since the [[United Kingdom parliamentary expenses scandal|expenses scandal]], and a number of experienced MPs were leaving. Neighbouring Loughborough MP [[Nicky Morgan]] described him as \"a really important political figure in Leicestershire since 1979. He has been a great support to me\". She denied claims she would stand in Dorrell's Charnwood seat (rather than Loughborough) at the 2015 general election, saying that these were \"rumour-mongering\" by members of the Labour Party. (In May 2015 she held the Loughborough seat with an increased majority.)\n\nThe Labour candidate for Charnwood, Sean Kelly Walsh, paid tribute to Dorrell's long service and constituency work, as well as his roles as Secretary of State for Health and chairman of the Health Affairs Select Committee.<ref name=dan>{{cite news|url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Conservative-Charnwood-MP-Stephen-Dorrell/story-24673441-detail/story.html|title=Conservative Charnwood MP Stephen Dorrell quitting Parliament to join KPMG|work=Leicester Mercury|author=danjmartin|date=25 November 2014|access-date=26 November 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150219133226/http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Conservative-Charnwood-MP-Stephen-Dorrell/story-24673441-detail/story.html|archive-date=19 February 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Resignation call over conflict of interest===\nIn December 2014, Dorrell was criticised for alleged conflict of interest when it became clear that he would be working both as an MP and KPMG consultant for six months until the election, and that KPMG were considering bidding for a \u00a31 billion NHS contract. Pointing out that Dorrell had previously admitted the two roles were incompatible, Dr Clive Peedell, co-leader of the [[National Health Action Party]], called for him to resign from one of the posts. Dorrell responded saying no issues were raised as he was not seeking re-election.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/conservative/11264425/Stephen-Dorrell-MP-faces-calls-to-resign-over-conflict-of-interest.html|title=Stephen Dorrell MP faces calls to resign over conflict of interest|work=Daily Telegraph|date=1 December 2014|accessdate=4 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141203220517/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/conservative/11264425/Stephen-Dorrell-MP-faces-calls-to-resign-over-conflict-of-interest.html|archive-date=3 December 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2015, a group of six pensioners, who called at Dorrell's offices in [[Thurmaston]] to hand in a 2,286 signature petition calling on him to resign, were told they were trespassing and the police would be called. Hanif Asmal, Chairman of Charnwood Conservative Association claimed police were called as the group didn\u2019t have an appointment.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Police-called-deal-petitioning-pensioners-MP/story-25838352-detail/story.html|title=Police called to MP Stephen Dorrell's office to deal with petitioning pensioners|author=PA_Warzynski|work=Leicester Mercury|date=11 January 2015|access-date=17 January 2015|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150115064212/http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Police-called-deal-petitioning-pensioners-MP/story-25838352-detail/story.html|archive-date=15 January 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', Dorrell's extra-parliamentary work took up 1,736 hours, or 33.4 hours per week, in 2014.<ref name=lyn>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/investigations/11428075/The-MPs-who-topped-up-their-salaries-with-1600-an-hour-second-jobs.html|title=The MPs who topped up their salaries with \u00a31,600-an-hour second jobs|author=Lyndsey Telford and Luke Heighton|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=22 February 2015|accessdate=23 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150223213505/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/investigations/11428075/The-MPs-who-topped-up-their-salaries-with-1600-an-hour-second-jobs.html|archive-date=23 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> ''The Telegraph'' also stated he voted in 63% of opportunities in Parliament, ranking him 517 out of 650 MPs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/general-election-2015/11522642/Election-2015-How-active-was-my-MP.html|title=Election 2015: How active was my MP?|author=Michael Wilkinson|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=28 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150425133839/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/general-election-2015/11522642/Election-2015-How-active-was-my-MP.html|archive-date=25 April 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Criticisms of business practice==\nDorrell has been criticised for his actions when, in 2009, his family-owned firm went into a [[prepack administration]], a \"controversial\" but legal procedure which the Government's [[Insolvency Service]] said was \"mocking rules\".<ref name= backlash>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/retailandconsumer/5880627/MP-Stephen-Dorrell-faces-backlash-over-Wensum-pre-pack.html|title=MP Stephen Dorrell faces backlash over Wensum 'pre-pack'|author=Graham Ruddick|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=21 July 2009|accessdate=1 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110828153033/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/retailandconsumer/5880627/MP-Stephen-Dorrell-faces-backlash-over-Wensum-pre-pack.html|archive-date=28 August 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>  \nDavid Blake, Director of the [[Cass Business School]] in London, believes the method is used to dump pension fund liabilities.<ref name=Fran>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/8555694.stm|title=How firms 'avoid' pension costs|author=Fran Abrams|work=[[BBC News]]|date=9 March 2010|accessdate=1 May 2012}}</ref> The controversy may have deterred David Cameron from inviting Dorrell to join the Front Bench.<ref name= backlash/> His stake was in clothing company, Faithful, a family business established in the 19th century which made [[blue collar]] [[workwear]] in [[Worcester]].<ref name=fo4>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/console/b00r66v2|title=Pensions crisis|publisher=BBC File on 4|author=Fran Abrams|date=14 March 2010|accessdate=1 May 2012}}</ref> Finance Director Steve Hall reported the company had been quite profitable until 2004 when it was split between Dorrell and his brother.<ref name=fo4/>  \n\nBy 2005, after loss-making acquisitions, the [[defined benefit|company pensions]] [[Minimum funding requirement|deficit]] was almost \u00a33 million. The pension scheme was changed to [[money purchase]], and the factory site was [[Pledge (law)|pledged]] to support it.<ref name=fo4/> However, when the site was sold, some of the money was used to buy another business, and the firm was bought by stock market-listed Wensum.<ref name=fo4/> None of the money was paid into the pension scheme.<ref name=fo4/> Per Dorrell, the scheme then required 10% of annual turnover, making (debt or equity) restructuring (by financiers) impossible.<ref name=fo4/> An independent trustee was appointed, the pension fund received nothing and Wensum continued as a company.<ref name=fo4/> In May 2009, Wensum was put into a prepack administration which allowed a new company, GG125, to acquire Wensum's assets for \u00a37.9 million, whilst leaving its debts unpaid.<ref name=imm>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/retailandconsumer/6209674/Stephen-Dorrell-criticised-over-immoral-deal.html|title=Stephen Dorrell criticised over 'immoral' deal|author=Graham Ruddick|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=19 September 2009|accessdate=1 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120421054205/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/retailandconsumer/6209674/Stephen-Dorrell-criticised-over-immoral-deal.html|archive-date=21 April 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><br />\n \nGG125 was then renamed Wensum Group Limited.<ref name= imm/> The deal was completed in a day, Dorrell receiving a director salary (increased to \u00a3200,000 in September 2009) plus 15% share ownership in the new company.<ref name=fo4/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/6237266/MP-gets-pay-rise-as-creditors-struggle-with-4m-debt.html|title=MP gets pay rise as creditors struggle with \u00a34m debt|author=Graham Ruddick|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=27 September 2009|accessdate=1 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121112154447/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/6237266/MP-gets-pay-rise-as-creditors-struggle-with-4m-debt.html|archive-date=12 November 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> As company contributions had ceased, the workers were put into the [[Pension Protection Fund]] (PPF), which caps (often reducing) personal payouts and tends to erode with inflation.<ref name=fo4/> Hall expected 30\u201340% pension loss to him as such.<ref name=Fran/> Dorrell and his wife had already withdrawn their pensions.<ref name=fo4/> Dorrell claimed he had lost \u00a3550,000 because of the failure and that the alternative to the prepack would have offered less.<ref name= backlash/>\n\nThe prepack was criticised as \"completely immoral\", and inappropriate for listed companies, by a South African creditor, LA group. It had sold a clothing manufacturer to Wensum in May 2009 for Wensum shares which became worthless and ceased after the prepack.<ref name= imm/> Another Wensum shareholder compared the deal to a \"spider eviscerating a fly it has caught, taking all the good bits, then dropping the useless carcass, which is the creditors, the shareholders and of course the taxpayer\".<ref name= backlash/>\n\n==After Parliament==\nHe was reckoned by the [[Health Service Journal]] to be the 24th most influential person  in the English NHS in 2015 after he became Chair of the [[NHS Confederation]].<ref>{{cite news|title=HSJ100 2015|url=http://www.hsj.co.uk/7000366.article|accessdate=23 December 2015|publisher=Health Service Journal|date=23 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151224052509/http://www.hsj.co.uk/7000366.article|archive-date=24 December 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016 he became Chair of the [[European Movement UK]], succeeding [[Richard Corbett]], in order to lead its campaign to stop [[Brexit]].\n\nIn 2018, Dorrell became a committee member of the Tories Against Brexit campaign, which is run  by Citizens4Britain.org. He also became the chair of healthcare consultancy [[LaingBuisson]].<ref>{{cite web|title=LaingBuisson names chairman and CEO|url=http://www.pmlive.com/pharma_appointments/laingbuisson_names_chairman_and_ceo_1052738|website=PMLive|accessdate=6 May 2017|language=en|date=4 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160707055525/http://www.pmlive.com/pharma_appointments/laingbuisson_names_chairman_and_ceo_1052738|archive-date=7 July 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHe became a supporter of [[Change UK]] in 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dorrell |first1=Stephen |title=As nationalists grip the Tories, I now support Change UK |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2019/apr/14/nationalists-grip-tories-i-now-support-change-uk-brexit-european-elections |accessdate=14 April 2019 |work=[[The Observer]] |date=14 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190414090703/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2019/apr/14/nationalists-grip-tories-i-now-support-change-uk-brexit-european-elections |archive-date=14 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> He stood for the party in the [[2019 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|2019 European Parliament elections]] in the constituency of the [[West Midlands (European Parliament constituency)|West Midlands]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/former-tory-cabinet-minister-stephen-16168202|title=Ex-Tory minister Stephen Dorrell stands for anti-Brexit party|last=Walker|first=Jonathan|date=2019-04-23|website=birminghammail|access-date=2019-04-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423220949/https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/former-tory-cabinet-minister-stephen-16168202|archive-date=23 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDorrell stood unsuccessfully in the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]] as the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] candidate for [[Buckingham (UK Parliament constituency)|Buckingham]] to succeed former [[Speaker of the British House of Commons|Speaker of the House of Commons]] [[John Bercow]], having joined the Lib Dems in August from [[Change UK]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/buckslibdems/status/1190558455955939329?s=21|title=Stephen Dorrell to contest Buckingham for @LibDems! He held a number of senior posts incl Secretary of State for Health. He left the Conservatives earlier this year & has since joined @LibDems. We're campaigning to WIN Buckingham. Meet Stephen today! http://bit.ly/BCLDSuperSaturday\u00a0\u2026pic.twitter.com/EhKrDmivVi|first=Bucks Lib|last=Dems \u00a0\ud83d\udd36|date=2 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000608 |title=BBC election result |access-date=13 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190413154208/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000608 |archive-date=13 April 2019 |url-status=live |work=BBC News }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life ==\nDorrell is married to Penelope Taylor<ref name=WPR>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliamentaryrecord.com/content/profiles/mp/Stephen-Dorrell/Charnwood/116|title=Stephen Dorrell MP|publisher=Westminster Parliamentary Record|access-date=2 May 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120527133143/http://www.parliamentaryrecord.com/content/profiles/mp/Stephen-Dorrell/Charnwood/116|archive-date=27 May 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and has three sons and a daughter.\n\nHe is a Trustee of [[Uppingham School]] and a Governor of [[Loughborough Endowed Schools]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/regmem/?p=10175|title=Changes to the Register of Members' Interests Stephen Dorrell|publisher=TheyWorkForYou|accessdate=2 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111230195956/http://www.theyworkforyou.com/regmem/?p=10175|archive-date=30 December 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n<!--Conservative Party profile-->\n*{{UK MP links | parliament = stephen-dorrell/336 | hansard = mr-stephen-dorrell | hansardcurr = 3007 | guardian = 1442/stephen-dorrell | publicwhip = Stephen_Dorrell | theywork = stephen_dorrell | record = Stephen-Dorrell/Charnwood/116 | bbc = 25769.stm | journalisted = stephen-dorrell }}\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/2061932.stm Profile: Stephen Dorrell MP], ''[[BBC News]]'', 18 October 2002\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Cronin (British politician)|John Cronin]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Loughborough (UK Parliament constituency)|Loughborough]]|years=[[1979 United Kingdom general election|1979]]\u2013[[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Andy Reed (politician)|Andy Reed]]}}\n|-\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Charnwood (UK Parliament constituency)|Charnwood]]|years=[[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]\u2013[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Edward Argar]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[David Alton, Baron Alton of Liverpool|David Alton]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Baby of the House]]|years=1979\u20131981}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Bobby Sands]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Bobby Sands]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Baby of the House]]|years=1981}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Owen Carron]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Francis Maude]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Financial Secretary to the Treasury]]|years=1992\u20131994}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[George Young, Baron Young of Cookham|George Young]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=