nte]] GC1000 Core\n| memory        = 1&nbsp;[[Gigabyte|GB]] [[random-access memory|RAM]]\n| storage       = 16&nbsp;GB or 32&nbsp;GB [[flash memory]]\n| memory_card   = [[microSD]] (up to 128&nbsp;GB [[SDXC]])\n| battery       =  1,650&nbsp;/1,800[[Ampere-hour|mAh]] [[Lithium-ion battery|Li-ion]]<br /> User replaceable\n| input         = [[Multi-touch]] [[capacitive touchscreen]], [[#Audio|headset controls]], [[Proximity sensor]], [[low-key lighting|Ambient light]] sensor, 3-axis [[Gyroscope]], [[Magnetometer]], [[Accelerometer]], [[Assisted GPS|aGPS]]<ref name=\"thinnest\" />\n| display       = {{unbulleted list | {{convert|4.3|in|mm|abbr=on}} [[Super AMOLED Plus]] (480\u00d7800) [[pixel]]s (217&nbsp;[[Pixel density|ppi]]) and RGB-Matrix (GT-I9100/G, GT-I9105, SHW-M250S/K/L) | 4.5 in [[Super AMOLED Plus]] (480\u00d7800) [[pixel]]s and RGB-Matrix (GT-I9210)}}\n| rear_camera   = 8 [[Megapixel|MP]]\n{{Collapsible list\n  | title =\n  | 8 [[Megapixel]] [[Back-illuminated sensor]] with [[auto focus]]\n  | [[1080p]] 30&nbsp;[[Frame rate|fps]] [[High-definition video|Full HD]] video recording |[[Aperture]] f/2.7\n  | [[LED]] flash}}\n| front_camera  = 2 [[Megapixel]]\n| sound         = [[SoundAlive]], 16&nbsp;kHz 64&nbsp;kbit/s Mono in HD Video Recording\n| connectivity  =\n{{Collapsible list\n  | title =\n  |3.5&nbsp;mm [[TRS connector|TRRS]]; [[Wi-Fi]] ([[802.11|802.11a/b/g/n]]); [[Wi-Fi Direct]]; [[Bluetooth]]&nbsp;3.0; micro&nbsp;[[USB 2.0]]; [[DLNA]]; [[Mobile High-definition Link|MHL]]; [[HDMI]]; [[USB On-The-Go|USB OTG]] Host&nbsp;2.0; [[Generic Access Network|UMA]]; FM radio/[[T-DMB]] (SHW-M250S/K/L)\n}}\n| other         =\n{{Collapsible list\n  | title =\n  |[[Hotspot (Wi-Fi)|Wi-Fi hotspot]], AllShare, Exchange ActiveSync, Damage-resistant [[Gorilla Glass]], Polaris\u2122 Office\n  | '''Online services''' [[Google Play]], [[Samsung Apps|GALAXY Apps]] (''Social Hub'', ''Readers Hub'' and ''Game Hub'')\n}}\n| sar           =\n* Int'l version:Head: 0.16 W/kg 1&nbsp;g<br />Body: 0.96 W/kg 1&nbsp;g<br />Hotspot: 1.16 W/kg 1&nbsp;g<ref>https://apps.fcc.gov/oetcf/eas/reports/ViewExhibitReport.cfm?mode=Exhibits&RequestTimeout=500&calledFromFrame=N&application_id=950779&fcc_id='A3LGTI9100', ID=1429681</ref>\n* U.S. version:<br />0.34&nbsp;W/kg (head)<ref>{{cite web|title=Samsung I9100 Galaxy S II- Full phone specs|url=http://www.gsmarena.com/samsung_i9100_galaxy_s_ii-3621.php|publisher=GSM Arena}}</ref>\n| hac           = M3/T3<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sprintrelaystore.com/ |title=Sprint Relay Store |accessdate=15 December 2011}}</ref>\n| website       =\n| references    =\n| commons       = Category:Samsung Galaxy S II I9100, Samsung Galaxy S II I9100G or Samsung Galaxy S II I9100P\n}}\n\nThe '''Samsung Galaxy S II''' is a [[touchscreen]]-enabled, [[Slate phone|slate]]-format [[Android (operating system)|Android]] [[smartphone]] designed, developed, and marketed by [[Samsung Electronics]], as the second smartphone of the [[Samsung Galaxy S series]]. It has additional software features, expanded hardware, and a redesigned physique compared to its predecessor, the [[Samsung Galaxy S]]. The S II was launched with [[Android Gingerbread|Android 2.3 \"Gingerbread\"]], with updates to [[Android Jelly Bean|Android 4.1.2 \"Jelly Bean\"]].\n\nSamsung unveiled the S II on 13 February 2011 at the [[Mobile World Congress]] (MWC) in Barcelona.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newsden.net/samsung-galaxy-sii-s2-officially-announced-hand-on-video-6607/ |title=Samsung Galaxy S II gets official at MWC 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110216191419/http://www.newsden.net/samsung-galaxy-sii-s2-officially-announced-hand-on-video-6607/ |archivedate=16 February 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> It was one of the slimmest smartphones of the time, mostly 8.49&nbsp;mm thick, except for two small bulges which take the maximum thickness of the phone to 9.91&nbsp;mm.<ref>Ionescu, Daniel. (2011-09-14) [http://www.pcworld.com/article/240075/iphone_4_worlds_thinnest_phone_not_samsung_galaxy_s_ii.html Article stating measured dimensions]. Pcworld.com. Retrieved on 28 November 2011.</ref>\nThe Galaxy S II has a 1.2&nbsp;GHz [[Multi-core processor|dual-core]] \"[[Exynos]]\" [[system on a chip]] (SoC) processor,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.samsung.com/global/business/semiconductor/products/mobilesoc/Exynos/products4210.html |title=Samsung Exynos 4210 |work=Samsung Semiconductor |accessdate=29 September 2011}}</ref> 1 GB of [[Random-access memory|RAM]], a {{convert|10.8|cm|in|abbr=on}} [[Graphics display resolution|WVGA]] [[AMOLED|Super AMOLED Plus]] screen display and an 8-[[Pixel|megapixel]] camera with flash and [[1080p]] full high definition video recording. It is one of the first devices to offer a [[Mobile High-definition Link]] (MHL),<ref name=\"MHL\">{{cite web |url=http://armdevices.net/2011/02/15/mobile-high-definition-link-mhl/ |title=Mobile High-Definition Link (MHL) |date=15 February 2011 |work=ARMdevices.net}}</ref> which allows up to 1080p [[uncompressed video]] output to an MHL enabled TV or to an MHL to [[HDMI]] adapter, while charging the device at the same time. [[USB On-The-Go]] is supported.<ref name=\"USB OTG\">{{cite web |url=http://blog.gsmarena.com/this-is-how-you-plug-your-usb-flash-drive-into-the-samsung-galaxy-s-ii/ |title=This is how you plug your USB flash drive into the Samsung Galaxy S II |date=12 May 2011 |work=GSMArena Blog}}</ref><ref name=\"Samsung Official Specification\">{{cite web |url= http://www.samsung.com/global/microsite/galaxys2/html/specification.html |title=Samsung GALAXY S II Specification |work=Samsung.com |accessdate=21 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe user-replaceable battery gives up to ten hours of heavy usage, or two days of lighter usage.<ref name=techradarreview>[http://www.techradar.com/reviews/phones/mobile-phones/samsung-galaxy-s2-930907/review?artc_pg=9 Samsung Galaxy S2 review: Battery life and connectivity]. Techradar.com (2011-04-26). Retrieved on 28 November 2011.</ref> According to Samsung, the Galaxy S II is capable of providing 9 hours of talk time on 3G and 18.3 hours on 2G.<ref name=techradarreview/><ref>[http://www.phonearena.com/phones/Samsung-Galaxy-S-II_id5106 Samsung Galaxy S II specs]. Phonearena.com. Retrieved on 28 November 2011.</ref>\n\nThe Galaxy S II was popular and a huge success both critically and commercially,<ref>https://www.geeky-gadgets.com/samsung-galaxy-s-ii-hits-the-us-in-august-20-07-2011/</ref><ref>https://www.talkandroid.com/285756-samsung-galaxy-s-series-history/</ref> selling 3 million units within its first 55 days on the market.<ref>https://www.gsmarena.com/galaxy_s_ii_breaks_samsungs_records_sells_3_million_in_55_days-news-2846.php</ref> It was succeeded by the [[Samsung Galaxy S III]] in May 2012.<ref name=\"Cnet pre-release predictions \">{{cite web | url=http://crave.cnet.co.uk/mobiles/samsung-galaxy-s3-complete-guide-50006020/ | title=Samsung Galaxy S3 complete guide | publisher=CNET | date=25 January 2012 | accessdate=19 February 2012 | author=Andrew Hoyle}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe Galaxy S II was given worldwide release dates starting from May 2011, by more than 140 vendors in some 120 countries.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5jifPR0ObtyXNiRtsEN-1vv4BCVyg?docId=CNG.329c6cccb28bef19304d6977b2e73a97.601 |title=Samsung challenges Apple with new smartphone |date=28 April 2011 |agency=AFP}}</ref> On May 9, 2011, Samsung announced that they had received pre-orders for 3 million Galaxy S II units globally.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.samsunghub.com/2011/05/09/3m-galaxy-s-ii-units-are-pre-ordered-by-carriers-globally/ |title=3m Galaxy S II units are pre-ordered by carriers globally |date=9 May 2011 |work=Samsung Hub}}</ref>\n\nSome time after the device's release, Samsung also released a variation of the phone known as the [[Samsung Galaxy R|Galaxy R]], which uses a [[Nvidia]] [[Tegra 2#Tegra 2 series|Tegra 2]] chipset.<ref name=\"gsmarena.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gsmarena.com/samsung_i9103_galaxy_z-review-614.php |title=Samsung I9103 Galaxy R preview: First look |date=30 June 2011 |accessdate=20 August 2011 |work=GSMArena.com}}</ref><ref name=\"intomobile.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.intomobile.com/2011/08/10/samsung-galaxy-r-official-nvidia-tegra-2-dualcore-cpu-42-inch-display-5-megapixel-camera-goodness/ |title=Samsung Galaxy R official \u2013 NVIDIA Tegra 2-toting Galaxy S 2 variant |date=10 August 2011 |accessdate=20 August 2011 |work=IntoMobile |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130105121515/http://www.intomobile.com/2011/08/10/samsung-galaxy-r-official-nvidia-tegra-2-dualcore-cpu-42-inch-display-5-megapixel-camera-goodness/ |archive-date=5 January 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nSamsung also reportedly shipped Galaxy S II's for free, to several developers of the custom Android distribution [[CyanogenMod]] (particularly those who had maintained its ports for the Galaxy S with an intent for them to port CyanogenMod 7 to the device).<ref name=engadget-cm7sii>{{cite web|title=Samsung shows affection to CyanogenMod, gives its devs a free Galaxy S II (update)|url=https://www.engadget.com/2011/06/08/samsung-shows-affection-to-cyanogenmod-gives-its-devs-a-free-ga/|publisher=Engadget|accessdate=5 April 2013}}</ref>  In 2019, the Galaxy S II received Android 9.0 Pie (through custom ROMs), although it only supports up to Android 4.1.2\n\n==Features==\n\n===Software and services===\nThe Galaxy S II was launched with [[Android version history#Android 2.x Gingerbread|Android 2.3 \"Gingerbread\"]]. American variants began shipments with the slightly updated version 2.3.5 installed.<ref name=\"sgs2 epic 4g samsung official\">{{cite web |url=http://www.samsung.com/us/mobile/cell-phones/SPH-D710ZKASPR |title=Samsung Galaxy S\u2122 II, Epic\u2122 4G Touch |work=Samsung Mobile |accessdate=1 September 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"sgs2 at&t samsung official\">{{cite web |url=http://www.samsung.com/us/mobile/cell-phones/SGH-I777ZKAATT |title=Samsung Galaxy S\u2122 II, available at AT&T |work=Samsung Mobile |accessdate=1 September 2011}}</ref> Version 2.3.6 was made globally available on December 12, 2011.<ref name=\"thinnest\">{{cite web |url=http://www.samsung.com/au/news/newsPreviewRead.do?news_seq=24298 |title=Samsung Announces the GALAXY S II, World\u2019s Thinnest Smartphone that Will Let You Experience More with Less |date=15 February 2011 |work=Samsung.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120820194558/http://www.samsung.com/au/news/newsPreviewRead.do?news_seq=24298 |archivedate=20 August 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://news.in.msn.com/technology/article.aspx?cp-documentid=5628795 | title=Samsung's Galaxy S II receives Android 2.3.6 update | publisher=MSN India | date=28 November 2011 | accessdate=21 December 2011 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120102181412/http://news.in.msn.com/technology/article.aspx?cp-documentid=5628795 | archive-date=2 January 2012 | url-status=dead }}</ref> On March 13, 2012, Samsung began to roll out upgrades to [[Android version history#4.0.3|Android 4.0.3 \"Ice Cream Sandwich\"]]<ref name=\"Samsung Galaxy SII Ice Cream Sandwich Roll Out Begins\">{{cite web |url=http://www.t3.com/news/samsung-galaxy-sii-ice-cream-sandwich-roll-out-begins | title=Samsung Galaxy SII Ice Cream Sandwich Roll Out Begins | publisher=T3 | date=2012-03-13 | accessdate=13 March 2012}}</ref> through their phone management software [[Samsung Kies|KIES]] to users in South Korea, Hungary, Poland and Sweden. Russian users received the update on July 5, 2012, while the rest of Europe received it on August 1, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sammobile.com/2012/07/09/confirmed-samsung-start-android-4-0-4-updates-for-galaxy-sii | title=Confirmed: Samsung start Android 4.0.4 updates for Galaxy SII | publisher=SamMobile | date=9 July 2012 | accessdate=16 August 2012}}; {{cite web | url=http://www.christianpost.com/news/samsung-galaxy-s2-i9100-receives-android-4-0-4-ice-cream-sandwich-update-79290 | title=Samsung Galaxy S2 I9100 Receives Android 4.0.4, Ice Cream Sandwich Update | publisher=CP Tech & Biz | date=1 August 2012 | accessdate=16 August 2012}}</ref> In February 2013, Samsung began rolling out an update to [[Android version history#4.1.2|Android 4.1.2 \"Jelly Bean\"]] for the device.<ref name=uwv-galaxysii-jb>{{cite web|title=Samsung rolls out Jelly Bean update for Galaxy S II I9100G|url=http://www.unwiredview.com/2013/01/23/samsung-galaxy-s-ii-android-4-1-2-jelly-bean-update-now-rolling-out/|publisher=Unwired View}}</ref>\n\nThe S II employs the [[TouchWiz]] 4.0 user interface, following the same principle as TouchWiz 3.0 found on the Galaxy S, with new improvements, such as [[hardware acceleration]]. It also has an optional [[Gesture recognition|gesture]]-based interaction called \"motion\" which (among other things) allows users to zoom in and out by placing two fingers on the screen and tilting the device towards and away from themselves to zoom in and out respectively. This gesture function works on both the web browser and the images in gallery<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2011/03/29/samsung-galaxy-s-ii-shows-off-gyro-zoom-option-in-touchwiz-4-0/ |title=Samsung Galaxy S II shows off motion-zoom option in TouchWiz 4.0 (video) |date=29 March 2011 |work=Engadget}}</ref> used within this device. \"Panning\" on TouchWiz 4.0 allows the movement of widgets and icons shortcuts between screens, by allowing the device to be held and moved from side to side to scroll through home screens. This gesture-based management of widgets is a new optional method next to the existing method of holding and swiping between home screens.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://androidcommunity.com/samsung-galaxy-s2-touchwiz-4-0-special-features-demo-exclusive-20110325/ |title=Samsung Galaxy S2 Touchwiz 4.0 Special Features Demo [Exclusive] |date=25 March 2011 |work=Android Community}}</ref> The Android 4.1 update [[backporting|backports]] the TouchWiz Nature interface and other features from the [[Samsung Galaxy S III|Galaxy S III]], such as Direct Call, Pop-up Play, Smart Stay, and Easy Mode.<ref name=uwv-galaxysii-jb/>\n\nFour new [[Samsung Hub (Digital Store)|Samsung Hub]] applications were revealed at the 2011 MWC: Social Hub, which integrates popular social networking services into one place rather than in separate applications, Readers Hub, providing the ability to access, read and download online newspapers, ebooks and magazines from a worldwide selection, Music Hub (in partnership with [[7digital]],<ref name=\"techradar mwc 2011\"/>) an application store for downloading and purchasing music tracks on the device, and Game Hub (in partnership with [[Gameloft]],<ref name=\"techradar mwc 2011\">{{cite web |url=http://mwc2011.techradar.com/2011/02/samsung-galaxy-s2-what-you-need-to-know/ |title=Samsung Galaxy S2: what you need to know |date=14 February 2011 |work=TechRadar |access-date=21 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110420002414/http://mwc2011.techradar.com/2011/02/samsung-galaxy-s2-what-you-need-to-know/ |archive-date=20 April 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>) an application store for downloading and purchasing games. Additional applications include [[Samsung Kies|Kies 2.0]], Kies Air,<ref>{{YouTube|_qah8q631Jk|Samsung Kies Air Demo (Samsung Galaxy II)}}. Retrieved on 28 November 2011.</ref> AllShare (for [[DLNA]]), Voice Recognition, Google Voice Translation,<ref>{{YouTube|YjqwRPUMhBU|Samsung Galaxy SII \u2013 Voice Translator Demo}}. Retrieved on 28 November 2011.</ref> [[Google Maps]] with Latitude, Places, Navigation (beta) and Lost Phone Management, [[Adobe Flash]] 10.2, [[QuickOffice]] application and 'QuickType' by SWYPE.\n\nBefore launch, it was announced that Samsung had taken steps to incorporate [[Enterprise software]] for business users, which included On Device Encryption, [[Cisco]]\u2019s [[AnyConnect]] VPN, device management, Cisco WebEx, [[Juniper Networks|Juniper]],<ref name=\"Samsung Official Features\">{{cite web |url=http://www.samsung.com/global/microsite/galaxys2/html/feature.html |title=Samsung GALAXY S II Features |work=Samsung.com |accessdate=21 April 2011}}</ref> and secure remote device management from [[Sybase]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.sybase.com/afaria/2011/02/big-news-for-android-at-mobile-world-congress/ |title=Big news for Android at Mobile World Congress |date=13 February 2011 |work=Sybase Enterprise Mobility Blog}}</ref>\n\nThe Galaxy S II comes with support for many multimedia file formats and codecs. For audio it supports [[FLAC]], [[WAV]], [[Vorbis]], MP3, [[Advanced Audio Coding|AAC]], [[AAC+]], [[eAAC+]], [[Windows Media Audio|WMA]], [[AMR-NB]], [[AMR-WB]], [[Musical Instrument Digital Interface|MID]], [[Dolby AC-3|AC3]], [[XMF]]. For video formats and codecs it supports [[MPEG-4]], [[H.264]], [[H.263]], [[DivX HD]]/[[XviD]], [[VC-1]], [[3GP]] ([[MPEG-4]]), [[WMV]] ([[Advanced Systems Format|ASF]]) as well as [[Audio Video Interleave|AVI]] ([[DivX]])), [[Matroska|MKV]], [[Flash Video|FLV]] and the [[Sorenson codec]]. For H.264 playback, the device natively supports 8-bit encodes along with up to 1080p HD video playback.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gsmarena.com/samsung_i9100_galaxy_s_ii-review-588p4.php |title=Samsung I9100 Galaxy S II preview: Second encounter \u2013 Page 4 |date=13 April 2011 |work=GSMArena.com}}</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=y4d-wWCf4CQ#t=416s Samsung Galaxy S II Preview]. YouTube (2011-04-15). Retrieved on 28 November 2011.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.clove.co.uk/2011/07/06/htc-sensation-review-vs-samsung-galaxy-s-ii-video-playback-shootout/ |title=HTC Sensation Review Vs Samsung Galaxy S II: Video playback shootout \u00ab Clove Technology\u2019s Blog |date=16 July 2011 |work=Clove}}</ref>\n\n===Hardware and design===\n[[File:Samsung Galaxy S 2 and its removable parts.jpg|thumb|250px|Dismantled Samsung Galaxy S II in black, from left to right components include the handset, battery and back cover|left]]\nThe Galaxy S II has a 1.2&nbsp;GHz [[dual core]] [[ARM Cortex-A9]] processor that uses Samsung's own '[[Exynos]] 4210' [[System on a chip]] (SoC) that was previously code-named \"Orion\". The Exynos branded SoC was the source of much speculation concerning another branded successor to the previous \"[[Exynos|Hummingbird]]\" single-core SoC of the Samsung Galaxy S. The Exynos 4 Dual 45&nbsp;nm (previously Exynos 4210) uses [[ARM Holdings|ARM]]'s Mali-400 MP [[Graphics processing unit|GPU]].<ref name=\"mali-400 official\">{{cite web |url=http://www.arm.com/products/multimedia/mali-graphics-hardware/mali-400-mp.php |title=Mali-400 MP \u2013 ARM |accessdate=6 August 2011 |work=ARM.com}}</ref><ref name=\"Engadget Exynos 4210\">{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2011/03/03/samsungs-exynos-4210-flexes-3d-gaming-muscle-at-gdc-2011-video/ |title=Samsung's Exynos 4210 flexes 3D gaming muscle at GDC 2011 (video) |date=3 March 2011 |work=Engadget}}</ref> This graphics GPU, supplied by ARM, is a move away from the [[PowerVR]] GPU of the Samsung Galaxy S.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2011/02/10/samsung-dubs-its-mobile-processors-exynos-dual-core-4210-forme/ |title=Samsung dubs its mobile processors Exynos, dual-core 4210 (formerly Orion) arriving next month |date=10 February 2011 |work=Engadget}}</ref>\n\nThe Exynos 4210 supports ARM's [[SIMD]] engine (also known as ''Media Processing Engine'', or 'NEON' instructions), and may give a significant performance advantage in critical performance situations such as accelerated decoding for many multimedia codecs and formats (e.g., On2's [[VP6]]/7/8 or [[RealVideo|Real]] formats).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mobile.arm.com/products/processors/technologies/neon.php?tab=Why+NEON |title=NEON \u2013 ARM |work=ARM.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.anandtech.com/show/4098/nvidias-tegra-2-take-two-more-architectural-details-and-design-wins/2 |title=NVIDIA's Tegra 2 Take Two: More Architectural Details and Design Wins |date=5 January 2011 |work=Anandtech}}</ref><ref>[[Texas Instruments OMAP#OMAP 4]]</ref>\n\nThe Mali 400 GPU in the Exynos 4210 SOC is one of the only, if not the only GPU powering Android devices, that does not support GL_RGB Framebuffer Objects (FBOs), only GL_RGBA. The newer Galaxy S II (9100G), based on the PowerVR SGX540, does not exhibit the issue.\n\nAt the 2011 [[Game Developers Conference]] ARM's representatives demonstrated 60&nbsp;Hz framerate playback in stereoscopic 3D running on the same Mali-400 MP and Exynos SoC. They said that an increased framerate of 70&nbsp;Hz would be possible through the use of an [[HDMI 1.4]] port.<ref name=\"Engadget Exynos 4210\"/>\n\nThe [[Motorola Atrix 4G|Motorola Atrix]] advertised in June 2011 that it was \"the world's most powerful smartphone\"; in August 2011 the UK [[Advertising Standards Authority (United Kingdom)|Advertising Standards Authority]] ruled that the Atrix was not as powerful as Galaxy S II due to its faster processor.<ref>[http://www.asa.org.uk/ASA-action/Adjudications/2011/8/Motorola-Mobility-UK-Ltd/SHP_ADJ_161483.aspx UK ASA adjudication: Atrix is not world's most powerful as Samsung S II is more powerful] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110926084320/http://www.asa.org.uk/ASA-action/Adjudications/2011/8/Motorola-Mobility-UK-Ltd/SHP_ADJ_161483.aspx |date=26 September 2011 }}. Asa.org.uk. Retrieved on 28 November 2011.</ref>\n\nA newer Samsung Galaxy S II (i9100G) uses a 1.2&nbsp;GHz dual core TI OMAP 4430 processor with PowerVR SGX540 graphics.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gsmarena.com/ti_omappowered_samsung_galaxy_s_ii_i9100g_pops_up_quietly-news-3371.php |title=TI OMAP-powered Samsung Galaxy S II I9100G pops up quietly |date=11 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe Galaxy S II has 1 GB of dedicated RAM and 16 GB of internal mass storage.  Within the battery compartment there is an external [[microSD]] card slot capable of recognizing and utilizing a 64 GB [[microSDXC]] card.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sandisk 64GB micro SDXC cards confirmed working in the SGSII|url=http://androidforums.com/samsung-galaxy-s2-international/418531-sandisk-64gb-micro-sdxc-cards-confirmed-working-sgsii.html}}</ref>{{Verify source|date=March 2013}}\n\nThe Samsung Galaxy S II uses a {{convert|108.5|mm|in|adj=on}}<ref name=\"Samsung Official Specification\"/> WVGA (800 x 480) [[Super AMOLED Plus]] [[capacitive touchscreen]] that is covered by [[Gorilla Glass]] with an [[oleophobic]] fingerprint-resistant coating. The display is an upgrade of its predecessor, and the \"Plus\" signifies that the display panel has done away with Pentile matrix to regular [[RGB]] matrix display which results in a 50% increase in sub-pixels. This translates to grain reduction and sharper images and text. In addition, Samsung has claimed that Super AMOLED Plus displays are 18% more power efficient than the older Super AMOLED displays.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oled-info.com/super-amoled-plus|publisher=OLED-Info|title=http://www.oled-info.com/super-amoled-plus|accessdate=2010-12-04}}</ref> Some phones have display issues, with a few users reporting a \"yellow tint\" on the left bottom edge of the display when a neutral grey background is displayed.<ref name=\"Galaxy S II display reportedly has yellow spots, we test\">[http://www.gsmarena.com/samsung_galaxy_s_ii_display_plagued_by_uneven_brightness_yellow_tint-news-2719.php Galaxy S II display reportedly has yellow spots, we test \u2013 GSMArena.com news]. Gsmarena.com. Retrieved on 28 November 2011.</ref>\n\nThe Galaxy S II uses [[Yamaha Corporation|Yamaha]] audio hardware.<ref name=\"REAL USER REVIEW PART 3: MEDIA\">{{cite web |url=http://blog.clove.co.uk/2011/05/31/samsung-galaxy-sii-real-user-review-part-3-media/ |title=SAMSUNG GALAXY S II \u2013 REAL USER REVIEW PART 3: MEDIA |date=17 June 2011 |work=Clove Technology\u2019s Blog}}</ref> The Galaxy S II's predecessor, the original Galaxy S, used [[Wolfson Microelectronics|Wolfson]]'s WM8994 DAC.<ref name=\"Wolfson audio hub\">{{cite web |url=http://www.wolfsonmicro.com/media_centre/item/wolfsons_innovative_ultra_low_power_audio_hub_selected_for_samsungs_latest_/ |title=Wolfson\u2019s innovative ultra low power audio hub selected for Samsung's latest Bada and Android smartphones |date=17 June 2011 |work=Wolfson Microelectronics}}</ref> User feedback on [[Internet forums]] as well as an in-depth review at ''Clove'',<ref name=\"REAL USER REVIEW PART 3: MEDIA\"/> have expressed the Yamaha chip's inferior sound quality compared to that of the Wolfson chip featured in the original Galaxy S.\n\nOn the back of the device is an 8-megapixel [[Back-illuminated sensor]]<ref name=\"Silicon Summary in the Samsung Galaxy S II\">{{cite web |url=http://www.chipworks.com/en/technical-competitive-analysis/resources/recent-teardowns/2011/07/silicon-summary-in-the-samsung-galaxy-s-ii/ |title=Silicon Summary in the Samsung Galaxy S II \u00bb  Recent Teardowns \u00bb Chipworks |date=25 July 2010 |work=Chipworks |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111002205921/http://www.chipworks.com/en/technical-competitive-analysis/resources/recent-teardowns/2011/07/silicon-summary-in-the-samsung-galaxy-s-ii |archivedate=2 October 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> camera with single-LED flash that can record videos in full high-definition [[1080p]] at 30 frames per second. There is also a fixed focus front-facing 2-megapixel camera for [[Video call#Current usage|video calling]], taking photos as well as general video recording, with a maximum resolution of 640x480 ([[VGA]]).\n\nThe Galaxy S II is one of the earliest Android devices to natively support NFC [[Near field communication]].<ref name=\"Samsung Official Features\"/> This follows on from the Google [[Nexus S]] which was the first de facto NFC smartphone device.<ref name=\"First NFC Android phone\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nearfieldcommunicationsworld.com/2010/12/07/35385/google-unveils-first-android-nfc-phone-but-nexus-s-is-limited-to-tag-reading-only-for-now/ |title=Google unveils first Android NFC phone \u2013 but Nexus S is limited to tag reading only for now |date=17 June 2011 |work=NFC World}}</ref> Reportedly the UK version was supplied without an NFC chip at the beginning of its production run,<ref name=\"UK w/o NFC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.knowyourmobile.com/blog/867287/no_nfc_for_uk_samsung_galaxy_s2.html |title=No NFC for UK Samsung Galaxy S2 |date=28 April 2011 |work=Know Your Mobile |access-date=11 May 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120430003500/http://www.knowyourmobile.com/blog/867287/no_nfc_for_uk_samsung_galaxy_s2.html |archive-date=30 April 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> with an NFC-equipped version released later in 2011.<ref name=\"UK w/ NFC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.techradar.com/news/phone-and-communications/mobile-phones/samsung-officially-confirms-nfc-enabled-galaxy-s-ii-954965 |title=Samsung officially confirms NFC-enabled Galaxy S II |date=12 May 2011 |work=techradar.com}}</ref>\n\nSamsung has also included a new high-definition connection technology called [[Mobile High-definition Link]] (MHL). The main specialty of MHL is that it is optimized for mobile devices by allowing the device's battery to be charged while at the same time playing back multimedia content.<ref>{{YouTube|ZtwTcnR0hqA|Mobile High-Definition Link (MHL)}} (2011-02-15). Retrieved on 28 November 2011.</ref> For the Galaxy S II, the industry standard micro USB port found on the bottom of the device can be used with an MHL connector for a TV out connection to an external display, such as a [[High-definition television|high definition]] television.<ref name=\"MHL to TV\">{{cite web |url=http://blog.gsmarena.com/watch-samsung-galaxy-s-ii-connect-to-hdtv-through-its-mhl-port-video/ |title=Watch Samsung Galaxy S II connect to an HDTV through its MHL port [VIDEO] |date=13 May 2011 |work=GSMArena Blog}}</ref>\n\nThe micro USB port on this device also supports [[USB On-The-Go|USB OTG]] standard which means the Galaxy S II can act as a 'host' device in the same way as a desktop computer in allowing external USB devices to be plugged in and used.<ref name=\"USB OTG\"/> These external USB devices typically include [[USB flash drive]]s and separately powered [[Disc form factors|external hard drives]]. A video demonstration on YouTube<ref>{{YouTube|giJXF5pIITc|Samsung Galaxy S2 USB OTG demo}}. Retrieved on 28 November 2011.</ref> has shown the OTG function to be readily available with an ordinary micro USB (B-type) OTG adaptor. The same YouTube video goes on to mention a successful test completed on a 2 [[Terabyte|TB]] USB external hard drive (requiring own power source) but however reports of failure when trying to connect USB keyboards, tested USB mice and tested USB [[Game controller|game pads]]. Currently the only [[File System|file-system]] supported for USB drives within OTG is [[FAT32]].<!-- What about [[FAT16B]]? -->\n\nA 3.5&nbsp;mm [[TRS connector|TRRS]] headset jack is available and is located on the top side of the device. The micro USB connection port is located on the bottom side of the device.\n\nBroadcom BCM4330 combo chip integrates [[802.11n]] Wi-Fi, Bluetooth 4.0+HS and FM radio.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadcom.com/products/Wireless-LAN/802.11-Wireless-LAN-Solutions/BCM4330|title=Broadcom BCM4330 product description|date=14 February 2012|publisher=}}</ref><ref>[http://www.broadcom.com/press/release.php?id=s549642 Broadcom's New Combo Chip Integrates 802.11n Wi-Fi, Bluetooth 4.0 + HS and FM to Bring New Multimedia Applications to Smartphones, Tablets and Other Mobile Devices], Broadcom press release</ref> Phones released to the US market lack the FM receiver. BCM4330 supports [[Wi-Fi Direct]] that enable devices to communicate directly with one another without having to interact with an access point. Even if the BCM4330 chip supports Bluetooth 4.0, the Galaxy S2 is limited to Bluetooth 3.0 using the last Android version released by Samsung (4.1.2). Bluetooth 4.0 support has been introduced in Android 4.3 versions, however the upgrade to an alternative firmware is required.\n\nAdditional accessories available include:\n* [[Dock connector]] for battery charging and [[audio-visual]] output<ref name=\"GS2 accessories\"/>\n* MHL cable which makes use of the device's [[micro USB]] port for HDMI output<ref name=\"GS2 accessories\"/>\n* USB OTG adaptor for use with external USB devices such as [[USB flash drive]]s.<ref name=\"USB OTG\"/>\n* [[stylus (computing)|Stylus pen]] for use on the device's capacitive screen.<ref name=\"GS2 accessories\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mysamsunggalaxys2.com |title=Des accessoires pour le Samsung Galaxy S2 |date=17 March 2011 |work=Le Journal Du Geek|language=fr}}</ref> Support for a stylus on the Galaxy S II was a precursor to the [[Samsung Galaxy Note (original)|Samsung Galaxy Note]].\n* A number of case manufacturers have released a variety of cases for the Galaxy S II.\n* A Samsung branded [[Bluetooth]] headset for making phone calls.<ref name=\"Samsung Galaxy S2 Accessories\">{{cite web |url=http://www.samsung.com/global/microsite/galaxys2/html/accessories.html |title=Samsung Galaxy S2 Accessories |date=9 July 2012 |work=Galaxy S2 Accessories}}</ref>\n* A pair of portable speakers powered by the phone's USB port.<ref name=\"Samsung Galaxy S2 Accessories\"/>\n* A vehicle mounting kit for dashboard placement of the phone, allows [[GPS]] navigation using the phone.<ref name=\"Samsung Galaxy S2 Accessories\"/>\n\n==Variants==\n\n===Galaxy S II - Model GT-I9100G===\nThe Samsung Galaxy S II GT-I9100G was released in late 2011, and is usually sold instead of the original GT-I9100 in certain markets (mostly Asia and some parts of Europe). An overview of the Samsung Galaxy S II GT-I9100G can be seen on [[Samsung]]'s official website.<ref name=\"Samsung Galaxy S II\">{{cite web|publisher=[[Samsung]]|url=http://www.samsung.com/my/consumer/mobile-devices/smartphone/android-os/GT-I9100OIGXME|title=Samsung Galaxy S II|accessdate=2012-10-05}}</ref>  It features a Texas Instruments OMAP4430 SoC instead of the Exynos 4210 in the GT-I9100. It is visually identical to the GT-I9100, as well as having the same 1.2&nbsp;GHz processor speed and dual-core ARM Cortex A9 processor technology. However, the SoC is of a different design and the Mali-400 GPU has been replaced by a PowerVR SGX 540 GPU. This difference in the SoC makes this variant incompatible with custom [[Read-only memory|ROM]]<nowiki/>s intended for the I9100, but it has been steadily gaining its own aftermarket support (such as from [[CyanogenMod]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Samsung Galaxy S II G|url=http://wiki.cyanogenmod.org/wiki/Samsung_Galaxy_S_II_G}}</ref>) due to the relative ease of development and the openness of the TI OMAP platform.\n\n===Australia===\n\n====Telstra and Vodafone Australia - Models GT-I9100T====\nThe Galaxy S II (Model GT-I9100T) sold by [[Telstra]], [[Vodafone Australia]] and some certain other carriers outside Australia is virtually identical to the I9100 and is functionally equivalent.\n\n====Telstra and Optus - Model GT-I9210T====\nIn Australia the Galaxy S II 4G (Model GT-I9210T) uses a Qualcomm processor and supports Telstra's and Optus' [[4G]] networks. However, analog radio and digital media are not supported.\n\n===Canada===\n\n====Bell Mobility - Models GT-I9100M and SGH-I757M====\n[[Bell Mobility|Bell]]'s Galaxy S II (Model GT-I9100M) Samsung Galaxy S II is identical to the international version except that its model number is GT I9100M. All custom ROMs running on international versions can be flashed to bell's Galaxy S II also.\n\nBell's Samsung Galaxy S II HD LTE (Model SGH-I757M) is identical to the cancelled AT&T's Skyrocket HD hence making the device another variant of the South Korean model of the Galaxy S II HD LTE. One difference between the South Korean model and the Bell Mobility model is the lack of a physical home button, instead, four capacitive buttons are used, one of which directly replaces the physical home button. The specification of the device is identical to the South Korean model. However, different frequencies bands are enabled on this device.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://mobilebusiness.bell.ca/_content/uploads/771e9e54-93e2-11e1-ad47-0025903439d2/sgh-i757-ug-en.pdf | title=SGH-i757M User Manual | publisher=Samsung | accessdate=2 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n====Rogers - Models SGH-I727R and SGH-I927====\nThe Rogers Galaxy S II LTE (Model SGH-I727R) is identical to the AT&T Skyrocket, and features a larger screen 4.52\", a bigger battery 1,850&nbsp;mAh, and a different 1.5&nbsp;GHz Qualcomm processor.\n\nRogers' Galaxy S Glide (Model SGH-I927) is the same phone with the same specs as the AT&T's Captivate Glide, except the carrier logo is on the back instead of behind the front glass panel.\n\n[[Rogers Wireless|Rogers]] launched the Samsung Galaxy S II LTE, launching in Fall 2011, soon after its [[Long Term Evolution|LTE]] Launch in [[Toronto]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mobilesyrup.com/2011/08/30/confirmed-rogers-launching-lte-samung-galaxy-s-ii-plus-lte-network-in-toronto-goes-live-september-28th/ |title=Confirmed: Rogers launching LTE Samsung Galaxy S II, plus LTE network in Toronto goes live September 28th. |date=30 August 2011 |work=MobileSyrup}}</ref>\n\nNote that the Galaxy S II LTE has a different model number: I9210\nand came out later and only in select markets, including Canada and South Korea.\n\n====Telus Mobility - Model SGH-T989D====\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Samsung Galaxy S2 Koodo.jpg|thumb|Telus's Samsung Galaxy S II X (Model SGH-T989D)]] -->\n[[Telus Mobility]]'s 4G Galaxy S II X (Model SGH-T989D) has a Qualcomm 1.5&nbsp;GHz dual core processor, larger 4.52&nbsp;inch screen and 1,850&nbsp;mAh battery, is thicker at 9.4&nbsp;mm and has a different design.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.telusmobility.com/en/AB/samsung_galaxy_s_II_x/index.shtml |title=4G Samsung Galaxy S II X \u2013 Bient\u00f4t disponible |work=Telus |accessdate=27 September 2011}}</ref>  There is a chrome band around the edge and the plastic on the back has a leathery feel.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mobilesyrup.com/2011/09/22/video-telus-samsung-galaxy-s-ii-x-quick-overview/ |title=Video: TELUS Samsung Galaxy S II X quick overview |date=22 September 2011 |work=MobileSyrup}}</ref> Instead of the hardware home button, it has the standard four capacitive buttons. The Qualcomm processor allows for 42&nbsp;Mbit/s HSPA+ download speeds that the Samsung Exynos processor is not currently capable of. It was released on 28 October 2011.\n\nA subsidiary of Telus, Koodo Mobile, also offers the SGH-T989D.\n\n===China===\n\n====China - Model GT-I9108(China Mobile), GT-I9100G, SCH-I929====\nThe Samsung Galaxy S II (Model GT-I9108) was released in late 2011, and it is sold in China by China Mobile. It is identical to the GT-I9100G, featuring the same Texas Instruments OMAP4430 SoC with a 1.2&nbsp;GHz dual-core ARM Cortex A9 processor and PowerVR SGX 540 graphics processor. However, the GT-I9108 has TD-SCDMA support in place of WCDMA support found in other variants. The GT-I9108 is a regional model and has few available custom ROMs.\n\nThe Samsung Galaxy S II (Model SCH-I929) was released in late 2011, and it is sold in China by China Telecom. It is based on the design of Galaxy S II LTE (GT-I9210), but supports CDMA2000 1x EVDO for use with the carrier.\n\n===Europe - Model GT-I9100P===\nThe Samsung Galaxy S II (Model GT-I9100P) was released in late 2011. It has the same hardware as GT-I9100 plus the NFC chip and battery (the battery is specific because it includes the antenna). To keep NFC enabled it is necessary to update the firmware using a P version. Any I9100 firmware can be used, but doing so will disable the NFC hardware.\n\n===India===\n\n====Model: GT-i9100====\n\nGT-i9100 is a sim-free model released on May 2, 2011. This supports 2G/3G only.\n\n===Japan===\n\n====KDDI AU - Model: ISW11SC====\nThe [[KDDI]] [[Au (mobile phone company)|Au]] Galaxy S II WiMAX (Model: ISW11SC) was first released on January 20, 2012 in the color Noble Black and was followed by a Ceramics White model on March 24, 2012 and a Shiny Magenta model on July 20, 2012. The ISW11SC currently runs Android 4.0.4 via an OTA update from the original 2.3.6 firmware. The ISW11SC uses the Samsung Exynos 4210 dual-core 1.4&nbsp;GHz main CPU and a Qualcomm QSC6085 Modem chipset running at 192&nbsp;MHz. It features 1 GB of RAM and 16 GB of ROM (11&nbsp;GB available for user data storage) with support for up to 64&nbsp;GB additional storage via the internal microSD slot. An 1850mAh battery powers the device. The ISW11SC features a Samsung SUPER AMOLED HD 1280x720 screen measuring 4.7 inches. Connectivity includes CDMA 800&nbsp;MHz/2,100&nbsp;MHz; 3G EV-DO Rev A; 2.4&nbsp;GHz / 5&nbsp;GHz 802.11 a/b/g/n Wi-Fi; Bluetooth 3.0 and an integrated WiMAX modem with speeds up to 40Mbit/s down and 15.4Mbit/s up. Like most Japanese domestic model phones the ISW11SC includes many Japan-specific applications. This phone features NFC functionality which is technically compatible with FeliCa RFID (such as with PASMO and SUICA payment systems) however, the software doesn't support the Japanese \"Osaifu Keitai\" mobile wallet and thus the phone cannot be used to make transactions with NFC in Japan.\n\n====NTT DoCoMo - Model SC-02C====\n[[NTT DoCoMo]] introduced a variant of the Galaxy S II (Model [[:ja:SC-02C|SC-02C]]) on 23 June 2011 as the successor to the DoCoMo Galaxy S (Model [[:ja:SC-02B|SC-02B]]). The SC-02C includes [[1seg]] terrestrial television support, as well as [[i-mode]] software functions specific to DoCoMo handsets, such as i-channel, BeeTV, MelodyCall and DoCoMo map navigation. The SC-02C is powered by the Samsung Exynos 4210 Orion Dual-core 1.2&nbsp;GHz (S5PC210) processor.  The SC-02C uses the [[Wnn]] Japanese [[input method editor|input system]].\n\n===South Korea===\nAll of variants optimized for use with South Korean wireless carriers have Samsung's Korean input system for feature phones, a [[Dubeolsik]]-layout virtual keyboard and a [[T-DMB]] tuner in place of an [[FM broadcasting|FM radio]] tuner.\n\n====KT - Model SHW-M250K====\nThe [[KT (telecommunication company)|KT]] variant, the Galaxy S II KT (Model SHW-M250K) uses KT's Wi-Fi CM{{Clarify|date=November 2011}} instead of Android's Wi-Fi CM to connect to Wi-Fi networks. Additional features for KT users are installed by default.\n\n====LG U+ - Model SHW-M250L====\nInstead of WCDMA and HSPA, [[LG U+]]'s variant of the Galaxy S II (Model SHW-M250L) uses EV-DO Rev.B (KPCS 1.8&nbsp;GHz) to accommodate the network technology deployed by LG U+. The SHW-M250L is slightly thicker (9.4&nbsp;mm) than SK Telecom and KT variants (8.89&nbsp;mm). Additional features for LG U+ users are installed by default.\n\n====SK Telecom - Model SHW-M250S====\nThe [[SK Telecom]] variant of the Galaxy S II (Model SHW-M250S) uses the SK-MMS system instead of the OMA-MMS system for multimedia messaging. Additional features for SK Telecom users are installed by default.\n\n===United States===\n\n====AT&T - Models SGH-I777, SGH-I727 and SGH-I927====\n[[AT&T Mobility]] began offering its first variant of the Galaxy S II (Model SGH-I777) on 2 October 2011. Prior to its release, AT&T Mobility's first variant of the device was code named \"Attain\" by Samsung.\n\nThe AT&T Mobility variant maintains the 4.3&nbsp;inch display of the international version, but features four capacitive buttons.<ref name=\"sgs2 at&t samsung official\"/> It also includes [[Near Field Communication|NFC]] capability.<ref name=\"sgs2 US NFC\"/>\n\nAT&T Mobility introduced a second variant of the device called the Galaxy S II Skyrocket (Model SGH-I727) on 6 November 2011. Prior to its release, this second variant was code named \"Skyrocket\" by Samsung. This variant is similar to the international Samsung Galaxy S II LTE and is notable for its inclusion of an LTE radio. The inclusion of the LTE radio required changing the device's main processor from the Exynos to the Qualcomm Snapdragon MSM8660 because the Exynos does not support LTE.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.engadget.com/2012/01/09/samsung-galaxy-s-ii-skyrocket-hd-coming-to-atandt-1-5ghz-dual-cor/ |title=Samsung Galaxy S II Skyrocket HD coming to AT&T: 1.5GHz dual-core CPU, LTE, 'razor-thin' |author=Amar Toor |date=Jan 9, 2012 |publisher=Engadget |accessdate=May 15, 2012}}</ref> This version features the same 4.52&nbsp;inch screen of the Sprint model. This variant supports Near Field Communications (NFC).\n\nAT&T Mobility introduced a third variant called the Captivate Glide (Model SGH-I927) on 20 November 2011. The Captivate Glide differs from the other two AT&T Mobility variants primarily by the inclusion of a slide-out, physical QWERTY keyboard.<ref>[http://www.samsung.com/us/mobile/cell-phones/SGH-I927ZKAATT Coming Soon! Samsung Captivate Glide | Samsung Mobile] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111118084418/http://www.samsung.com/us/mobile/cell-phones/SGH-I927ZKAATT |date=18 November 2011 }}. Samsung.com. Retrieved on 2013-07-10.</ref> The Captivate Glide also includes a dual-core, 1&nbsp;GHz Tegra 2 dual-core processor instead of a 1.2&nbsp;GHz Exynos processor. The display of this third variant is Super AMOLED instead of Super AMOLED Plus and the display size is reduced to 4&nbsp;inches.\n\n====Sprint - Model SPH-D710====\n[[File:Samsung Galaxy S2 Epic 4G Touch.jpg|thumb|Sprint's Samsung Galaxy S II Epic 4G Touch (Model SPH-D710)]]\nThe [[Sprint Corporation|Sprint]] variant (Model SPH-D710) of the Galaxy S II was initially released as the Galaxy S II Epic 4G Touch and was later renamed to the simpler Galaxy S II 4G. Prior to its release, Sprint's variant was codenamed \"Within\" by Samsung. The SPH-D710 first became available for Sprint customers on 16 September 2011, making Sprint the first carrier in the United States to offer a variant of the S II.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://newsroom.sprint.com/news/sprint-first-us-carrier-to-debut-galaxy-s-ii-with-samsung-epic-4g-touch.htm |title=Sprint First U.S. Carrier to Debut Galaxy S II With Samsung Epic 4G Touch |work=Sprint Newsroom |date=30 August 2011 |accessdate=1 September 2011}}</ref> The SPH-D710 is available to Sprint customers in black, titanium grey or white.\n\nThe Sprint variant has key differences from the \"International\" version of the Galaxy S II. The Sprint variant includes a 2500&nbsp;MHz WiMax radio. The display of the Sprint variant, at 4.52&nbsp;inches, is larger than that of the international version.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://newsroom.sprint.com/news/samsung-galaxy-s-ii-epic-4g-touch-fact-sheet.htm |title=Samsung Galaxy S\u2122 II, Epic\u2122 4G Touch fact sheet \u2013 Delivering rich content at blazing fast speeds |work=Sprint Newsroom |date=30 August 2011 |accessdate=1 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110907183622/http://newsroom.sprint.com/news/samsung-galaxy-s-ii-epic-4g-touch-fact-sheet.htm |archivedate=7 September 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The Sprint variant features four touch-capacitive buttons as opposed to the three-button hardware/capacitive combination found on the international version. Other differences include an LED notification light and a larger, 6.66&nbsp;[[Watt-hour|Wh]] battery.\n\nThe Sprint variant does not come equipped with NFC capability, unlike the variants offered by [[T-Mobile US]] and [[AT&T Mobility]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pocketnow.com/android/sprint-epic-4g-touch-lacking-nfc-unlike-att-and-t-mobile-models |title=Sprint Epic 4G Touch Lacking NFC Unlike AT&T and T-Mobile Models |work=Pocketnow |date=3 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe Galaxy S II 4G is a touchscreen-only device, unlike the [[Sgh-i897|Epic 4G]], which includes a physical [[QWERTY]] keyboard.\n\nOn 28 March 2013, the Android 4.1.2 Jelly Bean (GB27) update was released through the [[Samsung Kies]] software As of February 2014, there are no additional confirmed updates for this device.\n\nThe device has received 7 updates from Samsung since its original release on 16 September 2011.\n\nSprint has announced that on 6 November 2015 the Sprint [[WiMAX]] network will be decommissioned effectively removing 4G capabilities on the SPH-D710 model. Users will still have access to data service using the 3G network.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fiercewireless.com/story/sprint-shutter-wimax-network-around-nov-6-2015/2014-10-07 |title=Sprint to shutter WiMAX network around Nov. 6, 2015 |work=Pocketnow |date=7 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n=====Boost Mobile and Virgin Mobile USA=====\nSprint subsidiaries Boost Mobile offers a Sprint SPH-D710 variant of the Galaxy S II 4G in both titanium grey or white options. Virgin Mobile offers a variant, model i9210, for their service.\n\n[[Boost Mobile]] began the Samsung Galaxy S II 4G on 6 September 2012 for $369.99. [[Virgin Mobile USA]] began offering the Galaxy S II 4G on 15 November 2012 for $369.99.\n\nIn March 2013, the Boost Mobile and Virgin Mobile variants were also updated along with Sprint's to Android 4.1.2 Jelly Bean.\n\n====T-Mobile - Model SGH-T989====\n[[T-Mobile USA]] began taking pre-orders for its variant (Model SGH-T989) of the Galaxy S II on 11 October 2011 and began selling it in stores on 12 October 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/technology/2011/09/t-mobiles-new-4g-phones-htc-amaze-and-samsung-galaxy-s-ii.html |title=HTC Amaze, Samsung Galaxy S II: T-Mobile's fastest 4G phones yet |date=26 September 2011 |work=LA Times}}</ref> Prior to its release, T-Mobile's variant of the device was code named \"Hercules\" by Samsung.\n\nThe T-Mobile variant has important key differences from the \"International\" version of the Galaxy S II. The T-Mobile variant uses a 1.5&nbsp;GHz dual-core [[Qualcomm]] APQ8060 (S3) [[Snapdragon (system on chip)|Snapdragon]] processor, as opposed to the 1.2&nbsp;GHz dual-core Exynos processor of the International version because the Exynos processor is not compatible with T-Mobile's 42 Mbit/s HSPA+ network. The cellular radio of the T-Mobile supports UMTS bands I (2100&nbsp;MHz), II (1900&nbsp;MHz), IV (1700&nbsp;MHz) and V (850&nbsp;MHz). The display of the T-Mobile variant, at 4.52&nbsp;inches, is larger than that of the international version. The T-Mobile variant features four touch-capacitive buttons as opposed to the three-button hardware/capacitive combination found on the international version, this variant of the smartphone uses the powerful Adreno-220 series GPU and supports up to version 4.4.4\u2013based ROMs of the Android OS<ref name=\"sgs2 t-mobile\">{{cite web |url=http://newsroom.t-mobile.com/articles/T-Mobile-confirms-Samsung-Galaxy-S-II |title=Samsung Galaxy S II Coming Soon to T-Mobile |work=T-Mobile |date=30 August 2011 |accessdate=1 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930151453/http://newsroom.t-mobile.com/articles/T-Mobile-confirms-Samsung-Galaxy-S-II |archivedate=30 September 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The T-Mobile variant, like the AT&T variant, supports Near Field Communications (NFC) integrated in the battery, which has 6.85Wh capacity.<ref name=\"sgs2 US NFC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.engadget.com/2011/08/31/samsung-galaxy-s-ii-logs-confirm-nfc-support-for-atandt-none-for/ |title=Samsung Galaxy S II logs confirm NFC support for AT&T, none for Sprint |date=31 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nAs of March 8, 2013, the T-Mobile variant can be updated to Android 4.1.2 [[Android version history#Android 4.1.x Jelly Bean|\"Jelly Bean\"]] using Samsung Kies.<ref name=\"t-mobile sgs2 jelly bean\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sammobile.com/2013/04/08/update-your-galaxy-s-ii-t-mobile-usa-to-android-4-1-2/ |title=Update your Galaxy S II T-Mobile USA to Android 4.1.2+ |date=8 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n====U.S. Cellular - Model SCH-R760====\n[[U.S. Cellular]]'s variant (Model SCH-R760) is equivalent to the Sprint variant, except for one specification; the U.S. Cellular variant does not include a 2500&nbsp;MHz WiMax radio.\n\n==Galaxy S II Plus - Model GT-I9105/P==\nThe Galaxy S II Plus was announced in [[Consumer Electronics Show#2013|CES 2013]]. The phone has a [[Broadcom]] BC28155 [[System on chip|SoC]] with a 1.2&nbsp;GHz dual-core processor and a [[VideoCore]] IV HW GPU instead of the Mali 400MP in the original Galaxy S II. It has 1 GB of RAM but only with 8 GB of internal storage. It uses a hyperglazed plastic body (the same as the Samsung Galaxy S III) and is available in Chic White and Dark Blue. The phone originally ran on Android 4.1.2 [[Android version history#Android 4.1.x Jelly Bean|\"Jelly Bean\"]] with Samsung's [[TouchWiz]] Nature UX.<ref name=\"plusgsmarena\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gsmarena.com/jelly_beanrunning_samsung_galaxy_s_ii_plus_announced-news-5326.php|title=GSMArena.com Jelly-Bean running Galaxy S II Plus announced}}</ref> An update to Android 4.2.2 is available in some countries. Also released was a I9105P model, which supports [[Near field communication|NFC]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Samsung I9105 Galaxy S II Plus - Full phone specifications|url=http://www.gsmarena.com/samsung_i9105_galaxy_s_ii_plus-5213.php|publisher=GSMarena.com|accessdate=17 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nReviews of the Galaxy S II have been universally positive. It was honored by MWC's Global Mobile Awards as [http://www.globalmobileawards.com/awards-2013/winners-2012/ \"SmartPhone Of The Year 2012\"] ''Engadget'' gave the device a 9/10, calling it \"the best Android smartphone yet\" and \"possibly the best smartphone, period.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Savov |first=Vlad |title=Samsung Galaxy S II review |url=https://www.engadget.com/2011/04/28/samsung-galaxy-s-ii-review/|work=Engadget |date=28 April 2011}}</ref> ''CNET'' UK gave the device a favorable review of 4.5/5 and described it as \"one of the slimmest, lightest mobiles we've ever had the privilege to hold.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://reviews.cnet.co.uk/mobile-phones/samsung-galaxy-s-2-review-50002442 |title=Samsung Galaxy S 2 review |date=6 May 2011 |accessdate=14 May 2011 |first=Luke |last=Westaway |work=CNET UK |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110507232209/http://reviews.cnet.co.uk/mobile-phones/samsung-galaxy-s-2-review-50002442/ |archivedate=7 May 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> ''TechRadar'' gave the device 5/5 stars and describes the device as one that \"set a new bar for smartphones in 2011.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.techradar.com/reviews/phones/mobile-phones/samsung-galaxy-s2-930907/review?artc_pg=1 |title=Samsung Galaxy S2 Review |work=TechRadar |first=Gareth |last=Beavis |date=26 April 2011 |accessdate=14 May 2011}}</ref> ''Pocketnow'' was \"impressed\" with the speed of the web browser.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pocketnow.com/android/galaxy-s-ii-web-browser-speed-test-video |title=Galaxy S II Web Browser Speed Test (Video) |date=11 May 2011 |work=Pocketnow.com}}</ref> ''SlashGear'' states that the device \"sets the benchmark for smartphones in general.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.slashgear.com/samsung-galaxy-s-ii-review-26148446/ |title=Samsung Galaxy S II Review |date=26 April 2011 |accessdate=14 May 2011 |first=Chris |last=Davies |work=SlashGear}}</ref> ''GSMArena'' points out minor drawbacks such as an \"all-plastic body\" and the handset having \"no dedicated camera key,\" but still calls the handset \"absurdly powerful\" and concluding \"we just cannot see beyond the new Samsung flagship if we're to name the ultimate smartphone.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gsmarena.com/samsung_i9100_galaxy_s_ii-review-597p12.php |title=Samsung i9100 Galaxy S II review: Brightest star \u2013 Final words |work=GSMArena |date=13 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nAfter slightly over one month since its debut, more than 1 million units of Samsung Galaxy S II were activated in South Korea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.antaranews.com/en/news/72648/galaxy-s2-sales-to-consumers-top-1-mln-in-s-korea |title=Galaxy S2 sales to consumers top 1 mln in S. Korea |date=13 June 2011 |work=Antara News}}</ref> Worldwide, 3 million units were sold in 55 days.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/samsungtomorrow/5895933600/ |title=Galaxy S 2 Set a Record of 3 Million Global Sales in 55 Days |date=30 June 2011 |work=SamsungTomorrow Flickr}}</ref> 85 days after its first release, Samsung declared global shipments of over 5 million for the Galaxy S II<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mobot.net/samsung-galaxy-s2-sales-figures-world-27840 |title=Samsung Galaxy S2: Sales figures out of this world |date=8 August 2011 |work=Mobot.net}}</ref> and 10 million after 5 months.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2011/09/25/samsung-moves-10-million-galaxy-s-iis-pats-itself-on-the-back/ |title=Samsung moves ten million Galaxy S II smartphones, pats itself on the back |date=25 September 2011 |work=Engadget}}</ref> Partially owing to strong sales of Samsung's Galaxy range of smartphones, Samsung overtook [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] in smartphone sales during Q3 2011, with a total market share of 23.8%, compared to Apple's 14.6%.<ref>28 October 2011, [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-15489523 Samsung overtakes Apple in smartphone sales], BBC News</ref>\n\n==Successor==\n{{main|Samsung Galaxy S III}}\nThe successor to the Galaxy S II was the [[Samsung Galaxy S III|Galaxy S III]], unveiled in London on 3 May 2012 and commencing sales on 29 May 2012 with 10 million reported pre-orders.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/samsung/9244619/Samsung-unveil-new-Galaxy-S3-smartphone-at-London-launch.html |title=Samsung Galaxy S3 to launch in early 2012, 4G tablet coming sooner |publisher=CNET UK |date=1 June 2011 |first=Andy |last=Merrett |work=crave cnet 2012 |accessdate=4 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://crave.cnet.co.uk/mobiles/samsung-galaxy-s3-complete-guide-50006020/ | title=Samsung Galaxy S3 complete guide | publisher=CNET | date=25 January 2012 | accessdate=28 February 2012 | author=Andrew Hoyle}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thehindu.com/sci-tech/gadgets/article3383875.ece|title=Samsung S III launch |accessdate=2012-05-16}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Comparison of Samsung Galaxy S smartphones]]\n* [[Comparison of smartphones]]\n* [[Samsung Galaxy S series]]\n* [https://forum.xda-developers.com/galaxy-s2/help/guide-tutorial-samsung-galaxy-s2-i9100-t3538601 Update Galaxy S2 to the latest Android version]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Samsung Galaxy S II}}\n* {{official website|http://www.samsung.com/global/microsite/galaxys2/html/}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{Succession box\n | title  = Samsung Galaxy S II\n | years  = 2011\n | before = [[Samsung Galaxy S]]\n | after = [[Galaxy S III]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Samsung smartphone}}\n{{Samsung phones}}\n{{Android smartphones}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Samsung Galaxy S II}}\n[[Category:Android (operating system) devices]]\n[[Category:Smartphones]]\n[[Category:Samsung mobile phones|Galaxy S II]]\n[[Category:Samsung Galaxy|Galaxy S II]]\n[[Category:Mobile phones introduced in 2011]]\n", "name_user": "Djibe89", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samsung_Galaxy_S_II"}
{"title_page": "Siberian State Technological University", "text_new": "{{Infobox University\n|name = Siberian State Technological University\n|native_name = \u0421\u0438\u0431\u0438\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0442\u0435\u0445\u043d\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0443\u043d\u0438\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0438\u0442\u0435\u0442\n|image = \n|established = 1930\n|motto = \n|rector = \n|students = 15,000\n|faculty = 1,051 lecturers and teachers\n|city = [[Krasnoyarsk]]\n|country = [[Russia]]\n|website = http://www.sibstu.kts.ru\n{{Infobox building\n| embed = yes\n| name               = \n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| image              = Siberian State Technological University, Krasnoyarsk, pic 2.jpg\n| image_size         = 250px\n| caption            = \n| start_date         = \n| completion_date    = \n| location           =\n| coordinates        =             \n| map_type           = \n| architectural      = \n| status             = \n| antenna_spire      = \n| top_floor          = \n| floor_count        = \n| elevator_count     = \n| floor_area         = \n| developer          = \n| owner              = \n}}\n}}\n\n'''Siberian State Technological University''' is the oldest university in [[Krasnoyarsk]], [[Russia]]. It was established in 1930 as the Siberian Institute of Forest (\u0421\u0438\u0431\u0438\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043b\u0435\u0441\u043e\u0442\u0435\u0445\u043d\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0438\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0442). Later it was known as the Siberian Technical Institute of Forest (\u0421\u0438\u0431\u0438\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043b\u0435\u0441\u043e\u0442\u0435\u0445\u043d\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0438\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0442) (renamed 1933), Siberian Technological Institute (\u0421\u0438\u0431\u0438\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0442\u0435\u0445\u043d\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0438\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0442) (renamed 1958), Krasnoyarsk State Technological Academy (\u041a\u0440\u0430\u0441\u043d\u043e\u044f\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0442\u0435\u0445\u043d\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0430\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043c\u0438\u044f) (renamed 1994) and finally the Siberian State Technological University (renamed 1997).\n\nCurrently 15,000 students are studying in one of the nine faculties.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of forestry universities and colleges]]\n\n{{coord|56.0126|92.8689|type:edu_region:RU|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Universities in Krasnoyarsk Krai]]\n[[Category:Universities and institutes established in the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1930]]\n\n\n{{Russia-university-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox University\n|name = Siberian State Technological University\n|native_name = \u0421\u0438\u0431\u0438\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0442\u0435\u0445\u043d\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0443\u043d\u0438\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0438\u0442\u0435\u0442\n|image = \n|established = 1930\n|motto = \n|rector = \n|students = 15,000\n|faculty = 1,051 lecturers and teachers\n|city = [[Krasnoyarsk]]\n|country = [[Russia]]\n|website = http://www.sibstu.kts.ru\n}}\n\n'''Siberian State Technological University''' is the oldest university in [[Krasnoyarsk]], [[Russia]]. It was established in 1930 as the Siberian Institute of Forest (\u0421\u0438\u0431\u0438\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043b\u0435\u0441\u043e\u0442\u0435\u0445\u043d\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0438\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0442). Later it was known as the Siberian Technical Institute of Forest (\u0421\u0438\u0431\u0438\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043b\u0435\u0441\u043e\u0442\u0435\u0445\u043d\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0438\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0442) (renamed 1933), Siberian Technological Institute (\u0421\u0438\u0431\u0438\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0442\u0435\u0445\u043d\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0438\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0442) (renamed 1958), Krasnoyarsk State Technological Academy (\u041a\u0440\u0430\u0441\u043d\u043e\u044f\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0442\u0435\u0445\u043d\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0430\u043a\u0430\u0434\u0435\u043c\u0438\u044f) (renamed 1994) and finally the Siberian State Technological University (renamed 1997).\n\nCurrently 15,000 students are studying in one of the nine faculties.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of forestry universities and colleges]]\n\n{{coord|56.0126|92.8689|type:edu_region:RU|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Universities in Krasnoyarsk Krai]]\n[[Category:Universities and institutes established in the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1930]]\n\n\n{{Russia-university-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rakoon", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Siberian_State_Technological_University"}
